<FIRST>r a AM-MandelAppeal     03-02 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandel Appeal,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Lets Stand Order Vacating Mandel Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM PAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Wednesday upheld a
lower court ruling that vacated the 1977 convictions of former
Maryland Gov. Marvin Mandel and five others in a political
corruption case.
   The tie vote by the full 4th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Richmond, Va., could be the final stop for a political scandal that
turned into a prolonged legal battle for the ex-governor as he
sought vindication from charges that he misused his powers to help
his associates' horse racing business.
   However, U.S. Attorney for Maryland Breckinridge Willcox said he
would ask the Justice Department to authorize an appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   ``It encourages me to think that there's enough uncertainty over
this very issue that it needs Supreme Court review,'' Willcox said.
   The appeals court voted 5-5 on a prosecution request to re-hear
an appeal that had been denied by a three-judge panel of the court
in December, Willcox said. A tie vote means rejection of the request.
   ``We are gratified that after more than a decade, the Mandel case
now appears to be over,'' Mandel's Baltimore attorney, Arnold
Weiner, said in a statement.
   In 1975, while he was still governor, Mandel was charged with
helping five men obtain extra racing days for Marlboro Race Track.
He also was accused of accepting $350,000 in gifts and financial
help in a divorce settlement.
   Indicted on the mail fraud charges halfway through his second
four-year term, Mandel remained in office until the day he was
sentenced.
   He won a reversal on appeal, allowing him to regain the
governor's office for the last days of his term, which expired in
1979. But another appeals court reinstated the conviction, forcing
Mandel to serve 14 months at a federal prison camp.
   In November 1987, U.S. District Judge Frederic Smalkin set aside
the mail fraud convictions on grounds that Mandel's trial jury was
improperly allowed to consider a theory of mail fraud law that has
since been overturned by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The Supreme Court ruled in June 1987 that the federal mail fraud
statutes cannot be used to prosecute public officials for defrauding
citizens of their ``intangible rights'' to honest government.
   In December, three judges of the appeals court agreed with
Smalkin.
</TEXT>
