<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Guatemala-Peace     03-02 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guatemala-Peace,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Reconciliation Panel Meets _ Without Rebels, Army or Opposition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guatemala's National Reconciliaton
Commission has begun meeting _ but without the rebels, the army or
the exiled political opposition it was designed to bring together to
end decades of civil war.
   The commission, which met Wednesday, was created under an
18-month-old Central American peace plan designed to end
insurgencies in El Salvador, Nicaragua and Guatemala.
   Guatemalan rightists fiercely oppose talks with leftist
guerrillas. An abortive coup last year followed a meeting between
President Vinicio Cerezo and rebel representatives, the last meeting
he has held with them.
   The commission includes representatives of labor unions, the
media, educators, clergymen and most of the country's political
parties.
   The government is represented on the commission by Vice President
Roberto Carpio and 15 elected local delegates.
   But the panel does not include representatives of the rebels, the
military, the private sector and the exiled political opposition.
The group has no set meeting schedule and is expected to meet on and
off during the next few months, commission members said.
   The Christian Democratic government has so far refused to say if
it will try to implement any accord the commission might reach.
</TEXT>
