<DOCNO> AP890302-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Labor     03-02 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Labor,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>2.5 Million Job-Seekers Flock To Canton Area In One Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTON, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liu Guangyong squatted next to her
possessions outside the main Canton railway station, one of the 2.5
million peasants who have descended on this prosperous region in
search of good jobs at good wages.
   She and a group of 16 people from her village in central Sichuan
province arrived Monday in this capital of Guangdong province after
riding the rails for three days and three nights. By the following
day, however, it was clear they could not get the garment factory
jobs they thought were available.
   ``We got no jobs. So we just slept on the road outside the
factory,'' Liu, a mother of two, said as she guarded a meager pile
of clothing and toiletries.
   Her group was among legions of disappointed job seekers who
returned to the train station Tuesday to try to obtain tickets to go
back to their villages.
   ``Why don't they add more trains to take us home?'' the woman
asked.
   Peasants from the interior of China have long flocked to coastal
Guangdong province to work the textile, toy and other factories set
up largely with capital from the neighboring British colony of Hong
Kong, 90 miles to the southeast of Canton.
   China's official Statistics Bureau said the average annual wage
in Guangdong last year was $586 per worker, or about double the
national average.
   But the crush in February, in which an army of itinerant workers
roughly equal to the population of the city of Atlanta descended on
the province, clearly surprised authorities, who said Guangdong did
not have work for so many people.
   Guangdong officials claimed the onslaught, estimated by official
media at 2.5 million people, occurred when migrant laborers who
briefly returned home for the Chinese Lunar New Year that began Feb.
6 and convinced fellow villagers they could strike it rich in the
province.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said public security, transport
and hygiene in Guangdong were strained by the influx. Crime was up,
and begging was expected to rise, it said.
   The Guangdong government ordered factories not to hire new
employees from other provinces, issued an urgent appeal to the rest
of China to prevent people from coming, and threatened to kick out
the itinerants who did not leave on their own. As of Tuesday, 20,000
people reportedly were leaving the province daily, and Guangdong
officials said the situation was improving.
   Ma Shenwu, a 38-year-old peasant who arrived with five friends
from Hunan, a province on Guangdong's eastern border, was back at
the Canton station Tuesday after failing to find a job in four towns.
   ``We have to borrow money to go home,'' he said.
   Liu Qian, 18, also was at the station trying to return to her
village in neighboring Hunan province after she failed to get a job
at an electronics factory in Shenzhen, a special economic zone next
to Hong Kong.
   She said the factory boss refused to employ her and five friends
she had brought from home because they did not have the proper
permits.
   ``When I was in Hunan, the government office was off for the
festival so I could not renew my permit,'' she said.
   Rural peasants were not the only ones who rushed to Guangdong.
Sitting next to a group of peasants at the railway station were
several fashionably clothed women from Shanghai wearing makeup and
earrings.
   ``We were deceived. They told us we could earn 700 yuan ($188) a
month in Shenzhen, but we found it was less than 300 ($81), and 16
hours work a day. We were cheated,'' one of them said.
   ``We worked for two weeks and decided to leave,'' another added.
   Unlike the job-seekers from the countryside, the Shanghai women
kept smiling as they told their story because they had jobs waiting
for them in a clothing factory back home.
   ``When we left (Shanghai), our boss asked us not to leave and
said he would welcome us back. We can even charge this trip to him.
So we see this trip as a holiday,'' the first girl said.
   China's migrant labor force, estimated at 20 million, is a
byproduct of the nation's easing of travel restrictions and of
market-oriented reforms which have encouraged labor mobility.
   The influx of peasants to the cities has helped solve problems of
surplus labor in the farming areas and provided workers for
factories and the booming construction industry.
   Last fall, the government announced a cutback on investment
credit and a halt to thousands of construction projects to reduce
inflation and cool the overheated economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
