<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-02 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workshop topics include ``The Future of Food'' and
``Can Recipes Travel Through Time.''
   But before you get indigestion over the idea that the 11th annual
gathering of the International Association of Cooking Professionals
was a bit ethereal, they concentrated on what is yummy to the tummy,
too.
   Albert Kumin's ``Luxuriate in Chocolate'' was the most popular
workshop, according to convention spokeswoman Valerie Bergman.
Kumin, a renowned pastry chef and confectioner, designed menus for
the White House.
   To be sure, the convention could get a little technical. For
example, a workshop in ``High-Tech Tips for Fail-Safe Recipes'' was
clearly not for the kind of cook who relies on Hamburger Helper.
   But it wasn't all hard work.
   Participants sampled some of the goodies and will be allowed to
kick up their heels during ``Wine Tasting _ A Personal Sensory
Analysis,'' ``Ways With Walnuts,'' or the ``Fisherman's Feast,''
billed as the ``finale'' that includes a ``bounty of fish from the
North Atlantic.''
   ``I think the most exciting thing is that people who like to eat
are people who like life,'' said Janeen Sarlin, a cooking teacher
who is one of nearly 400 participants in the convention that ends
Saturday. ``If I learn just one thing, some new way of doing
something this week, it'll be worth it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BROWN DEER, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sherry Wall wants to become the Jane
Fonda of the canine set.
   Wall said she has received about 20 calls from prospective
customers since she started speaking on the radio and distributing
fliers last month, promoting her aerobic exercise course for dogs.
   ``Dogs are very social animals, and many of them are alone eight,
10, 12 hours a day,'' she said. ``They turn into real couch
potatoes.''
   Wall, a veterinary technician and dog groomer, plans to begin
teaching exercise classes for dogs and their owners at a shopping
center in this Milwuakee suburb in late March.
   The exercises, she said, are takeoffs on common calisthenics for
humans and should be easily mastered by any dog that has had basic
obedience training.
   ``A sit-up goes from a sit-down position to a jump,'' she said.
``And a push-up is sit to lie-down.''
   Her two Dobermans, Dobie and Dylan, do those exercises and
others, she said, adding that they also willingly offer their front
paws for some aerobic dance steps.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who sent a Christmas card to a
relative in South China, Maine, but forgot to put Maine or the zip
code on the envelope has had the card returned to her _ from China.
   Lorette Bellevance of Augusta says the envelope, bearing the
Beijing post mark, was returned to her because it contained
``insufficient address.''
   She had sent the card to Joanne Pauley on Dec. 5. When postal
authorities in China's capital could not find a Joanne Pauley in
their city, the card was returned to Mrs. Bellevance.
   Julie Jackson, the postmaster in South China, said the confusion
with mainland China occurs about once every two years.
</TEXT>
