<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FlagArt     03-02 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art School Reopens Controversial Exhibit to Students, Staff Only</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial exhibit using an American flag
spread on the floor at the School of the Art Institute will go back
on display, but not for public viewing, officials said Wednesday.
   The display will be only for students, faculty and staff of the
museum school, but the move drew immediate protest from veterans'
groups, which filed a lawsuit late Wednesday to remove the flag.
   ``What we're objecting to, of course ... is that it is the
American flag and the flag is being disgraced, walked on,'' said
John Mahoney of the American Legion.
   ``This is totally unacceptable to the veterans groups,'' said
Joseph A. Morris, general counsel for the Mid-America Legal
Foundation, which represents the Veterans of Foreign Wars, Disabled
American Veterans and the Military Order of the Purple Heart, among
others.
   The work by student Scott Tyler, titled ``What Is the Proper Way
to Display A U.S. Flag?'' last week sparked demonstrations by angry
veterans and threats of violence, countered by student concerns
about freedom of expression.
   School officials canceled weekend classes and closed the gallery
where Tyler's work is displayed. After meetings with students,
faculty and veterans representatives, officials said the gallery
would reopen Thursday for in-house viewing only, and under
additional security.
   ``The school will continue to ensure that the First Amendment
rights and the safety of its students are protected,''
   ``To fulfill its responsibility to viewers, the school will post
a sign advising persons of the intent of the police and prosecutor's
offices should a viewer choose to step on the flag,'' officials said
in a written statement.
   Police have determined it is legal to display the work, but says
trampling or otherwise desecrating the flag is a felony, the school
has said previously.
   In the work, a flag is spread on the floor in front of a
photomontage of flag-draped coffins, South Koreans burning the U.S.
flag and other scenes. Visitors are invited to comment in a ledger
on a shelf in front of the exhibit.
   The veterans complain that in doing so, most will step on the
flag.
   ``It is NOT necessary for the viewer to walk on the flag to write
in the book,'' said the school's statement Wednesday. ``There is
sufficient room to stand on either side of the flag for those
viewers who choose to write comments in the book.''
   It's the second time in a year that an exhibit at the school has
stirred controversy. Black aldermen stormed its halls last year to
take down a portrait of the late Harold Washington, the city's first
black mayor, who was depicted by a student wearing frilly women's
underwear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Power     03-02 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Power,0874</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Whittles Christian Rival Down, Opens Door To Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army commander Gen. Michel Aoun is
whittling down the power of his main rival in a fight for control of
Lebanon's Christian enclave and has opened the door a crack for a
settlement with Moslems to end 14 years of civil war.
   Aoun heads the country's Christian government, which is vying for
legitimacy with a rival Moslem Cabinet.
   Last month, he scored a military victory over Samir Geagea,
leader of the right-wing Lebanese Forces militia, in the fiercest
street battles between Christian factions in four years.
   But Aoun has not completely crushed the messianic Geagea, a
Maronite Catholic like himself, and Christian political leaders
expect more bloodshed before the power struggle is finally resolved.
   ``You can't have two roosters in one yard,'' one former Christian
Cabinet minister warned. ``There may have to be more fighting.''
   Although Geagea's forces remain largely intact, Aoun has forced
him out of his strongholds in east Beirut, opening up the
possibility of reuniting the divided capital for the first time
since the civil war erupted in April 1975.
   The stumpy 53-year-old general has driven the Lebanese Forces,
the Christians' main militia, out of the so-called 5th Basin in
Beirut port.
   That robbed the militia of one of its main sources of revenue and
allowed the port to be reopened after a five-year closure, enhancing
hopes of reuniting the battle-scarred capital.
   The port straddles the city's Green Line, which divides Christian
east Beirut from Moslem west Beirut.
   By taking over control of the mid-city Museum Crossing, one of
the main Green Line gateways, and other customs posts on the borders
of the Christian sector controlled by the dominant Maronite sect,
Aoun has stripped Geagea of an estimated $400,000 a day in revenue.
   He also has ordered that no taxes be paid to the Lebanese Forces
in areas under army control, cutting Geagea's income by another 30
percent.
   Aoun's military success has made him the most likely next
candidate to succeed Amin Gemayel as president. Gemayel's term
expired Sept. 22 with no successor elected because the Lebanese
Forces opposed Syrian-backed candidates.
   The Lebanese Forces, however, remain largely intact because Aoun
reined in his troops after only two days of fighting in response to
appeals by Maronite religious leaders.
   Both sides are regrouping and fortifying their positions.
   ``He should have gone all the way,'' said a Moslem government
official who sympathizes with Aoun, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``Geagea's been left with a chance to hit back and he'll
be merciless if he does.''
   An Aoun aide said the cease-fire was ``a risk the general had to
take. He's perfectly aware of the consequences. He knows he'll
either be the next president or dead.''
   Electing Aoun would make possible an accomodation with Syria _
the main power broker in Lebanon _ and its Lebanese Moslem and
leftist allies and avert the threatened formalization of partition
into sectarian cantons.
   Aoun has taken a more moderate stand toward the Syrians since he
attended Arab League talks in Tunis aimed at defusing the political
crisis and has made it clear he is prepared to take Syrian security
interests into account if elected president.
   The Syrians have signalled they're ready to deal with him and
their state-run press has openly supported him.
   Removing the fiercely anti-Syrian, anti-Moslem Geagea has long
been a key demand of Syria and its Lebanese allies, who charge the
militia commander has close ties with Israel.
   Geagea says the 40,000 Syrian troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab
League peacekeeping mandate are an occupation force. He demands
their unconditional withdrawal as a precondition for a
Christian-Moslem settlement based on a loose federal system.
   Aoun wants Geagea out of east Beirut and isolated north of the
city so the capital can be reunited and parliament convened to elect
him president on a reunification platform.
   For their part, the Syrians are understood to be willing to
withdraw their forces from west Beirut to the hills overlooking the
city and turn over security to Moslem units of the Lebanese army
under Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib.
   The Syrian scenario for a Lebanese settlement hinges largely on
eliminating the extremists on both sides of the sectarian divide to
give more moderate elements a chance to work out an agreement.
   Through their main surrogates, the Shiite Moslem Amal militia,
the Syrians have weakened the the Iranian-backed Shiite Hezbollah,
or Party of God, which seeks to create an Islamic republic in
Lebanon.
   However, like Geagea's fighters, Hezbollah has not been totally
crushed.
   No one in Lebanon believes that an end to Lebanon's agony, in
which some 150,000 people have been killed, is just around the
corner, given the deep-rooted divisions. But with Arab pressure
growing for a settlement, there may at last be a light, albeit
flickering and faint, at the end of the tunnel.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Farouk Nassar, Beirut correspondent for The
Associated Press, has covered Lebanon for more than 15 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
