<FIRST>r w PM-SEC-Infotech     03-02 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Infotech,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Partnership Wants To Acquire Infotech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch investment partnership wants to acquire
Infotechnology Inc., the conglomerate that controls United Press
International.
   Avacus Partners LP told the Securities and Exchange Commission it
may seek control of New York-based Infotechnology through a tender
offer or merger.
   Infotechnology stock closed at $9.62{ Wednesday, up 25 cents from
Tuesday and $1.12{ since Monday. According to documents filed with
the SEC on Tuesday, Avacus holds 587,500 share of Infotechnology,
8.03 percent of the company, including 231,500 shares it purchased
between Feb. 16 and Feb. 23 for between $6.90 and $7.25 per share.
   Infotechnology has wide-ranging holdings of technology and
information companies, including two cable television channels,
Financial News Network and The Learning Channel.
   Infotechnology has managed UPI since February 1988, when it took
over the company from Mexican publisher Mario Vasquez Rana, who
relinquished control of his stock for 10 years. Its chairman, Earl
W. Brian, and Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. are the major shareholders.
   Avacus was formed in March 1988 for the sole purpose of acquiring
Infotechnology, according to the documents filed with the SEC. Reiss
&amp; Co., a Dutch investment company, is the majority partner. Johannes
M.K. Nyks, former president and chief executive of the American
subsidiary of the Netherlands newspaper, VNU, also has an interest.
   Nyks, in a letter to Brian dated Feb. 27, said Avacus considers
Infotechnology's stock undervalued and sought a meeting to discuss
``opportunities to increase shareholder value through a mutually
agreeable transaction.''
   Dwight Geduldig, a spokesman for UPI, said Wednesday that Brian
has responded publicly, ``I look forward to meeting with any
shareholder who has suggestions about ways to increase shareholders'
values.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
