<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     03-02 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Budget Writers Cite Movement in Budget Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional budget writers say they are
edging closer to negotiations with the Bush administration, even as
the House Appropriations Committee warns it is unhappy with the
president's 1990 spending plan.
   The Democratic chairmen of the two congressional budget
committees, and the top-ranking Republicans, emerged from a session
with administration budget director Richard Darman to say their
series of informational meetings together seems to be nearing an end.
   House Budget Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., and Rep. Bill
Frenzel of Minnesota, the panel's ranking Republican, said talks
might be held next week between Darman and the four top members of
the budget panels about how negotiations among administration
officials and congressional leaders might proceed.
   ``We might sit down, without staff, and talk about where to go,''
Frenzel said.
   Panetta said the sessions would examine ``whether there are
approaches Congress and the White House could agree to'' on deficit
reduction.
   Panetta said that meanwhile, in a ``two-track approach,'' his
committee probably will begin writing a budget resolution in
mid-March with a goal of finishing its work by April 1.
   Darman and congressional budget writers have already met several
times recently. During these sessions, congressional leaders have
tried to learn more details about Bush's budget plan, which they say
is vague.
   The administration has been seeking high-level talks on its $1.16
trillion fiscal 1990 spending plan. Many Democrats have been leery,
however, arguing that it would be a better strategy for Democrats to
write their own plan or wait until Bush spells out where he would
make spending cuts necessary to meet his overall budget goals.
   Meanwhile, Democrats and Republican on the appropriations panel,
in a report to the House Budget Committee, said Bush's $1.16
trillion fiscal blueprint ``does not deal adequately with essential
national needs'' and said they will make changes in his spending mix.
   ``The committee will adjust priorities as it deems necessary to
provide for essential national needs,'' panel members wrote in a
required annual report.
   Republicans on the committee submitted a statement saying they
favored reducing the deficit by raising new revenues and by saving
money in so-called mandatory programs. These programs are usually
benefits for which people automatically qualify, such as Medicare
assistance for the elderly and handicapped.
   ``Clearly the first step is to see if we can find enough
mandatory program savings and new resources to pay for any new
initiatives,'' said the GOP statement, submitted by the panel's
ranking Republican, Rep. Silvio Conte, R-Mass., and supported by at
least 21 of the 22 GOP members.
   ``The best way to seek agreement on this fundamental issue is to
convene a leadership group to negotiate,'' the Republicans said.
   Asked if he was suggesting new revenues and mandatory spending
cuts beyond those recommended by Bush in his budget, Conte said,
``That has to be considered.''
   The views of the appropriations committee's members, though
important, are not surprising because the panel oversees all
spending programs except for the mandatory ones.
   The Gramm-Rudman law requires a deficit next year of no more than
$100 billion. Every dollar collected in taxes or saved by reducing
mandatory programs is another dollar the appropriations committee
can spend on the programs it controls.
   The committee expressed doubt over whether Congress will grant
the $303 billion in military spending or the $14.7 billion for
foreign affairs that Bush seeks.
   The committee also said it believes Bush has sought insufficient
spending for housing, environmental protection and medical care for
veterans.
</TEXT>
