<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Sullivan-HHS     03-02 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sullivan-HHS,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Faces Early Decisions on Tough Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan soon will have to come up with answers on some of the most
difficult issues facing his department, including fetal tissue
research and planned Medicare spending cuts.
   Sullivan goes into the job of secretary of a department that
spends a third of the federal budget with the confidence of the
Senate, which approved his nomination 98-1 on Wednesday.
   ``I think he's well equipped to meet these challenges,'' Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said during debate on the nomination.
   Sullivan, who stepped down as president of the Morehouse School
of Medicine in Atlanta to take the HHS job, has avoided taking
positions on some of the hot issues he faces, and one of those cost
him a vote in the Senate.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., cast the lone vote against the
55-year-old Atlanta doctor ``as a matter of conscience'' because
Sullivan had declined to support the anti-abortion position against
use of federal funds to back medical research using aborted fetuses.
   At his confirmation hearing last week before the Senate Finance
Committee, Sullivan said he would not do ``anything to encourage
abortion in order to get fetal tissue'' for research. However, he
said he wanted to review an advisory committee's recommendations
before stating a final position on what conditions, if any, such
research could be allowed.
   The advisory committee concluded that research on tissue from
intentionally aborted fetuses, now under a moratorium at the
National Institutes of Health, be resumed under guidelines that
assure women would not be encouraged to have abortions to produce
the tissue.
   Abortion-related questions have been the most controversial for
Sullivan. Indeed, the doctor's introduction to the Washington
political scene was rocky because of his comments in a newspaper
interview favoring individual choice on abortion. He later told Sen.
Bob Packwood, R-Ore., he favored retaining the Supreme Court
decision that legalized abortion.
   But at two committee hearings before his confirmation, Sullivan
declared that he, like the president, opposes abortion except in
cases of rape, incest and danger to the mother's life, and wants the
court decision reversed.
   Packwood, a pro-choice advocate, appeared to hold no grudge
against Sullivan either for his abortion views or his flip-flop on
the court issue, and the senator said abortion has received too much
attention already.
   ``Dr. Sullivan fully realizes that the major things his
department has to do relate to Medicare, Medicaid, Social Security
and the tremendous budget restraints,'' he said.
   Sullivan was asked in the confirmation process about President
Bush's proposal to trim Medicare spending by $5 billion in fiscal
1990, but he has deferred on the specifics of that question, saying
he was not involved in the administration's detailed budget
discussions.
   Generally, Sullivan has said the department must evaluate
utilization of medical procedures funded by the federal health
insurance program for the elderly and disabled _ which has grown at
more than twice the rate of general inflation for several years.
   As part of an overall strategy for cutting the increase in
soaring medical costs in the federal budget, Sullivan has said that
focusing more on preventive medicine ``is ultimately more humane and
economical than merely treating illnesses.''
   But one senator cautioned him against optimism on this front,
saying the burgeoning federal deficit has stalled previous efforts
to promote prevention.
   ``You've got to spend money to save money, and you can't do that
in this system,'' Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., said during
Sullivan's appearance before the Finance Committee last week.
</TEXT>
