<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HijackingTrial     03-02 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacking Trial,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Didn't Give Accused Hijacker a Lawyer</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Aql in graf 7 is CQ</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents who arrested accused hijacker Fawaz
Younis say they advised him of his rights but did not provide him
with a lawyer or allow him to make a telephone call.
   Two of the FBI agents involved in ``Operation Goldenrod,'' in
which Younis was captured on Sept. 13, 1987, said they read him his
rights twice in Arabic, and that he waived his right to an attorney.
   Francis D. Carter, Younis' court-appointed attorney, on Wednesday
sought to show that Younis did not have an adequate understanding of
the U.S. legal system to grasp what was happening, and that some
legal lines were blurred in an arrest that was carried out in the
Mediterranean Sea with help from the Navy.
   Four eyewitnesses have identified Younis as the leader of five
heavily armed men who stormed aboard Royal Jordanian Airlines flight
402 at Beirut Airport on June 11, 1985. No one was killed in the
incident, which ended 30 hours later with the release of the
passengers and crew.
   Younis, 30, has pleaded innocent. He is on trial under a 1984
statute which asserts ``long-arm'' jurisdiction for the United
States in cases involving American hostages taken abroad.
   In testimony Wednesday, FBI agents said Younis told them after
his arrest that he hijacked the plane on orders from a senior
official of Lebanon's Amal militia, two of the agents testified
Wednesday.
   Younis told the FBI that the military commander of Amal, Aql
Hamiyya, gave him the orders and that they were approved by Nabih
Berri, the head of Amal.
   Berri is Lebanon's minister of justice. Amal is a Shiite Moslem
party.
   FBI agents Thomas Hansen and Dmitri Droujinksi told the jury at
U.S. District Court that Younis recounted the hijacking in detail
during four days aboard the Navy ship USS Butte after his arrest.
   Younis was later transferred to the aircraft carrier USS Saratoga
and flown non-stop to Andrews Air Force Base near Washington,
arriving four days after his arrest, the agents said.
   Carter sought to show that the government took inordinately long
in transporting the suspect and interrogated him while he was
suffering from two broken wrists inflicted during his arrest.
   Carter asked Droujinski whether there was an attorney aboard the
Butte.
   ``I don't think so,'' said the agent.
   ``Did you give him a chance to use the radio to contact anybody
at home, the proverbial telephone call? Did you offer him that?''
Carter asked.
   ``No, sir,'' replied the agent.
   Droujinski, an Arabic speaker who acted as interpreter during the
interrogation, testified that Younis gave his confession orally and
signed a written Arabic language version of it, making two changes.
   Younis corrected the spelling of one word and rephrased one
sentence to say that Berri ``approved'' rather than ``ordered'' the
hijacking.
   Droujinski read the altered sentence aloud, translating it into
English:
   ``On the day before the hijacking of the plane, a highly placed
representative of Amal got in touch with me and informed me that the
head of Amal approved the hijacking of a plane from the airport of
Beirut.''
   Carter has said that he will attempt to prove that his client was
acting under the equivalent of military orders when he led the
hijacking.
   Two other FBI agents described how they arrested Younis aboard an
80-foot sailboat in international waters 13 miles off Cyprus.
   Six members of the FBI hostage rescue team, including two women
in two-piece bathing suits, were visible on board the boat as Younis
approached in a launch, testified David W. Johnson, head of the
group.
   Another agent, George Gast, testified that he and another male
agent led Younis to the back of the yacht, slammed him to the deck,
told him he was under arrest and handcuffed him.
   Johnson said he had planned the ``take-down'' as a precaution.
   ``I was concerned for the safety of my team,'' testified Johnson.
``I didn't know whether he might be a karate expert or a judo
expert. I didn't know whether at the time of the arrest we would
have a double-cross.
   ``I had a bad experience with an arrest on a boat several weeks
before, in which the subject jumped overboard. It caused a great
deal of trouble,'' he said. ``It could get tricky, and somebody
could drown.''
</TEXT>
