<FIRST>r i PM-Johnson-Steriods     03-02 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Johnson-Steriods,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coach: Sprinter On Steroids Was `Worth A Meter'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben Johnson's coach says the sprinter, who was
stripped of Olympic gold last year for steroid use, had used the
performance-enhancing drugs since 1981 because it is virtually the
only way to stay competitive.
   Coach Charlie Francis told an inquiry Wednesday that he had
turned the Canadian sprinter on to steroids because Johnson's
competitors were taking them and it was thus necessary.
   He said sterioids had been ``worth a meter'' to Johnson, who won
the gold medal and set a world record in the 100 meters at the Seoul
Olympics only to be stripped of both the record and medal after
testing positive for steriod use.
   The 27-year-old Johnson has maintained that he never knowingly
used drugs.
   Francis, Johnson's coach since 1977, told the Canadian inquiry
board that he first approached Johnson about anabolic steroids and
other performance-enhancing drugs in the summer of 1981.
   He said Johnson ``was not sure of the advantages'' but had during
the fall ``decided he would go on.
   ``If he wanted to compete, it's pretty clear that steroids are
worth a meter at the highest level of sports,'' Francis said. ``I
think he understood that his competitors were on them.''
   Francis' only previous statement since the Olympics was that the
sprinter's urine test may have been sabotaged.
   In four hours of testimony, Francis said Johnson was among
several Canadian athletes who had received steroids from George
Astaphan, the St. Kitts doctor accused of administering the steroid
found in Johnson's urine sample taken after Johnson set the world
record in Seoul.
   Astaphan has denied the charge.
   Francis said top-level international competition is virtually
impossible without steroids _ which have harmful side-effects.
   He cautioned against believing any claims from top-level athletes
that they are clean and that their records are the result only of
hard work.
   ``It just isn't true, not at the highest level,'' Francis said.
He said repeatedly that steroids ``are not a short cut'' but the
reason top-level athletes are able to train as hard as they do.
</TEXT>
