<FIRST>r w PM-Yeutter-Aflatoxin     03-02 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yeutter-Aflatoxin,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Secretary Says Carcinogenic Fungus Aflatoxin Being Kept out of
Food Supply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers shouldn't be afraid that aflatoxin is
going to show up in their food, even though the recent drought
created conditions under which the carcinogen thrives, says
Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter.
   ``Any time we have a drought, we are going to see more aflatoxin
problems,'' Yeutter said Wednesday before the House Appropriations
subcommittee on rural development, agriculture and related agencies.
``That doesn't mean we're going to have more in the food supply ...
or any that slips in is going to hurt anyone.''
   In answer to a question from Rep. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., Yeutter
said a recent article in The Wall Street Journal reporting that
aflatoxin-tainted corn is moving through the nation's food chain
focuses on the ``worst case scenarios.''
   ``It articulates a viewpoint that has scare dimensions to it,''
he said.
   ``Everyone is going to do their best to minimize the risk of
letting aflatoxin into the food supply,'' he said. ``Nobody in the
food chain wants it.''
   He said the government cannot guarantee a risk-free world, but
``there aren't people trying to slip aflatoxin-laden products into
the food supply.''
   The heat and drought that year were ideal for the fungus that
produces aflatoxin, which researchers have linked to the development
of liver cancer in laboratory rats.
   On Tuesday, the Food and Drug Administration said about 6 percent
_ 95 samples out of 1,650 _ of the field corn tested in recent
months had higher levels.
   That corn cannot be used for human consumption, but can be
diverted to feed non-dairy cattle, the FDA said.
   FDA tested about 263 samples of corn flour and corn meal and
found 2 percent, or six samples, to have more than 20 parts of
aflatoxin per billion. FDA policy requires that these products be
removed from the market.
   Yeutter also discussed international trade reform with the
committee, saying the climate for change is better than it has been
in a decade.
   He said that there are some hurdles the United States and
European Community must work out before talks in the Uruguay Round
resume next month in Geneva.
   ``I'm cautiously optimistic we'll get that worked out between now
and April,'' he told the committee.
   The United States has been seeking removal of government
subsidies on exports worldwide, but its position has been unpopular
with other nations.
   ``What happens in the Uruguay Round will determine what we should
have in farm legislation,'' Yeutter said.
   He said he doesn't anticipate any significant changes from the
1985 farm bill that is due to expire in 1990. He said Congress could
extend the 1985 law until the Uruguay talks are complete, or pass a
new bill and amend it as necessary after the negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Tower-Senators     03-02 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower-Senators,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Challenges Senate to Live up to Same Standards</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tower is challenging the Senate to live up
to the same standards by which it is judging him, saying senators
sometimes vote after drinking alcohol and that he doubts he is alone
in having broken his marriage vows.
   Nobody's perfect, the secretary of defense-designate seemed to be
saying in his speech Wednesday to the National Press Club.
   Even before Tower spoke, the leader of the Senate's Democratic
majority, George Mitchell of Maine, said in a speech that ``it is
not moral perfection or the qualifications of senators that are at
issue here.''
   The things that are at issue are far different than they used to
be, however.
   Tower devoted his press club speech to defense policy questions,
saying these are the subjects that ``normally occupy the mind of the
nominee of secretary of defense.''
   They are not the subjects that have dominated his confirmation
proceedings.
   Nor, for that matter, did these or similar dry subjects force
Gary Hart from the race for the Democratic presidential nomination
or sidetrack President Reagan's nomination of Douglas Ginsburg to be
a Supreme Court justice.
   Hart, who served on the Senate Armed Services Committee when
Tower was its chairman, withdrew from the White House contest in May
1987 after a newspaper story that he had spent a night with a
part-time actress while his wife was out of town.
   ``We're all going to have to seriously question the system for
selecting our national leaders that reduces the press of this nation
to hunters and presidential candidates to being hunted,'' Hart said
at the time.
   Ginsburg withdrew from contention for the Supreme Court seat in
November, 1987, saying his views on the law had ``been drowned out
in the clamor'' over his admission that he smoked marijuana as a
student in the 1960s and a Harvard Law School professor in the 1970s.
   In Tower's case, opponents have zeroed in on his drinking and
relations with women, as well as his activities as a consultant to
defense contractors. The nominee says he has cut out all drinking
except for wine with meals, and will eliminate that too if he is
confirmed.
   Tom Korologos, a lobbyist and former Nixon White House official
who has guided a number of Republican nominations through the
Senate, said he could remember no confirmation battle so dominated
by personal issues.
   ``This one has no constituency out there, nobody rising up and
down over a policy, over an environmental or a strategic issue,''
Korologos said. ``This is all personal, and it's unfortunate that
the Senate has come to this.''
   Mitchell, announcing his opposition to Tower, saw it differently.
   ``Public officials have a right to a private life,'' he said.
``They do not have a right to engage publicly in behavior which
could interfere with the discharge of their public duties.''
   ``A single lapse in judgment _ or perhaps even a few _ should not
disqualify an individual from public service,'' Mitchell continued.
   ``But when the lapses in judgment form a pattern of many
incidents spanning many years, and when there is insufficient
evidence to demonstrate that the pattern has been broken, then there
are reasonable grounds to question whether the individual possesses
the qualities necessary for the uniquely demanding job of the
secretary of defense.''
   Tower said he agreed that the nominee for the top Pentagon job
should be held to a high standard, but also asked whether it is
acceptable for members of the Senate ``who had a few drinks in
hideaways ... to come onto the floor late in the evening and vote on
vital issues of nuclear deterrence.''
   Then, when he was asked whether he had ever broken wedding vows,
the twice-divorced and now single ex-senator said, , ``As a matter
of fact, I have broken wedding vows. I think I am probably not alone
in that connection.''
   It was an extraordinary confession for an American political
figure. Hart, although he admitted poor judgment, said he did not do
anything immoral during his night with actress-model Donna Rice and
refused to answer questions about whether he had ever committed
adultery.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   W. Dale Nelson is a Washington reporter for The
Associated Press who has covered the Senate and the White House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
