<FIRST>r p PM-Tower-Grassroots     03-02 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower-Grassroots,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>State GOP Officials Report Little Push for Tower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative activists are trying to generate
grassroots support for John Tower, but Republican Party officials
around the nation concede they haven't seen much of a groundswell of
support for President Bush's Pentagon nominee.
   ``Senator Tower is being victimized by a partisan power play on
the part of some Democrats in the United States Senate,'' said a
newspaper ad run Wednesday by Conservative Future PAC.
   ``An exercise in rumor-mongering and the most vile form of
partisan politics,'' was how L. Brent Bozell III, director of the
Conservative Victory Committee, described the opposition to the
former Texas senator.
   The conservative groups that are making the Tower confirmation a
partisan confrontation may be suffering from the early damage done
by one of their own. Paul Weyrich of the Free Congress Foundation
testified against Tower last month before the Senate Armed Services
Committee, raising allegations of drinking and womanizing.
   On the party level, Mark Goodin, communications director for the
Republican National Committee, said efforts were under way to
generate support for Tower. But local GOP officials said they hadn't
been contacted.
   ``No one has called me from the RNC to talk about the Tower
situation at all,'' said Dwight Adams, chairman of the South Dakota
Republican Party. Sen. Larry Pressler of South Dakota was among the
wavering Republicans.
   Another undecided Republican senator was Charles Grassley of
Iowa. His state party chairman, Rich Schwarm, said, ``I don't think
anyone would want to pressure Sen. Grassley by generating a
groundswell.''
   ``I haven't been asked to do anything,'' said Jean Sullivan, a
Republican National Committeewoman from Alabama. The state has two
Democratic senators. Richard Shelby has announced his opposition to
Tower and Howell Heflin is among the undecided.
   Mrs. Sullivan said she thought Republicans could generate some
pressure on Heflin, but ``I don't like pressure tactics. ... We
could beat him up pretty good.''
   But, she went on, national party officials ``better tell us what
they want us to start doing.''
   In North Carolina, Robert Jones, spokesman for the state
Republican Party, said he knew of no effort to generate a
groundswell for Tower.
   ``We personally haven't done anything,'' he said.
   That was in sharp contrast to the effort made last year on behalf
of the nomination of Robert H. Bork to the Supreme Court.
   ``We did quite a bit of work on that,'' said Jones. ``There was a
strong matter of principle involved.''
   Asked if the Tower nomination was a political issue in his state,
Fred Logan, the Kansas GOP chairman, repl;ied, ``I don't think so.''
   Senate GOP leader Bob Dole of Kansas has been leading the fight
for confirmation, but his Kansas colleague, Nancy Kassebaum is among
the undecided.
   Mary Alice Lair, a national committeewoman from Kansas, said,
``Certainly, our Sen. Dole is doing his part.''
   Asked if there was any effort to convince Kassebaum to support
Tower, Mrs. Lair said: ``We are trying. But, you know, she has a
mind of her own, which I respect.''
   ``I have not been asked by anyone to have any contact with her,''
said Fred Logan, the Kansas Republican Party chairman. ``Nancy
Kassebaum is going to make up her own mind and I trust her
judgment.''
</TEXT>
