<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded after a setback in early
trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, while the dollar
inched up from the previous day's closing.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 21.30 points
Wednesday, sharply rebounded and gained 109.43 points, or 0.34
percent, to end trading at 32,073.73. The index, which shed 83.74
points in the morning session, reversed the trend and rose in the
afternoon.
   The dollar finished trading at 128.07 yen, up 0.39 yen from
Wednesday's 127.68-yen close. The currency opened at 127.93 yen and
fluctuated between 127.90 yen and 128.50 yen.
   Dealers said the dollar started higher in Tokyo following its
overnight strength in overseas trading where market players bought
the currency following diminishing concern of an interest-rate hike
in West Germany.
   They said foreign banks and securities firms were leading buyers
of the U.S currency in Tokyo. If West Germany did not raise its
interest rate, investors were likely to buy it in even larger
quantities, the dealers added.
   Stock dealers said the Nikkei started rebounding as investors
began buying real estate issues.
