<HEAD>Memphis Barbecue May Mean Gator Tail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual Memphis barbecue billed as the
world's largest overindulgence of pork and beer is expanding its
menu this year to include such delights as alligator tail and
``swamp cabbage.''
   ``It's a real motley assortment,'' said Carolyn Gluckert, a
spokeswoman for the Memphis in May International Festival.
   The World Championship Barbecue Cooking Contest, which is part of
the city's month-long May festival, is held on a downtown bluff
overlooking the Mississippi River and attracts cooking teams from
around the country, and occasionally from abroad.
   The May 11-13 affair includes a parade, costume contest and
outdoor musical shows. It draws thousands of spectators, beer
drinkers and barbecue eaters.
   Cooking teams for last year's 11th annual cookoff fired up 50,610
pounds of pork.
   The contest judging is in three categories, whole hog, shoulder
and ribs, but a new one is being added. It's called ``Anything
But,'' Ms. Gluckert said.
   The ``Anything But'' will be limited, on a first-come basis, to
60 of the 175 cooking teams taking part in the barbecue. Early
entries have indicated plans to cook venison, various crustaceans
and alligator tail, Ms. Gluckert said.
   The contestants can also add trimmings in trying to sway the
judges, and hush puppies and something mysterious called ``swamp
cabbage,'' have been mentioned so far, she said.
