<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ShamuWinter     03-02 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shamu Winter,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blubber Helps Ward Off Cold For Whale Spending First Winter In Ohio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AURORA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When your roots are in Iceland, the first
winter in Ohio isn't as intimidating, even if you spent your first
13 in Florida and California.
   It also helps to eat about 75,000 calories a day.
   Shamu, a 16{-foot, 6,400-pound white and black killer whale, is
getting along just fine amid 39 inches of snow and 85 days of
freezing temperatures for the season.
   She spent her first 13 winters at Sea Worlds in Orlando, Fla.,
and in San Diego but comes from hardy stock: She was captured off
Iceland.
   ``This has perhaps been her coldest weather,'' said Stan W.
Searles, curator at the 90-acre Sea World marine park 30 miles
southeast of Cleveland.
   During past winters Shamu _ a stage name shared by killer whales
at other Sea Worlds _ has been transported to Orlando or San Diego
because of research or breeding needs.
   ``This has been a very mild winter for Ohio,'' Searles said in an
interview in his office tucked inside the back of Shamu's 4,000-seat
stadium. ``It is not a problem for her. She has a huge blubber
layer.''
   Six inches in all, according to Searles.
   He adjusts Shamu's winter diet to provide her with more calories
because she must expend more energy to keep warm amid the cold air,
even if the water in her open-air pool is kept at about 55 degrees
year-round.
   ``She's certainly aware that it's colder,'' he said, ``because
she's breathing colder air.''
   On a recent day when snow was swirling in the wind and the
temperature dipped to 14 degrees, Shamu was active and ready to play
when trainer Beth Riegelmayer appeared in a multicolored wet suit
with a bucket of fish.
   Searles, whose staff feeds Shamu 140 pounds of frozen fish daily,
sometimes cuts back the rations of herring, smelt and squid to 130
pounds if she's less interested.
   ``We can just tell she's not as hungry,'' said Seales, who
increases calorie-rich herring portions when Shamu requires more
food to stay warm on cold days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
