<SECOND>PM-People-Jessica Hahn,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hahn Visits Charlotte For First Time Since Testifying In PTL Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica Hahn, whose sexual encounter with
Jim Bakker lead to his ouster from PTL, returned to the city where
the evangelical organization was founded and said she hopes to run
into Bakker.
   If she did, she told reporters Wednesday, ``I'd tell him, `What
did you hope to accomplish with all of this? Did you want to get
(wife) Tammy jealous or what?'''
   Hahn was last in Charlotte in 1987 to testify before a federal
grand jury investigating PTL. The former church secretary from New
York's Long Island returned for a radio station promotion today.
   The Bakkers, who live in Pineville, 10 miles south of Charlotte,
have started a television ministry that is shown on some cable
networks. PTL's properties are now owned by Canadian businessman
Stephen Mernick.
   Hahn admitted she felt somewhat awkward being in Charlotte. But
she said she would walk the grounds of Heritage USA, the Fort Mill,
S.C., religious retreat that was Bakker's citadel.
   ``I really want to go to PTL so I can understand what it's all
about,'' she said. ``It's like trying to find your real father.''
   She said she was saddened when the television ministry fell on
hard times following the revelation of the tryst.
   ``If people want to blame me, fine,'' she said. ``I had so little
to do with PTL falling, but it was that one day that led to it.''
   Hahn, who has appeared nude in two Playboy magazine issues and is
currently featured in a rock video version of ``Wild Thing'' by
comedian Sam Kinison, said she was enjoying her celebrity status.
   ``I am 29, I'm a girl and I'm having fun,'' she said.
