<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     03-02 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Curbs Some Emergency Powers In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some emergency powers introduced by Britain in 1978
to curb guerrilla action in Northern Ireland are not being renewed
because they were found to cause widespread resentment, Northern
Ireland Secretary Tom King says.
   King on Wednesday asked WParliament to drop measures that compel
crowds to disperse, impose directions on the conduct of funerals and
close drinking places.
   Parliament must renew the emergency powers annually for them to
stay in effect.
   Lord Colville, a barrister who reviews the operation of
counter-terrorist laws in the British-ruled province, reported last
month that rudeness on the part of police and soliders was stoking
long-term resentment toward security forces.
   He gave as an example the case of an unidentified man in
Londonderry who had been stopped 33 times last summer under
emergency powers _ and detained each time for between 15 and 45
minutes.
   Colville said winning hearts and minds should be a ``paramount
preoccupation'' for the security forces.
   King said in a House of Commons written reply that he welcomed
the recommendations.
</TEXT>
