<FIRST>u a PM-TinyTown Bjt   03-02 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tiny Town, Bjt,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Belt Residents Take Manhattan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in grafs 4, 6, 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The entire town of Bolan, Iowa, took the stage of
David Letterman's show knowing the joke was on them, but the 16
residents say the last laugh was theirs.
   They were wined and dined and eventually maligned during a
three-day all-expenses-paid adventure that saw them plucked from
quiet obscurity in the corn and soybean fields of the Midwest for a
sudden assault on their senses in the Big Apple.
   The moment in the sun for the entire population of Bolan's
metropolitan area _ six Bolanites and 10 from the ``suburbs'' _ came
on NBC-TV's ``Late Night with David Letterman.''
   They watched offstage on a monitor as comedian Jeff Altman, the
first guest, told Letterman and the audience that he walked past the
Bolanites to get on stage and one of them said, ``Who the hell is
that?''
   Larry Nydegger, 21, immediately defended himself.
   ``It was me but I didn't say, `hell.'''
   Letterman, whose show was taped late Wednesday and broadcast
early today, held nothing back.
   ``Do you have like a town slut?'' he asked 73-year-old Ruth
Hansen. ``And if so, when she comes up, point her out.''
   Mrs. Hansen, a 50-year resident, chuckled.
   Also put on the spot was Nydegger's 23-year-old sister, Lori, a
weekend resident who admitted that she spends most of her week away
from town.
   ``So, you're just here for the free trip?'' Letterman asked as
she blushed and shook her head. ``Let's string her up.''
   Lori Nydegger was the one who helped draw attention to Bolan
during a 1986 centennial celebration.
   She formed a standstill parade of floats, marching band members
on lawn chairs, and grand marshals on cars, all on the village's
single street. The spectators marched around it while the parade
stood still.
   The town is 130 miles north of Des Moines and consists of an
antique shop, a Methodist church and the Bolan Store Inc., a farm
equipment and supplies store that owns three-fourths of the town's
property and is for sale.
   A 16-acre property with a three-bedroom home, one of eight in
Bolan and its suburbs, is also on the market, for $42,000.
   The 103-year-old community at one time had 75 residents as well
as a general store, a blacksmith, a train depot, a post office,
lumber yards, stock yards and a creamery.
   But the automobile changed everything and Bolan's population has
remained relatively stable _ and small _ the last 20 years.
   While they were away, the Bolanites arranged for friends or
relatives to stay at each of their homes and hired additional
security officers to protect their belongings.
   Letterman, prompted by a staffer intrigued by Bolan, paid for the
Iowans' trip. They stayed at the Mayflower Hotel, where they held a
party after the taping _ and watched themselves on television.
   Earlier, they toured Manhattan, and every corner seemed to bring
something to turn their heads.
   A man cursing loudly for no obvious reason passed near Lori
Nydegger.
   ``Oh my,'' she said. ``They get kind of mad, don't they?''
   Her 17-year-old brother, Loren, said he was ``asked for money
twice in one block.''
   ``I'm glad I grew up where I did,'' he said.
   Comparing motorists in Bolan and Manhattan, 59-year-old Daryl
McCready said: ``We wave at everybody. They give each other the
bird.''
   But McCready said the town was enjoying the trip _ even if some
people were poking fun at them.
   ``We have to laugh at ourselves, too,'' he said. ``Main Street is
720 feet long and it ends in a dead end in a corn field. ...
   ``These people who might laugh at us would like to be in our
place, too,'' McCready said. ``We're in the enviable position of
being the only town that was flown for free to New York.''
   Says Mrs. Hansen: ``The town of Bolan got put back on the map,
especially after NBC and David Letterman.''
</TEXT>
