<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneEmergency     03-02 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Emergency,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lawsuits Filed in Connection with United Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight attendant who said she was nearly
dragged through a gaping hole in a jumbo jet and a passenger who
suffered ear injuries filed the first lawsuits stemming from the
tragedy aboard United Airlines Flight 811.
   Melvin Belli, the flamboyant San Francisco attorney, is
co-counsel in one of the lawsuits filed against United Airlines and
Boeing Co. on Wednesday, five days after the accident.
   Nine people were hurled to their deaths when the Boeing 747 bound
for New Zealand blew open shortly after takeoff from Honolulu.
Twenty-seven others were treated for injuries in what one crew
member said was ``unbelievable horror.''
   ``I felt like Dorothy in the Wizard of Oz when her house gets
picked up and everything gets blown away,'' purser Sarah Shanahan
said in an interview published Wednesday in The Honolulu
Star-Bulletin.
   Shanahan said it was ``truly a miracle that there were not more
injuries to people from things flying around in the cabin. There
were ice buckets, racks of glasses, cartons of juice and bins of
things around.''
   During the ordeal, she said, she instructed the passengers to
tighten their seat belts, grab their ankles and ``stay down until
you know we're back on Earth and we've stopped.''
   When the captain announced that the plane was two minutes from
the end of the runway, ``people kept unfastening their seat belts
and standing up to look out the windows,'' she said. ``I'm sure that
they wanted the reassurance. They wanted to see those Honolulu city
lights.
   ``That's why I'm hoarse. I screamed for two minutes: `Grab your
ankles! Stay down! Stay down! Stay down!''' Shanahan said.
   The lawsuits were filed by passenger Edwin Geoffrey Tudor of New
South Wales, Australia, and Mae S. Sapolu, a United flight attendant
from Honolulu.
   Tudor's lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court here, asks
unspecified damages from United Airlines and Boeing and alleges
negligence in maintaining the airplane.
   Tudor suffered ear injuries and emotional distress, according to
Belli's co-counsel, John S. Carroll. He declined to elaborate on
Tudor's claim of neglect.
   Ms. Sapolu is suing in state court, asking unspecified damages
from Boeing.
   She was serving drinks when the hole opened, according to her
attorney, L. Richard Fried Jr. She was thrown to the floor two rows
behind the hole and had to cling to a seat to keep from being swept
out of the plane, Fried said.
   Sapolu said she suffered physical and emotional injuries.
   Fried said he believes Boeing has failed to fully inform airlines
about problems with its jets: ``It's our feeling that Boeing knew
things about aging problems with these aircraft that they're not
passing along to carriers.''
   His firm has been designated lead counsel in suits stemming from
last year's accident aboard an Aloha Airlines Boeing 737, when a
hole ripped open in the fuselage, killing a flight attendant.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators suspect a
forward cargo door on the United jet popped open at 22,000 feet,
tearing away with a large section of fuselage.
   Jack Gamble, a spokesman for Boeing Commercial Airplanes, said
the company would not comment on the lawsuits. A United spokesman
did not immediately return a phone call.
   The damaged jetliner will be repaired, although there was no
estimate on when it will be returned to service, Jim Guyette,
United's executive vice president for operations, said earlier.
</TEXT>
