<FIRST>r a PM-FloridaWildfires     03-02 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Wildfires,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers, Clouds Ease Fire Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State foresters who battled a four-day fire that
scorched 17,000 acres of the drought-parched Everglades have offered
$1,000 for information leading to the arrests of those who sparked
the blaze.
   The wildfire was finally doused Wednesday afternoon as heavy
rains moved into the area, but firefighters planned to fly over the
burned area today to check on any new fires, said state Forestry
Division duty officer Phil DeAngelis in Fort Lauderdale.
   ``We don't expect any problems with (the fire restarting), but it
was an arson, so you never know what's going to happen,'' said
DeAngelis.
   Investigators today still tried to pinpoint the origin of the
massive fire, which threatened power lines and forced some road
closings because of thick smoke, DeAngelis said.
   Another wildfire in southeast Florida burned 4,100 acres of
cypress and palmetto trees and engulfed six camp buildings used by
hunters in Collier County before a brief shower helped firefighters
contain it Wednesday morning, said duty officer Roberta Smith in
Fort Myers.
   ``It seemed like it rained right over the fire,'' Ms. Smith said.
``That helped us out an awful lot.''
   The two blazes were the largest of more than 50 brush fires the
forestry division has fought since Monday with about 400
firefighters, said Charles Maynard, the agency's spokesman in
Tallahassee.
   ``We're probably in better shape than we have been all week,''
state forestry division spokesman Jim Whitson said Wednesday. ``It
looks like we've got some moisture coming into the state right now.''
   The Everglades fire finally stalled at a canal near the
Broward-Palm Beach county line after firefighters set backfires with
incendiary bombs dropped from a helicopter.
   Their strategy managed to keep a 10-mile-long wall of flame away
from power lines serving more than 3 million South Florida
residents. In 1985, an Everglades fire that burned more than 100,000
acres engulfed power lines and caused massive blackouts in South
Florida.
   ``We got it out with a little help from Mother Nature,''
DeAngelis said. ``Some of our boys suffered exhaustion from working
the fire so long, but there were no serious injuries.''
   In central Florida, however, two volunteer firefighters
responding to a wildfire Monday were killed when a tractor-trailer
slammed into their smoke-shrouded fire truck.
   The extent of last month's hot, dry weather became clear
Wednesday when the weather service released temperature and rainfall
data.
   In Miami, the average high temperature in February was 79.6
degrees, or 3.8 degrees above normal, and measurable rain was
reported only three times. Only 0.71 inch of rain fell at Miami
International Airport, or 1.31 inches below normal.
   In Fort Myers on the Gulf Coast, the average high temperature was
79.7 degrees, or 4.6 degrees above normal. Measurable rain fell only
twice for a total of 0.36 inch, or 1.7 inches below normal.
</TEXT>
