<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     03-02 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>280 To Be Freed Following Protest, But Detentions To Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan
Vlok said today that 280 detainees, more than a quarter of those
being held without charge, will be free by this weekend.
   However, Vlok, who arranged the releases over a two-week period
as part of an effort to end a widespread hunger strike, said the
government had no plans to lift the 32-month state of emergency that
allows indefinite detention without trial.
   An anti-apartheid newspaper, New Nation, said today that more
than 50 people had been detained in the two weeks since Vlok's
pledge of large-scale releases prompted most of the hunger strikers
to suspend their fast.
   Hunger strikes continue at prisons in Natal Province. The exact
number of participants is not known, but laywers say at least 18
have been hospitalized.
   Vlok, in a statement, said: ``Although the release of detainees
is an ongoing process, I will not hesitate to take whatever steps
necessary to prevent renewed violence and unrest.''
   ``The revolutionary climate is still very high,'' he said. ``The
present state of emergency is still very necessary.''
   He cited continuing black-on-black factional violence in Natal
Province, instability at schools in the township of Soweto, and a
persistent rent boycott by blacks in several townships.
   Vlok's statement came a day after he conferred with Anglican
Archbiship Desmond Tutu and other anti-apartheid church leaders.
Most of the clergymen had met with Vlok on Feb. 16, at the height of
the hunger strike, and emerged to call for suspension of the protest
because Vlok had promised to free a ``substantial number'' of
detainees.
   Anti-apartheid leaders have praised Vlok's willingness to meet
with clergymen and lawyers concerning detainees but have criticized
severe restrictions placed on many of those freed.
   Many of the released activists have been barred from political
activity and ordered to be in their homes each night.
   In a separate development, a pro-government newspaper criticized
the leader of the Dutch Reformed Church for questioning the
government's refusal to negotiate with the banned African National
Congress until the guerrilla movement renounces violence.
   Johan Heyns, leader of the denomination to which most government
officials and other Afrikaners belong, said in a debate Monday that
he had ``ethical problems'' with the government's stance.
   He said a renunciation of violence by the ANC would be a result
of negotiations and should not be a precondition.
   The Citizen, a Johannesburg daily, said it hoped Heyns' comments
had no effect.
   ``Why give credibility to an organization that uses violence to
achieve its political aims?'' it asked in an editorial. ``Why turn
the men with guns and limpet mines into ordinary, acceptable
participants in the efforts to establish a new order?''
   Under apartheid, the country's 28 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
