<FIRST>r a PM-JailhouseJournalism     03-02 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jailhouse Journalism,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Writers Win Awards In National Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They made headlines when they broke the
law, but now they write headlines in prison publications across the
country.
   ``We consider ourselves professionals,'' said 33-year-old Robert
Taliaferro, who edits The Prison Mirror at the Minnesota
Correctional Facility in Stillwater as he serves a life sentence for
murder.
   The Prison Mirror recently was named ``Best Newspaper'' for 1988
in the 25th annual American Penal Press contest, sponsored by
Southern Illinois University-Carbondale. Taliaferro's paper won the
title for the third consecutive year.
   ``There is so much passion and intensity in corrections'
journalism,'' said Walter Jaehnig, journalism school director at
SIU. He said the school's competition is the only penal press
contest in the nation.
   ``You can see it in their work. I've been real impressed with
what I've seen,'' he said. ``We feel it's important to encourage
journalism wherever you find it _ in high schools or prison, or
anywhere else.''
   Vienna in Progress, the newspaper at the Vienna Correctional
Center in Southern Illinois, captured second place in the prison
press contest, and the Echo of the Texas Department of Corrections
in Huntsville came in third.
   ``I think it shows the world that certain inmates are capable of
extracting the good from themselves,'' said David Patin, editor of
Vienna in Progress since October.
   ``It's an outlet here that lets them express themselves on a
different level,'' added Patin, 35, of Chicago, who is serving a
five-year sentence for robbery.
   ``Here, there's not much opportunity for intellectual exchange,''
he said Wednesday.
   ``I would be very happy,'' Taliaferro told a reporter, ``to send
my guys out there and compete with any one of you guys.''
   Both editors said their publications focus on the positive side
of prison life, including educational and vocational programs, as
well as on problems and issues in prison, like AIDS. Neither editor
has had formal journalistic training.
   Taliaferro said he looks for good, aggressive writers for his
five-member staff, people who can get information in a place known
for its reticent residents.
   He also said prison newspaper work has its perks, like freedom to
roam the institution.
   John Levesque, publisher of the Edwardsville Intelligencer and
judge of the ``Best Newspaper'' category, said he reviewed about 30
entries that ranged from good to ``dreadful.''
   ``There are some good writers in prison,'' said Levesque. ``I was
encouraged that these people are getting some worthwhile experience
in prison.''
   The contest offers 10 other categories in addition to ``Best
Newspaper,'' including best magazine, picture, sports, poetry,
editorial, feature, cartoon, fiction, art and news story.
   But most importantly, Taliaferro and Patin said, prison
publications give inmates an opportunity to learn a trade, bettering
their chances of getting a job after prison.
   ``What it comes down to is a sense of pride,'' said Taliaferro,
speaking about the newspaper's first-place award. ``Some of these
guys have not won anything in their lives. ``It's something
progressive, for once.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
