<FIRST>r a PM-Refugees-MentalHealth     03-02 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees-Mental Health,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Mental Health Care Severely Lacking In Cambodian Camps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lack of mental health care in the largest
Cambodian refugee camp in Thailand is leading to violence and
depression among its residents, according to a report released today.
   ``Mental health needs are neglected ... and there is a total lack
of capacity in the community to provide for their own members,''
said Dr. Richard Mollica, chairman of the World Federation for
Mental Health and co-author of the report.
   Mollica, the director of the Indochinese Psychiatry Clinic at
Boston's St. Elizabeth's Hospital, said levels of domestic violence
and suicide are escalating.
   The federation filed its report with the United Nations.
   Representatives of the group's Committee on Refugees and Migrants
conducted a field survey from Sept. 26 to Oct. 6, 1988, at a camp
said to be representative of conditions in all refugee camps on the
Thailand-Cambodia border.
   About 300,000 people have lived in the camps since 350,000
Cambodians fled their country during Pol Pot's Khmer Rouge regime.
The camp studied is the largest with about 170,000 people.
   Although medical and educational services at the camp have
improved in recent years, ``cultural norms have broken down to
dangerous levels _ with the ultimate outcome a major disintegration
of the Khmer (Cambodian) culture,'' the report said.
   The report said the residents have been subject to psychiatric
disorders not only because of the refugee flight and subsequent
arrival in the camps, but because of the trauma of the Vietnam War.
Approximately 60,000 people died in the U.S bombing of Cambodia, and
about 1 million were killed during the Khmer Rouge regime from 1975
to 1979.
   The rate of suicide increased last year at the camp, the report
said. More than 90 percent of attempts were by women ages 15 to 30,
usually using an overdose of medication.
   One factor characteristic of the mentally ill is the Tiing Moong,
or ``dummy'' personality, a state of psychological withdrawal
fashioned by refugees from the brutal Pol Pot regime in order to
survive.
   Refugees acted as if they were deaf, dumb, confused or stupid,
since many of those who had behaved intelligently or asked many
questions in Cambodia were usually tortured or executed.
   While originally an act to appear submissive, the mental health
federation found that many Khmer people, especially children, would
maintain this attitude to mask depression.
   ``Unless their problems are adequately addressed, they will
become dysfunctional adults and eventually enormous economic and
social burdens on their future communities,'' the report said.
   The report calls on the Thai government, internal organizations
in the camp, and the United Nations to help deal with the mental
health problem.
   The federation recommended that technical assistance and training
be provided by Khmer mental health professionals and religious
leaders to promote Khmer self-management. But the intervention of
administrators would probably diminish the effectiveness of the
self-help initiatives, the report said.
   Other recommendatons included an all-encompassing mental health
system.
   ``Our ultimate hope is that the environment in the camp will
improve so that the Khmer will be able to make a contribution to
their own society,'' Mollica said, ``now and when they are finally
repatriated.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0065 </DOCNO>
