<DOCNO> AP890302-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LittleRockDeseg     03-02 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Little Rock Deseg,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers Sign Settlement in Little Rock Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state has agreed to settle the
largest desegregation case in its history by paying out $118
million, including NAACP attorneys' fees dating back to the landmark
court-ordered integration of 1957.
   The proposed settlement, which ends six years of litigation
involving the state and the three school districts in Pulaski
County, was signed by attorneys for all the parties before U.S.
District Judge Henry Woods on Wednesday.
   ``We knew that we were going to have to pay a sizable amount of
money, and I think all things considered, this is the best possible
deal the state could have gotten,'' state Education Director Ruth
Steele said.
   The Little Rock School District, which is mostly black, had sued
the state and the neighboring, mostly white North Little Rock and
Pulaski County school districts in federal court, alleging the
defendants caused illegal segregation in Little Rock schools.
   Woods found North Little Rock and Pulaski County liable and
ordered the districts merged. But the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, while affirming Woods' liability ruling, said his proposed
countywide consolidation was too severe.
   Instead, the appeals court ordered the boundary line between the
Little Rock and Pulaski County districts redrawn, moving large,
mostly white sections of the city of Little Rock, which were in the
county district, into the city district. North Little Rock was not
affected.
   The appeals court then asked the district judge to consider how
much the state would have to pay for compensatory education programs
in the three districts, including magnet schools in Little Rock.
   The agreement calls for the payment of $59 million to the Little
Rock district, $19.7 million to the Pulaski County district and $2.7
million to the North Little Rock district for compensatory programs.
   Among other payments the state would make is $3.1 million in
attorneys' fees for the Legal Defense Fund of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, for work going
back to 1956 involving the original Little Rock desegregation case
and the 1957 school crisis.
   In 1957, enforcing a landmark Supreme Court decision, President
Eisenhower sent federal troops into Little Rock to protect the
court-ordered rights of nine black students to attend the otherwise
all-white Central High School.
   If Wednesday's agreement is approved by Woods, the state would be
released as a defendant in the case. Final approval is needed from
Woods, all three school boards, the Legislature and the state Board
of Education. No hearing was set.
   The Little Rock School Board quickly became the first public
group to approve the settlement.
   ``The settlement is more than just dollars. It's many concepts
and successful programs that will work when implemented correctly,''
school board President Robin Armstrong said.
   The payments would total $118 million over the next decade, the
most in a desegregation case in the state's history.
   A bill filed in the Legislature Wednesday would add a 5 percent
surcharge on the income taxes of residents of Pulaski County to
defray the desegregation costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HazardousWaste     03-02 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hazardous Waste,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Scrutinizes South Carolina's Waste Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency
intends to monitor South Carolina's ban on hazardous wastes from 32
states and Puerto Rico to determine its effects on the state's own
hazardous waste program.
   Greer Tidwell, the EPA's southeastern administrator, said the
agency is ``concerned'' about the state's action and urged eight
other states in the region to look at cooperative efforts in
handling hazardous waste.
   The EPA can take away any state's authority to handle its own
hazardous waste program. If it is removed, all related permits for
that state would have to be issued by the regional office and
accompanying federal money could be reduced, EPA spokesman Carl
Terry said.
   Terry's comments came as South Carolina began its ban on
hazardous wastes and two of the most affected states _ Florida and
North Carolina _ tried to regain access to the state's privately
owned landfill.
   Ten extra inspectors stood ready at the landfill to turn back
loads from banned states Wednesday, but all of the 25 trucks came
from approved states, state Health Department spokesman Bill Culler
said.
   ``It looks like the word got around and there haven't been a
whole lot of problems,'' Culler said.
   State Department of Health and Environmental Control officials
announced Tuesday that only 17 states plus South Carolina and the
District of Columbia would be allowed to continue disposing
hazardous waste in the state as a result of Gov. Carroll Campbell's
executive order of Jan. 18.
   Campbell announced that South Carolina would prohibit, beginning
Wednesday, the disposal of waste from any state that refused to
dispose of the waste itself. He said it was meant to encourage other
states to locate disposal sites within their own borders rather than
relying on South Carolina.
   In a statement Wednesday, the EPA's Tidwell said the agency
``will monitor the situation closely to determine what effect the
state's action, as a result of that executive order, may or may not
have on its authorized hazardous waste program.''
   The ban affects the GSX Services landfill on the shore of Lake
Marion in Sumter County near Pinewood. The site annually accepts
135,000 tons of hazardous waste, such as solvents, acids and other
chemical garbage. About 70 percent of the waste comes from out of
state.
   The GSX site is one of only two commercial hazardous waste
landfills in the Southeast. The other is in Emelle, Ala.
   The head of Florida's Department of Environmental Regulation,
Dale Twachtmann, has written South Carolina officials asking them to
reconsider the decision, according to Raoul Clarke, a department
administrator.
   ``We do recognize that we generate hazardous wastes and we can't
rely on the other states,'' Clarke said.
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Martin said he also sent Campbell a
letter Wednesday advising him of pending state legislation that
would repeal North Carolina's ban on a hazardous waste landfill
until a hazardous waste treatment plant could be built.
   Martin said he could understand Campbell's irritation with other
states' inaction on hazardous wastes.
   ``Would we have been that tolerant had other states been shipping
their hazardous wastes here?'' Martin asked. ``I doubt it. We
probably would have run out of patience sooner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0068 </DOCNO>
