<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--RobberRepents     03-02 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Robber Repents,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Purse Snatcher Turns Himself In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said a man who snatched purses from
two women tried to give them back because his conscience got the
best of him.
   But the women had their doubts.
   So instead, Anthony R. Jackson contacted a bail bondsman, who
told the victims their purses could be picked up at the Oklahoma
City police station, according to authorities. He surrendered a
short time later.
   ``He did call both victims at their homes offering to give them
their property back,'' police Lt. Charles Owen said Wednesday. ``He
told them his conscience was hurting him, but they were both
skeptical of it.''
   Jackson, who told police he snatched the purses Monday, was
booked Wednesday on two complaints of robbery by force and fear.
   Owen said Jackson told police he forged a check belonging to one
of the women and was in the process of forging another when he
decided not to.
   ``That's when he decided to give everything back,'' Owen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
