<FIRST>r a PM-PanamaCocaine     03-02 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama Cocaine,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Sentenced In Panama-U.S. Cocaine Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine people were sentenced for their roles
in an international cocaine ring that authorities said included
shipments of the drug from Panama on U.S. military planes.
   The sentences, handed down Wednesday, ranged from two years'
probation to 24 years in prison. Seven of the nine people were
sentenced to jail.
   The operation was responsible for bringing 600 pounds of cocaine
into the United States over a 13-month period, according to trial
testimony.
   Oscar Smith of New York City, called by authorities the ``New
York connection'' in the smuggling ring, received the 24-year term.
His wife, Regina Smith, got a 12-year, seven-month sentence.
   Julia Thom, a New York friend of the Smiths, was given three
years for helping Mrs. Smith take a delivery of cocaine from
Moultrie, Ga., to New York.
   Jackie Lee Bigelow, a former serviceman whose arrest in Moultrie
last May set off the investigation, received a five-year term. He
pleaded guilty and testified against some of the defendants in the
federal drug trial last fall.
   John W. Turner III, an Army reserve sergeant from Nashville,
Tenn., also was sentenced to five years.
   Others sentenced by U.S. District Judge J. Robert Elliott were
Gary King, 27, of Doerun, Ga., 15 years, eight months, and a $20,000
fine; Herberto Lynton, a Panamanian citizen who was on duty with the
U.S. Army when he was arrested, 15 years, eight months; Brenda
McGee, of Doerun, two years' probation; and Maxine Williams of
Doerun, also a witness at the trial, two years' probation.
   During the trial, the jury was told that the cocaine-stuffed
duffle bags were usually brought into the country from Panama aboard
military transport planes and carried on to New York by soldiers or
impostors in uniform.
   The uniformed couriers sometimes wrote out their own travel
orders so they could fly at government expense.
   The cocaine was brought into the United States through Dobbins
Air Force Base in Marietta, Ga., and airfields in Texas and South
Carolina, according to testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
