<HEAD>Three Schools Agree To Offer Joint Program In Music And Liberal Arts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Qualified students who wish to study music and
liberal arts will be able to take advantage of a joint degree
program announced by the Juilliard School, Columbia University and
Barnard College.
   The schools also announced a cross-registration program that will
open individual courses for academic credit at Juilliard to
qualified students in the other undergraduate schools, and vice
versa.
   ``Musically and academically talented young people have often had
to choose between a liberal arts and a conservatory education,'' the
schools said Wednesday. ``Now they will have the best of two worlds
and an opportunity to thrive as both performers and scholars.''
   The joint degree program will allow students to earn two degrees
_ a bachelor of arts in any major and a master's degree in music _
in five years rather than six.
