<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-FoodAid     03-02 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Food Aid,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Romania Sells Western Aid For Hard Currency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania's embassy declined comment today
on a newspaper report suggesting the East bloc country is secretly
trying to sell off Western shipments of humanitarian food aid for
hard currency.
   Neue Zuercher Zeitung, a conservative Zurich newspaper, reported
it received a letter and copies of documents ``from Romania''
indicating the state foreign trade agency in Bucharest offered ally
North Korea a discounted shipment of 18 staple goods under false
pretenses for payment in U.S. dollars.
   ``The sender accuses Romanian authorities of seizing Western aid
shipments for the starving, freezing population and bartering them
away for hard currency,'' the newspaper said Tuesday in a
correspondent's report from Copenhagen, Denmark. The sender was not
identified.
   An official at the Romanian embassy in Bern said he had not seen
the story and could not comment.
   ``I'm not aware of a problem,'' said the official, who declined
to give his name. ``The embassy concerns itself with other
questions.''
   The newspaper said one document was a fake bill from a Danish
mail order company to the Romanian embassy in Bonn, West Germany,
for an alleged shipment worth about $66,000.
   The fake, dated Dec. 21, listed 18 items including cooking oil,
spaghetti, rice, flour, yeast, sugar, honey, milk powder, butter and
margarine.
   In the second document, dated Jan. 19, the Romanian state foreign
trade company refers to the purported Danish bill and offers the
same goods to North Korea at a 40 percent discount.
   It says a hard currency shortage forced the embassy to resell its
order at a loss, according to the paper.
   The two documents ``raise the suspicion that the Ceausescu regime
is depriving its suffering population of aid shipments from Western
humanitarian organizations and tries to sell them to friendly
foreign countries at deep discounts, but for hard currency,'' Neue
Zuercher Zeitung said.
   President Nicolae Ceausescu's is the most repressive government
in the Soviet bloc and his attempt to rid Romania of foreign debt
has left the country financially strapped. Food and power shortages
are commonplace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
