<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker     03-02 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses Mistrial In `Night Stalker' Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the ``Night Stalker'' murder case
has refused to call a mistrial despite a defense attorney's
complaints of nervous exhaustion.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan told Daniel Hernandez on
Wednesday that stress is ``part and parcel of a death penalty
case,'' and he ordered the trial to proceed.
   Hernandez represents Richard Ramirez, a 29-year-old drifter from
El Paso charged with 13 slayings and 30 other felonies in a series
of attacks that terrorized California in 1985. The killer was dubbed
the Night Stalker.
   Testimony in the trial began Jan. 30, but the case has been in
recess since Feb. 21 when Hernandez, 44, complained of chest pains
and sent a doctor's letter saying he needed up to six weeks to
recuperate from nervous exhaustion.
   The judge noted a long history of requests for postponements by
Hernandez in Ramirez's nearly 4-year-old case. In at least two
previous criminal cases, the courts fined Hernandez for delaying
cases by not showing up and citing stress.
   Tynan said Hernandez failed to present sufficient medical
evidence that his health was threatened by the trial.
   ``Some of us have chest pains. Some have bellyaches,'' said the
judge, a former public defender. ``One of my friends lost part of
his vision, but it came back. Stress is part and parcel of a death
penalty case.
   ``Some of us deal with it better than others,'' he added. The
judge ordered Hernandez's co-counsel, Arturo Hernandez, who no
relation, to assist in the trial. The second lawyer left the
courtroom in July without explanation.
   Outside court, Hernandez said: ``I'm exhausted. I'm tired.'' He
said he would return to court Monday to represent Ramirez.
   But he added, ``I'm not going to kill myself.''
   At Wednesday's hearing, the lawyer had asked for two weeks off to
start a diet and exercise program.
   ``I'd like a month on the Riviera myself,'' said Deputy District
Attorney P. Philip Halpin. ``But the bottom line is, what are we
going to do?''
</TEXT>
