<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0509 03-02 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0509,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Meets With Interior Minister At Retreat Outside Warsaw</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 5th graf, ``The government...'' to ADD
background on Solidarity-government talks. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``But several...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and his
senior advisers met a government team led by Interior Minister Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak today in an apparent bid to overcome obstacles
after nearly a month of talks.
   Government spokesman Pawel Byra said the meeting at the secluded
Magdalenka residence in a forest south of the capital, was ``of a
working character. It is no extraordinary meeting.''
   State radio said a communique would be issued after the meeting.
   Walesa smiled at reporters but declined to answer questions as he
left for the meeting. He has over the past few weeks been traveling
the country pleading with people to hold back protests and give the
talks more time to succeed.
   The unprecedented ``round-table'' talks on seeking a way out of
political and economic turmoil began Feb. 6, with the banned
Solidarity free trade union movement seeking first and foremost to
have its legal status restored.
   The government said it is willing to legalize Solidarity if a
broad agreement is reached on economic and political reforms and on
opposition participation in parliament.
   But several sticking points have arisen, including the form of
elections to parliament.
   Solidarity has accepted the principle that a majority of seats
would be reserved for the ruling Communist Party and its allies, but
wants the rest freely contested.
   Another sore point is the banned Independent Students Association.
   Students have become increasingly restive about the fate of the
organization, known by the Polish initials NZS, especially after
signs that Solidarity and the farmers' Rural Solidarity would be
legalized.
   Communist authorities apparently regard the Independent Students
Association as more of a threat, but Walesa has defended the
organization.
   ``No table can stand on less than three legs. And those three
legs are: Solidarity of workers, NZS and Rural Solidarity,'' he has
said.
   The Independent Students Association was banned along with
Solidarity and other independent groups after the Dec. 13, 1981,
martial-law crackdown.
   The government and opposition also remain far apart on creating a
state presidency that would help guarantee continuation of a
communist system in Poland, on the degree of opposition's access to
the mass media and on the framework for an economic reform program.
   The meetings have occurred as economic unrest continues over
workers' declining wages, high inflation and the $39 billion foreign
debt.
   Walesa was accompanied to the meeting by a platoon of advisers
including historian Bronislaw Geremek, journalist Tadeusz
Mazowiecki, union organizers Zbigniew Bujak and Wladyslaw Frasyniuk,
Roman Catholic church spokesman the Rev. Alojzy Orszulik and Gdansk
bishop Tadeusz Goclowski.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
