<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0819EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AgentOrange     03-02 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agent Orange,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Of Deceased Veterans Receive First Agent Orange Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first of thousands of payments from the $170
million Agent Orange settlement fund have been mailed to the
families of deceased Vietnam veterans who were exposed to the
defoliant in Southeast Asia.
   The 172 checks sent out Wednesday, totaling about $500,000, were
approved by U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein, who oversees the
Agent Orange litigation. The payments averaged about $3,000.
   The payments to survivor families come from a fund that also will
provide money to disabled veterans who were exposed to Agent Orange.
Those payments begin going out at the end of the month.
   About 75,000 applications for payments have been sent out by the
Aetna Life Insurance Co., the fund administrator.
   Families getting checks from Wednesday's mailing may get an
additional check later, afer the total number of eligible applicants
is known and the final distribution of the fund is calculated.
   The money stems from the settlement in 1984 of a class-action
suit against seven manufacturers of Agent Orange, an herbicide
sprayed in Southeast Asia during the 1960s by the U.S. military to
deprive opposing troops of crops and cover.
   Many veterans claimed that exposure to the chemical caused
cancer, birth defects in their children and other illnesses.
   Although the settlement was reached in 1984, payments were not
made until now because of legal challenges and a complex
distribution plan.
   The deadline to request applications for veterans currently
eligible was Wednesday. Veterans who are not disabled now, but
become disabled in the next few years because of illnesses linked to
Agent Orange, can file claims through 1994.
   To be eligible for payment, veterans must be considered totally
disabled under Social Security guidelines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
