<DOCNO> AP890302-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MiamiDrugTests     03-02 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami Drug Tests,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Employers To Test Workers For Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the Miami area's biggest employers are
making the fight against drugs their business.
   Fifty-five corporations and public employers accounting for 16
percent of metropolitan Miami's work force have joined in a campaign
to administer urine tests to job applicants and to current workers
suspected of drug use.
   ``This campaign will tell those entering the work force that if
you use illegal drugs, don't bother applying for a job here,'' Ted
Hoepner, chairman of SunBank-Miami, said Wednesday. ``At the same
time, it offers help to those who may have a problem.''
   Business Against Drugs could be the biggest program of its kind
in the country, Hoepner said. The companies involved represent
137,000 employees.
   The program, sponsored by the Greater Miami Chamber of Commerce,
calls for drug screening as a prerequisite for employment, testing
of employees suspected of drug use and assistance to workers found
to have substance-abuse problems.
   Workers who fail to respond to the assistance programs would face
probable loss of their jobs, Hoepner said.
   Among the employers involved are Burger King Corp. Knight-Ridder
Inc., the University of Miami and Dade County Public Schools.
   Charter members of the chamber can take part in an employee
assistance plan for $18.50 per worker annually and receive a reduced
group rate for the urine tests.
   ``The most effective means of controlling something bad is a
forceful move, something that will create fear in the person,'' said
Dade County Medical Examiner Dr. Joe Davis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0079 </DOCNO>
