<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late-Winter Storm Hits Pacific Northwest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with airport still closed early
today, one traffic fatality, other detail. PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `The
snow ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A late-winter storm brought heavy snow to the Pacific Northwest
early this morning, and rain and thunderstorms were scattered across
much of the South.
   Up to half a foot of snow fell Wednesday evening in the Seattle
area, closing the Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, canceling
school today and snarling traffic. At least one traffic fatality was
blamed on the storm.
   ``Right now we have a half-inch of slush over ice in some areas
and up to an inch or more of snow over ice, no braking at all,''
said Rick Smith, airport fire chief. ``We're continuing to plow the
runways and working to try and get them cleared.''
   The airport remained closed near daybreak today, but officials
hoped to open it later in the day.
   Seattle and Tacoma public schools closed.
   It was the second severe snowstorm of the season for western
Washington and Oregon, where any snow is noteworthy and even a few
inches can paralyze urban traffic.
   ``It's not supposed to do this anymore,'' said Susan Thornton,
spokeswoman for the Snohomish County Public Works Department in
Everett.
   The snow also reduced visibility and hampered traffic in northern
Oregon, where up to a foot was expected to fall.
   Winter storm warnings were in effect for much of Idaho, Oregon,
northwest Washington and higher elevations of central and northern
California and west central Nevada. Snow advisories were posted for
the remainder of Washington, north central Oregon and the Idaho
Panhandle.
   Snow also was falling across the country's northern tier from the
Pacific Northwest to the Great Lakes, but accumulations outside of
Oregon and Washington were mostly no more than an inch.
   Rain fell in much of California, southern Oregon and southwest
Idaho.
   Thunderstorms continued across the Florida Peninsula while rain
stretched from South Carolina to northern Florida, across the
central Gulf Coast and eastern Texas.
   Today's forecast called for snow in the upper Great Lakes,
central Minnesota, Iowa, South Dakota, northern Wyoming, Montana,
northern Idaho and western Washington. Rain was expected in the rest
of the Pacific Northwest, Nevada and all but southeast California.
Rain and thunderstorms were predicted for much of the South from
southern portions of Virginia and West Virginia to much of Florida,
and across to the lower Mississippi Valley and eastern Texas.
   Highs were forecast to be in the single digits from Montana to
Minnesota; in the teens and 20s from the northern Rockies across the
remainder of the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley to the
Great Lakes, northern New York state and northern New England; the
30s and 40s from central New England to North Carolina, the Ohio
Valley, Missouri, northern Kansas, southern Wyoming and the Pacific
Northwest; the 50s and 60s from South Carolina to northern Florida,
the Tennessee Valley, the southern Plains, southern Rockies,
southern Plateau and all but southeast California; and the 80s in
central and southern Florida and the lower Texas Gulf Coast. Highs
elsewhere were expected to be in the 70s.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 24 degrees below zero at
Hibbing, Minn., to 74 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 44 cloudy; Boston 24 windy; Buffalo 13 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 47 foggy; Cincinnati 26 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 19 fair; Detroit 13 fair; Miami 71 foggy; New York 29
partly cloudy; Philadelphia 26 fair; Pittsburgh 20 fair; Portland,
Maine, 22 fair; Washington 32 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck -4 fair; Chicago 19 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
48 cloudy; Denver 27 foggy; Des Moines 17 snow; Indianapolis 24
cloudy; Kansas City 29 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul -1 cloudy;
Nashville 33 fair; New Orleans 57 cloudy; St. Louis 31 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 39 fair; Anchorage 19 cloudy; Las Vegas 62
cloudy; Los Angeles 54 rain; Phoenix 63 cloudy; Salt Lake City 49
windy; San Diego 55 cloudy; San Francisco 50 rain; Seattle 28 snow.
   _Canada: Montreal 14 fair; Toronto 10 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
