<FIRST>r a PM-O'HareFlights     03-02 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-O'Hare Flights,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Staggered United and American Flights Take Effect At O'Hare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two busiest airlines at O'Hare International
Airport began an experiment today in staggering their flight
arrivals in hopes of reducing delays and congestion at the nation's
busiest airfield.
   The Federal Aviation Administration had prodded United Airlines,
which runs the most flights out of O'Hare, and American Airlines,
into working out a solution.
   Under the agreement, neither airline will schedule more than
three arrivals during a two-minute period, and more than seven
arrivals in a five-minute period, said United spokeswoman Sara
Dornacker.
   Ms. Dornacker said she did not know how many flights had
previously been crammed into those time periods.
   In most cases, schedule changes of five minutes or less are
involved in the experiment.
   United will still have 396 arrivals and departures daily at
O'Hare; 240 United flights will be affected by the agreement,
Dornacker said.
   Nearly 37 percent of United arrivals at O'Hare were delayed in
December, the latest month for which figures were available, said
Dornacker.
   Figures from American were not immediately available. American
officials did not return telephone calls.
   The agreement, worked out in December as a two-year experiment,
also forbids either airline from increasing daily arrivals between
7:15 a.m and 10:44 a.m. and between 4:15 p.m. and 8:44 p.m, the
United spokeswoman said.
   ``The purpose of these actions is to reduce the delays now
occuring at O'Hare,'' she said. ``It's one step in a program and we
feel as a company that more work is needed to solve the Chicago
area's congestion problem.''
</TEXT>
