<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GorillaSurgery     03-02 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorilla Surgery,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Zoo Gorilla Undergoes Hernia Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeons put a 20-year-old female gorilla under the
knife to repair a grapefruit-sized hernia that could have been life
threatening.
   ``It went better than anybody could have hoped for,'' zoo
veterinarian Richard Cambre said after the two-hour operation
Wednesday. ``Surgeons are confident this will heal well, and she
won't have any recurrence of the hernia.''
   A team of doctors led by veterinary surgeon Robert Taylor
performed the operation on the anesthetized, 214-pound lowland
gorilla, Bibi. Surgeons stitched Goretex _ the material that keeps
skiers warm _ around the herniated area.
   ``The Goretex will act as a latticework for new fibrous tissue to
grow through and will give a lot of strength to the area,'' Cambre
said.
   By early Wednesday afternoon, Bibi was awake and hungry, but it
will be a month before the animal gets to rejoin her fellow
gorillas; veterinarians don't want to take the chance that some
rough gorilla-play will rip out her stitches.
   The hernia was discovered during an operation for colon disease
in 1986. Doctors removed part of the gorilla's intestines at the
time but feared the risk of infection was too high to repair the
hernia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
