<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Infiltration 1stLd-Writethru a0520 03-02 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Infiltration, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0520,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Thwart Infiltration, Four Guerrillas Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with army identifying guerrillas
as members of PLO faction. Pickup 13th graf pvs, ``Earlier today...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli paratroopers patrolling southern Lebanon
shot and killed four Palestinian guerrillas today who were en route
to attack targets in Israel, the army said.
   A fifth guerrilla escaped, and troops were searching the area,
said a military source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   No Israeli troops were injured, an army spokesman said.
   The clash occurred about three miles north of the
Israeli-Lebanese border in the western sector of Israel's
self-proclaimed security zone, said the spokesman, who cannot be
identified under military regulations.
   ``This was definitely an infiltration attempt,'' he said.
   The spokesman said documents found on the bodies of the
guerrillas identified them as members of the Democratic Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, a radical Marxist faction of the PLO.
   A security source in Lebanon said the clash occurred in the
Israeli-controlled security zone near the Lebanese village of Al
Jibbayn.
   It was the second infiltration attempt attributed to the
Democratic Front since Feb. 23, when Israeli soldiers killed three
Palestinian guerrillas in the six to 10-mile-wide buffer zone.
Israel created the security zone in 1985 when it pulled the bulk of
its forces out of Lebanon after a three-year occupation.
   Israel radio said the guerrillas killed today were armed with
Soviet-made Kalashnikov assault guns, grenades and missiles.
   Maj. Gen. Yossi Peled, head of the army's Northern Command, said
leaflets were also found in the possession of the guerrillas.
   ``The leaflet speaks of carrying out a hostage-taking mission in
Israel,'' Peled said on Israel radio. ``It speaks of military action
to support the political activities of the PLO leadership.''
   Earlier today, the Foreign Ministry gave reporters photocopies of
two Democratic Front identification cards it said belonged to two of
the three guerrillas killed Feb. 23. A ministry spokesman, who is by
tradition not identified, noted that the Democratic Front is a full
member of the PLO.
   Israel has tried to persuade the United States to end a dialogue
it began with the PLO after its chief, Yasser Arafat, said in
December that he recognized Israel's right to exist and renounced
terrorism.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who maintains the PLO will never
give up terrorism, said in an interview published Wednesday that the
U.S. talks with the PLO are ``useless.''
   On Tuesday, U.S. officials met with PLO representatives in Tunis,
where the organization has its headquarters, and asked them to put
an end to all attempts by its guerrillas to infiltrate Israel.
   But the State Department also criticized an Israeli retaliatory
air raid on Tuesday against a Democratic Front post in Lebanon
southeast of Beirut.
   On Wednesday, a State Department spokesman, Charles Redman, said
the U.S. talks with the PLO will continue despite Israel's pleas.
</TEXT>
