<FIRST>r i PM-Spain-Crash     03-02 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-Crash,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter Crashes Into Madrid Neighborhood, Three Crewmen Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Spanish air force helicopter burst into
flames over the capital and plunged into a densely populated
neighborhood today, killing its three crew members but causing no
injuries on the ground, police said.
   The explosion that occurred upon impact sent the front end of the
helicopter hurtling into the empty recess area outside Blas de Otero
high school, said a municipal police official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said the tail landed 180 feet away in a private courtyard.
   ``The students were apparently inside the building, in class,''
when the plane crashed at 1 p.m., he said.
   The police official said firefighters quickly extinguished the
burning wreckage, which was also near a shopping center in the
heavily populated southeast Aluche neighborhood.
   ``There was an explosion, then (the helicopter) started doing
somersaults and the rotor broke loose and then the tail
disintegrated,'' a witness to the accident told Spanish National
Radio.
   An air force spokesman, Cmdr. Julian Fernandez Torregrosa, said
the accident killed the helicoper's pilot, co-pilot and mechanic,
whom he identified as Capt. Alfredo Vidal Montero, 33, Capt. Ramon
Garrido de la Parra, 30, and 2nd Lt. Jose Rodriguez Montero,
respectively.
   Fernandez said the French-built Puma helicopter, which was on a
routine training mission, regularly took part in search and rescue
operations.
   An investigation was launched into the cause of the crash.
   The accident was the second this year involving a military
helicopter.
   On Jan. 18, one crewman died when an army helicopter crashed into
a reservoir near the capital.
</TEXT>
