<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0539,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Provincial Party Chief Arrested in Connection With Ethnic
Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with report that former provincial party
chief arrested, detentions of journalists. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Communist Party chief in the
province of Kosovo has been arrested in connection with recent
ethnic unrest there, the state-run Tanjug news agency said today.
   Police also arrested two directors of the Trepca lead and zinc
mine, the site of a recent eight-day sit-in by ethnic Albanian
miners pressing for political change, Tanjug reported.
   Tanjug said the three ``would be handed over to judicial organs
for further investigation and a possible trial.''
   The former party chief is Azem Vlasi. The mine directors are Aziz
Abrasi and Burhan Kavaja. Vlasi is an ethnic Albanian who headed
Kosovo's party until last year, when he was forced to resign because
of the ethnic tensions.
   Kosovo is a province in the republic of Serbia. Ethnic Albanians
make up about 90 percent of Kosovo's population, and the minority
Serbs say they are persecuted by the Albanians.
   The secretary of Kosovo's communist leadership, Tomislav Sekulic,
today announced widespread arrests of alleged organizers of recent
ethnic Albanian protests, but he did not give names.
   Sekulic also refused to comment on reports that Fadilj Hoxha, a
former vice president of Yugoslavia of Albanian descent, had
defected to neighboring Albania. Hoxha was kicked out of the
Communist Party in 1987 for his alleged support of ethnic Albanian
nationalists. Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said Hoxha
had defected.
   Huge demonstrations by Serbs, which began Tuesday in front of
Yugoslavia's federal Parliament, petered out during a heavy
overnight rain. About 4,000 protesters who had been in front of
Parliament dispersed.
   The arrests came after Lazar Mojsov, a former Yugoslav president,
announced that officials had a document from an ``illegal (ethnic
Albanian) group'' that allegedly detailed plans to destabilize the
province of Kosovo by an armed uprising of ethnic Albanians. Mojsov
warned in an address to Parliament on Wednesday that the unrest
seriously threatens Yugoslavia's unity.
   The session was called to discuss the deteriorating security
situation in the country in the wake of the protests in Kosovo and
counter-demonstrations by Serbs in Belgrade and other parts of
Serbia.
   An Associated Press photographer and a reporter and photographer
from the French news agency, Agence France-Presse, were detained by
Kosovo police this week while covering the unrest.
   Dieter Endlicher, a Frankfurt-based AP photographer, was detained
five hours Wednesday in the provincial capital of Pristina for
taking pictures of military vehicles deployed in the province.
   Endlicher, a West German citizen, was released after his film was
developed and no incriminating shots were found to be on it, he said.
   Helene Popovich, an AFP correspondent from Belgrade and a French
citizen, and Srdjan Ilic, the bureau's photographer, were taken in
for questioning after Ilic photographed a group of Yugoslav army
vehicles near Pristina, the French news agency said.
   Popovich was released after three hours at state security
headquarters, but the whereabouts of Ilic, a Yugoslav national whose
cameras were said to have been badly damaged by a Yugoslav army
officer, were not known.
   Popovich was told by an official of the state security police
that ``some of the foreign journalists in Kosovo would be kicked out
of the province.''
</TEXT>
