<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     03-02 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funeral Held For Girl Whose Death Is Linked To Mandela Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest called for reconciliation
between anti-apartheid groups and Winnie Mandela today at the
funeral of a 13-year-old girl killed in an attack police suspect was
linked to Mrs. Mandela's bodyguards.
   The teen-ager, Finkie Msomi, was killed Feb. 22 at a house in
Soweto when gunmen opened fire on the dwelling and set it alight
with a firebomb. Police have said the attackers may have been
seeking to avenge the slaying of Maxwell Madondo, who worked as a
bodyguard for Mrs. Mandela.
   Anti-apartheid groups have renounced Mrs. Mandela, accusing the
black leader's unofficial bodyguards _ known as the Mandela United
soccer club _ of waging a ``reign of terror'' in Johannesburg's
black township of Soweto.
   The funeral for the slain girl was the second in five days for a
teen-ager whose death has been linked to the Mandela controversy.
Stompie Seipei, a 14-year-old activist from the township of
Tumahole, was buried Saturday. Two members of the soccer club have
been charged in his death.
   News reports have asserted that Mrs. Mandela joined in whipping
Stompie, and three young men allegedly abducted along with him from
a Methodist Church. Mrs. Mandela has denied any wrongdoing.
   About 800 people, many of them schoolchildren, attended a
two-hour funeral service for Finkie Nsomi at St. Margaret's Church
in Soweto, the township of 2.5 million blacks.
   ``We gather here for reconciliation in the eyes of the Lord, not
for revenge,'' said a priest, the Rev. Reimi Makubane. ``We pray for
reconciliation for our own people, for justice and peace for all.''
   Some of the students at the service sang freedom songs, and 200
jogged along a street afterward.
   Mrs. Mandela formed the soccer club in 1986, saying she wanted to
organize activities for black youths living on the streets. But the
group, which grew to as many as 30, became an unofficial force of
bodyguards who seldom played soccer and antagonized members of the
community.
   After speaking about the controvery with her husband, jailed
black nationalist leader Nelson Mandela, Mrs. Mandela said she would
disband the club and move team members from her house. Mandela, the
leader of the outlawed African National Congress, has been jailed
since 1962, sentenced to life on charges of sedition and sabotage.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 28 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
