<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Guatemala 3rdLd-Writethru a0553 03-02 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Guatemala, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0553,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meeting Focuses on Central America Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 6 grafs new updating with Cerezo, Fitzwater comments. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, Bush joined.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush voiced doubts in talks today
with Guatemala's president about the recent Central American peace
agreement that would disband the Contra forces as he mulls keeping
them alive with U.S. aid, Bush's spokesman said.
   Bush told President Vinicio Cerezo the United States is concerned
about the commitment of the ruling Sandinistas to live up to their
promises of democratic reform in Nicaragua in exchange for
demobilizing the 11,000-strong Contra army, said White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater said no decison has been made on what the
administration will propose to Congress when the current $27 million
Contra aid package runs out at the end of this month.
   But he indicated some new humanitarian aid likely will be sought.
In the meantime the Central American presidents still must work out
details of their new peace agreement.
   In the general agreement last month, they said they would come up
with specifics on how to disband the Contras and impose the
accompanying conditions in Nicaragua within 90 days, a deadline that
falls after the Congra aid package expires.
   ``We're reviewing the matter now with a view toward the
humanitarian aid,'' Fitzwater said in his daily press briefing. He
did not mention military aid, saying, ``We would like a diplomatic
solution.''
   Cerezo, speaking to reporters after the session, said, ``We have
talked in the Central American countries about humanitarian aid at
least in this moment'' to keep the Contras organized while Nicaragua
works out conditions to repatriate them.
   U.S. officials have expressed concerns about likely timetables
and enforcement mechanisms by which the Sandinistas will be kept to
their promises.
   Bush, joined by Secretary of State James A. Baker and numerous
aides in his Oval Office session with Cerezo, declined to answer a
question on whether he feels the Contras should be kept together for
a year or so, as has been proposed in some quarters.
   Baker is considering proposing aid to keep the rebel forces
intact while waiting to see if the Sandinistas keep their word,
according to sources quoted in today's Washington Post.
   Cerezo met Wednesday with Vice President Dan Quayle on the same
topics, aides said.
   Cerezo told reporters that Nicaragua should make democratic
reforms _ such as freeing of political prisoners _ before and at the
time of a final agreement to demobilize the Contra forces that have
battled the Sandinistas for more than seven years. But Cerezo was
not specific on what reforms should be made when.
   Cerezo said administration officials ``still have reservations''
about the peace agreement reached two weeks ago by the presidents of
the five Central American nations: Costa Rica, El Salvador,
Guatemala, Honduras and Nicaragua.
   U.S. officials have said that the diplomatic approach should be
given a chance, but that they are skeptical of the Sandinistas'
commitment to live up to their promises unless there are adequate
enforcement mechanisms.
   In the past, the U.S.-funded Contras were said to constitute such
a mechanism.
   Previous peace talks have collapsed in disagreement over what
should occur first _ disarmament of the rebels or internal
democractic reforms in Nicaragua.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega pledged in the agreement last
month to free political prisoners, hold early elections with United
Nations observers, allow opposition parties access to the media and
repatriate the Contras.
   The agreement contained no timetable for such actions, and the
presidents said such details would be in a plan they would work out
by the end of 90 days.
   Cerezo, during a photo session with Quayle, said the Sandinistas
should implement the reforms ``before and at the same time when we
affirm the plans for the Contras' demobilization.''
   Cerezo said he assured Quayle the Contras would disarm ``in an
orderly manner.''
   The vice president also brought up Guatemalan human rights with
Cerezo, said an official, speaking on condition of anonymity and
revealing no further details.
   State Department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said that Guatemala has a continuing pattern of human rights abuses,
and that the government must bring those responsible for politically
motivated crimes to justice.
   Americas Watch, a private human rights group, has said that
Guatemala's record on the rights issue is far worse than the
administration is willing to concede.
   Juan Mendez, the group's executive director, told Congress last
month that Guatemala ``continues to have one of the worst human
rights records in the Western Hemisphere.''
   One State Department official said U.S. officials do not share
that dismal assessment, and that it was unlikely the Americans would
``hit Cerezo very hard on human rights.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
