<SECOND>AM-BRF--Snake Bite,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venom Researcher Bitten By Snake For 148th Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A researcher who maintains 1,000 venomous
snakes for scientific purposes was in serious but stable condition
Thursday after being bitten by a deadly Pakistan pit viper, his
148th snake bite.
   William E. Haast, 78, director of the Miami Serpentarium
Laboratories, was extracting venom from the viper Wednesday when it
bit his thumb, said John Dwan, spokesman for the University of Utah
Health Sciences Center.
   Haast drove himself to the hospital, but doctors were not
immediately able to administer anti-venin because Haast was allergic
to the stock on hand. Another type was flown in from the San Diego
Zoo.
   Dwan said Haast told him it was the 148th time he'd been bitten
by a snake.
   The 40-year-old Miami Serpentarium originated the concept of
importing snakes from around the world to collect their venom. Its
customers include the National Institutes of Health and hundreds of
research and medical laboratories, which use the venom to
manufacture anti-venins.
