<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--DogvsPig     03-02 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Dog vs Pig,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Cleared in Dog-Pig Spat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT LEBANON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Melvin Kelly's dog went after
Anthony Barrera's miniature pig, Barrera brandished a pistol at the
dog, showing ``bad judgment'' but committing no crime, a judge has
ruled.
   District Justice William Ivill on Wednesday dismissed charges
against Barrera, 36, who was charged with recklessly endangering
another person, simple assault and disorderly conduct in the Jan. 31
incident.
   Kelly said he and his wife were caring for a stray dog, a
Siberian husky weighing 40 pounds, when the dog ``got away from me''
and went after Barrera's pig next door.
   Barrera ``started waving'' a pistol at the dog but ``did not
point the gun directly at me,'' Kelly said. But, he said, ``I felt
like I was being intimidated.''
   Neither animal was injured and no shots were fired.
   Ivill said Barrera was on his own property and licensed to carry
a gun. He ruled Barrera was ``preparing to defend his pet from a
trespassing animal.''
   Barrera said he got the gun for protection and the pig because
``I'm asthmatic and allergic to dogs and cats.''
