<FIRST>u a PM-People-Busey 1stLd-Writethru a0421 03-02 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Busey, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0421,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor Continues To Oppose Mandatory Helmet Law Despite Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with physician ridiculing Busey's position; EDITS throughout
to shorten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Busey, his head scarred from a
near-fatal motorcycle crash, says he still opposes mandatory helmet
laws _ a position ridiculed today by a government physician.
   The 44-year-old actor, in his first public appearance since the
crash Dec. 4, said Wednesday he ``could be a vegetable'' if he had
been wearing a helmet.
   Dr. Jeffrey Saks of the Centers for Disease Control's injury
control division said 4,000 motorcycle riders are killed each year
and 360,000 injured. ``Most of the deaths and serious disabilities
are due to head injuries, and ... helmets significantly reduce the
chances of a head injury,'' he said.
   About Busey's continued opposition to helmets, Sacks said, ``I'm
assuming he doesn't have residual brain damage that led to what he
said.''
   Busey said he plans to help raise money to fight helmet laws, as
he did before his accident. During a news conference Wednesday,
Busey's publicists distributed a pamphlet extolling helmetless
riding.
   In the crash, Busey's unprotected head struck a curb, and he
underwent brain surgery to remove two blood clots. He was
hospitalized for two months.
   A scar, starting near the top of Busey's right ear and continuing
to the top of his scalp, was visible underneath his short hair.
   Busey, who won an Oscar nomination as best actor for the title
role in the 1978 film ``The Buddy Holly Story,'' said he favored a
law mandating helmets only for motorcyclists ages 16 to 21. ``I felt
that way before the accident,'' he said.
   In fact, Busey insisted, ``I could have been more seriously
injured'' with a helmet. ``I could have broken my neck if I'd had on
a helmet.''
   Helmets ``cut down your peripheral vision, they cut off your
hearing and they stop your neck from rotating,'' he said.
   Busey looked fit and walked without any visible problems.
Although he said he was suffering some ``post-traumatic amnesia,''
Busey reported that his recovery was nearly 100 percent complete.
   He blamed his accident on excessive speed and an oil puddle. He
has yet to resume riding his motorcycle, which he said has been
repaired.
   Busey had just completed ``Hider in the House'' at the time of
the crash. Another film, ``Howling at the Moon,'' has been put on
hold pending his recovery.
</TEXT>
