<FIRST>u a AM-OfficialEnglish Bjt   03-02 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Official English, Bjt,0965</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official English Remains Controversial Months after Passage in 3
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four months after voters passed ``official
English'' amendments in Colorado, Arizona and Florida, the effect is
far from clear, with supporters and opponents remain split over the
measures' legal meaning.
   In Arizona, a state employee's lawsuit challenging the
constitutionality of the amendment is pending in U.S. District Court.
   The author of the Colorado amendment has criticized the governor
and Denver's mayor for issuing executive orders directing that
bilingual government information still be provided. There's also a
lawsuit filed by opponents pending, seeking to get the measure
thrown out on technical grounds.
   In Florida, the furor has subsided somewhat since a Miami-area
grocery clerk was fired for speaking Spanish in front of customers.
The store agreed to rehire the clerk. And the Legislature has taken
no steps to pass laws to put the ballot measure into effect.
   ``All this law has done is take support away from other issues
that really need it,'' said Dorothy J. Porter, director of the
Colorado Civil Rights Division. ``We should be spending money to
improve relations between the races and I don't think this has done
that.''
   The Colorado measure, which won the approval of 64 percent of
voters, asked simply: ``Shall there be an amendment to the Colorado
constitution to delare that the English language is the official
language of the state of Colorado?''
   Supporters believe that means official government business should
be conducted in English, and say the amendment could be be used as
ammunition in lawsuits aimed at changing private conduct, such as
employers who require Spanish language facility for some jobs. They
say the law is necessary because of complaints from some people that
their rights were being violated because they could not speak a
foreign language.
   Opponents say the law is unclear and unnecessary. They see it as
an attack on their heritage and fear it will force them to renounce
their language and learn English.
   Colorado Attorney General Duane Woodard said, ``I have no idea
what that law means.''
   ``The amendment is very short. It says English is the official
language of Colorado. If that's the case, what about federal laws
that override it?'' he asked. Federal laws limit discrimination
against minorities in such areas as housing and jobs, and
requirement some government documents, such as ballots, to be
multilingual.
   Opponents say there have already been several incidents in which
citizens took the law into their own hands and tried to enforce it.
Porter said there was the public school bus driver in Grand Junction
who ordered children to stop speaking Spanish and the fast-food
restaurant worker who was fired for translating a menu into Spanish.
   But state Rep. Barbara Phillips, who led the campaign to pass the
amendment in Colorado, says those were ``regrettable''
misunderstandings that had nothing to do with official English.
   ``Those things happened before the amendment was passed, and they
will continue to happen,'' she said. ``Our concern is with
government actions. Our amendment was designed to prevent
discrimination, not cause it.''
   Phillips says the measure has been a success because there have
been no major complaints of discrimination since it was passed.
   But she has accused Colorado Gov. Roy Romer and Denver Mayor
Federico Pena, the city's first Hispanic mayor, of violating their
responsibilities by issuing executive orders that bilingual
government information still be provided.
   ``That was the whole purpose of the amendment in the first
place,'' she said. ``Sixty-four percent of the people in this state
said they don't want that. We want to make sure the governor
complies with the constitution.''
   Pena, who issued an executive order warning city officials that
the issue is potentially dangerous, said the purpose of the
executive order was to make sure no one was the victim of
discrimination.
   ``If the sponsors of the English-only initiative find that
troubling, then that means the commitment and promises they made
during their campaign were not correct,'' Pena said. ``During their
campaign, they said the amendment was not to discriminate against
anyone or deprive them of their rights, but only to ensure that some
other language would not be made the official one.''
   Florida's measure passed by an overwhelming majority, even though
it was opposed by most state officials from the governor on down.
The measure empowers the Legislature to implement it, but so far
there has been no enacting legislation. Without such a measure, the
amendment has no legal effect.
   However, the Florida amendment also has caused problems. A
Miami-area grocery store clerk lost his job for speaking Spanish in
front of customers. The store eventually agreed to rehire him
because of negative publicity.
   In Arizona, the official English measure is more specific, but
also contains broad exceptions. It calls for state and local
government actions and documents to be in English, except for
certain cases such as to comply with federal laws, to protect rights
of criminal defendants and victims of crime, and to protect public
safety.
   Within days of passage, a state employee challenged the Arizona
measure's constitutionality in a lawsuit, claiming she feared she
could be disciplined if she spoke Spanish while working. A state
legislator later joined the suit, saying the law could prevent him
from communicating with his constituents in Spanish. The lawsuit is
pending, although the state has asked a judge to dismiss it.
   Phillips said the purpose of official English is not to divide
the community, but to unite it behind a common language.
   ``That's not divisive, that's unity. ... It's the law,'' she
said. ``After all, we won.''
</TEXT>
