<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda-Hunger     03-02 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Hunger,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>20,000 Displaced People Face Starvation, Diseases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic church leaders say 20,000
people displaced from their homes by fighting in northern Uganda
face death from starvation and disease unless emergency food and
medicine are provided soon.
   ``The displaced people are faced with a difficult situation
because they have no food, clothes and medical care,'' the Rev.
Francis Exavi Ocaya was quoted as saying by the newspaper Munno on
Thursday.
   Munno said Ocaya, who works in northern Uganda, was speaking at
Wednesday's opening session of church information officials from
Uganda's 14 dioceses in Entebbe, about 17 miles south of Kampala.
   Bishop Joseph Mukwaya, speaking at the same meeting, appealed to
all Ugandans, regardless of their faith, to send food to the
displaced people, whom he described as ``brothers and sisters in
need.''
   Ocaya said some people had started returning to their villages
after peace had been restored, only to find their homes, crops and
granaries had been destroyed in fighting between President Yoweri
Museveni's troops and the rebels.
   Government troops launched an offensive against remnants of the
rebel Holy Spirit Movement in November. Officials have acknowledged
at least 100,000 people fled the countryside and camped around the
district capital of Gulu, 210 miles north of Kampala.
   Self-proclaimed warrior priestess Alice Lakwena started the Holy
Spirit Movement in 1986. Government troops halted her poorly
equipped warriors' southward march a year later. She fled to Kenya,
but her followers regrouped in northern Uganda.
   During the current campaign, both the government troops and the
rebels have accused each other of committing atrocities against
civilians.
   In December, however, Amnesty International, the London-based
human rights organization, accussed Museveni's soldiers of
indiscriminately killing unarmed civilians, destroying their homes
and setting farms and granaries afire.
   The Holy Spirit Movement is one of 10 groups that have fought
Museveni's 3-year-old government.
</TEXT>
