<FIRST>r w AM-Pesticides     03-02 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pesticides,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Again Seeks Legal Power to Act Faster on Pesticides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency again asked
Congress Thursday for authority to act faster in ordering dangerous
pesticides off the market.
   John Moore, acting deputy EPA administrator, told the House
Agriculture Committee's government operations subcommittee that he
frequently hears remarks, made in a tone of incredulity, about EPA
pesticide decisions such as, ``You want to cancel its use but can't
get around to it for four years?''
   ``We've got to find a process that can be done in real time. The
current process doesn't comport with real time,'' Moore said,
repeating a complaint by the agency that current law permits
excessive delays in regulatory actions.
   Currently, the agency proposes pesticide actions for public
comment, receives comment for a month or two, studies the comments
and comes to a final decision. This can take 15 to 18 months.
   The license-holder _ typically the manufacturer _ may appeal to
an administrative hearing, and then to the federal courts. Though
use restrictions are frequently accepted by manufacturers, orders to
end use are almost always appealed.
   During those hearings, which may last years, the pesticide stays
on the market _ and the hearing officer ``does not build upon what
has gone before,'' Moore said, forcing EPA and all other parties to
start over from square one.
   EPA could declare an emergency and force an immediate end to use,
but the data rarely show a large enough danger to justify it, he
said.
   ``Excuse the pun, but the registrant gets three bites at the
apple,'' the comment period, the agency hearings and the courts,
Moore said.
   The subcommittee and its parent committee included a streamlined
hearing process in a proposed overhaul of pesticide law two years
ago, but set the topic aside as too controversial in last year's
package of changes.
   That package did eliminate one bar to emergency action by
dropping the requirement that EPA buy up inventories when its rare
emergency bans are imposed.
   Rep. George E. Brown Jr., D-Calif., who heads the subcommittee,
and Rep. Pat Roberts of Kansas, the senior Republican member, were
sympathetic to Moore's complaints. Roberts said he soon would
introduce legislation.
   Moore took the opportunity of his testimony to denounce again a
study by the Natural Resources Defense Council released Monday that
said pesticide residues on food pose a significant risk of cancer
for young children. At the time, the agency said it was taking into
account the facts of young diets that the group said it was ignoring.
   Some calls to the agency from parents ``border on hysteria,''
Moore said.
   ``In my opinion the public is being misled by the ominous
rhetoric of these reports. ... It's way out of proportion to
reality.''
   He said a detailed examination of the NRDC work showed that the
group had used in its calculations out-of-date residue and other
data for one pesticide that EPA's independent scientific advisers
judged useless for estimating risk. EPA estimates the risk of this
pesticide, the apple growth regulator daminozide, at only 1 percent
of what NRDC estimates, and half the difference in estimates is
accounted for by the out-of-date data.
   The agency has said it expects in 18 months or so to order a ban
on daminozide, which it has been studying since 1979, because of its
cancer-causing potential.
</TEXT>
