<FIRST>r i AM-Botha     03-02 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha Says He'll Return at the End of March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha, still
recovering from a stroke suffered six weeks ago, said Thursday he
plans to return to work at the end of March.
   Botha, 73, gave no indication of possible retirement plans
despite the widespread speculation that he may soon step down.
   He returned to his Cape Town office Thursday and met with several
Cabinet members, including acting president Chris Heunis and F.W. de
Klerk, Botha's successor as leader of the National Party and the
heir apparent to the presidency.
   Botha's office visit was the first indication he has resumed
working since he suffered a stroke Jan. 18. Officials have said
Botha has not participating in the day-to-day activities of the
government while he has been recuperating at his home in Wilderness,
210 miles east of Cape Town.
   ``I intend to return from my private residence ... the week after
the Easter weekend (March 25-26),'' Botha said in a statement. ``I
will then resume my task as state president.''
   Botha's only public appearance since his stroke was television
footage two weeks ago that showed his left arm shaking noticeably.
   Some observers have questioned whether Botha's health will hamper
his ability to function as president and even some members of the
National Party have suggested he retire.
   ``South Africa wants F.W. de Klerk as president,'' Hendrik
Schoeman, a former Cabinet minister and member of Parliament said
Wednesday night when introducing de Klerk at a National Party rally.
``For the sake of the National Party, President Botha should now
give F.W. de Klerk a chance,'' Schoeman said.
   Botha's policies of gradual race reform have stalled in recent
years, and some National Party members have hinted a new leader is
needed even though de Klerk appears to endorse most of Botha's
agenda.
   Both men call for limited reforms that will increase the rights
of blacks, but preserve segregated white neighborhoods and schools
and keep political power in the hands of the white minority.
   Botha was chosen as prime minister in 1978 and became president
in 1984 when South Africa adopted a new constitution.
</TEXT>
