<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Stonehenge     03-02 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stonehenge,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monument to be Closed at Solstice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stonehenge, the ancient monument that is thronged
with latter-day Druids every summer, will be closed to the public
for the summer solstice, it was announced Thursday.
   English Heritage said it was taking the action reluctantly on the
advice of police, who have had to cope with thousands of rowdy
celebrants each June.
   ``It is like closing Westminster Abbey at Christmas,'' protested
Rollo Maughfling, Arch Druid of the Glastonbury Order.
   Francis Golding, head of English Heritage properties, said
Stonehenge would probably be closed for 24 hours.
   In the last 10 years, the problems associated with convoys of
travelers have disrupted the Salisbury plain. Last year 1,300 police
were involved in a $700,000 operation to escort and restrain the
celebrants, who call themselves hippies. There were 67 arrests and
10 injuries on the day of the solstice.
   Wiltshire Chief Constable Walter Girven said any convoys of
travelers entering the county would be warned there was nowhere for
them to go. If they persisted in gathering near Stonehenge they
would be arrested, he said.
   ``Unfortunately over the last 10 years there has been an
increasing amount of violence occuring at the occasion of the
solstice,'' Girven said.
   ``The solstice has been used as an excuse for moving into the
county, camping illegally, committing offenses and creating a
considerable amount of disturbance to the inhabitants of Wiltshire.''
   Maughfling called the decision ``a gross violation of religious
freedom.''
   He said his group intended to seek a judicial review and take the
issue to the European Commission of Human Rights.
   They were also taking legal advice on whether a private action
against the authorities would be possible.
   ``We and other members of the Druid Orders of Great Britain feel
that a great mistake may well be made here and leading to much worse
consequences than keeping the monument open,'' Maughfling said.
   ``Closing Stonehenge, we feel, will only add fuel to the fire,
inciting further unnecessary violence at even greater cost to both
tax and ratepayer.''
</TEXT>
