<FIRST>r w AM-GeneticCarp     03-02 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Genetic Carp,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA to Review Proposal for Tests of Genetically Altered Carp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal by Auburn University to field test
genetically altered carp will be reviewed later this month, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   The proposal will be taken up March 22-23 at a meeting of the
department's Agricultural Biotechnology Research Advisory Committee,
along with other business on the panel's agenda.
   Alvin Young, director of the department's Office of Biotechnology
and executive secretary of the committee, said the experimental carp
have already received a growth hormone gene from trout and will soon
be ready for testing in an outdoor pond.
   The purpose of the gene is to help the fish reach full market
size in less time with less feed. Such experiments could help fish
farmers, satisfy consumer demand for more fish, and shed new light
on transferring genes into fish, he said.
</TEXT>
