<FIRST>u i PM-US-ElSalvador 1stLd-Writethru a0554 03-02 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-El Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0554,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Denies Report That It Met With El Salvador Rebels</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with State Department denial. TRIMS. No
pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper said today that State Department
officials have held secret talks with guerrillas in El Salvador in
an attempt to resolve the conflict in that country. U.S. officials
denied the report.
   Spain's leading daily El Pais also said State Department
officials and representatives of the leftist Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front, or the FMLN, will meet again this week in
Washington. The paper based its report on unidentified sources in El
Salvador and Mexico.
   ``The United States does not have talks or negotiations with the
FMLN,'' State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in
Washington. The United States supports El Salvador's government in
its 9-year-old war with the front.
   El Pais correspondent Antonio Cano quoted the sources as saying
the talks began in January and were the first between U.S. officials
and the guerrilla leaders since the war began. It said the talks had
substantially influenced recent developments in El Salvador.
   But the report said the talks did not solve the conflict, in part
because of President Bush's lack of a clear foreign policy in
Central America.
   Redman said the United States maintains contacts with all
political parties in El Salvador. He noted that a leftist
presidential candidate, Guillermo Ungo, has been in Washington this
week for talks with administration officials and congressional
leaders.
   The paper said the first contacts took place in Washington from
Jan. 20-23 between middle-level guerrilla leaders and members of the
Bush administration and Congress. The paper said the guerrillas
promised they would no longer consider U.S. interests in El Salvador
military targets.
   State Department officials said the El Pais report apparently
referred to an appearance by FMLN representatives at the department
six weeks ago when they dropped off a peace proposal. The department
officials read the document, asked for some clarifications, then
told the visitors they should discus it with the Salvadoran
government, said the officials, who asked not to be identified.
   They said there have been no contacts with the FMLN since then.
</TEXT>
