<DOCNO> AP890302-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NavyDeath     03-02 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Death,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Makes Significant Changes Since Recruit's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Significant changes have been made at the
Navy Rescue Swimmer School since a 19-year-old recruit drowned a
year ago Thursday, Navy officials say.
   Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki of Appleton, Wis., died when
instructors forced him back into a training pool at Pensacola Naval
Air Station and held his head under water after he had panicked
during a rescue drill and climbed out of the water.
   Other students were ordered to face away during the episode and
sing the national anthem.
   A stressful exercise that was being conducted at the time has
been banned, and instructors now are prohibited from touching
students. Strickter safety monitoring also was ordered.
   ``To some extent, they must have learned their lesson,'' said
Mirecki's sister, Lynn Johansen of Appleton.
   She and other relatives have filed a $20 million claim against
the Navy, accusing officials of intentionally inflicting emotional
distress by first reporting the drowning as an accident and of
negligence in letting Mirecki continue the class even though he had
been diagnosed as having a phobia about being held under water.
   The claim is intended to make the Navy more responsive, Ms.
Johansen said. ``We're just trying to make sure that it doesn't
happen again.''
   Criminal charges were filed against six Navy men. One instructor
was convicted of negligent homicide and sentenced to 90 days in the
brig, while four other people were given administrative punishments
of fines or rank reductions.
   The officer in charge of the school was acquitted of dereliction
of duty in a separate court-martial, but his commanding officer was
given a letter of reprimand just prior to retiring.
   Since the changes were made last June, 187 students have
graduated with 18 more scheduled to complete the course Friday, said
Capt. J.W. Dickson, who became commanding officer of the Naval
Aviation Schools Command after Mirecki's death.
   ``We think the quality of the students is every bit as good,''
Dickson said.
   But attorneys at the court-martials had argued that now-banned
practices, including physically forcing scared or tired students to
participate in drills, was necessary for realistic training to make
students ready for emergencies. Navy rescuers must be prepared to
jump from hovering helicopters to rescue pilots downed at sea.
   No real assessment can be made until new graduates are required
to make rescues, Dickson said.
   But most have only recently reached their duty stations, and
statistics show only about half of the Navy's 1,200 rescue swimmers
make a single rescue every three years, Dickson said. The rest of
the time they do other work while awaiting an emergency call.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
