<FIRST>r w AM-CableTV-Telephone     03-02 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable TV-Telephone,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Says Most People Have More Trouble with Cable TV than with Phones</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most people have more trouble with their cable
television service than with their telephones and they think the
situation would improve if competitors were allowed into the cable
TV market, according to a telephone industry poll released Thursday.
   The United States Telephone Association said the poll of 6,435
people backed its contention that local phone companies should be
allowed to compete with cable television operators. Congress this
year may consider allowing phone companies into the cable TV arena.
   Sixty-eight percent of those contacted believed their cable
service would improve if competitors were allowed to enter the cable
market. Typically, local governments only allow one cable franchise.
   Fifty-seven percent of the respondents said local telephone
companies should be able to provide cable services.
   ``Findings indicated that phone service is much more reliable
than cable service, with interruptions in cable service occurring
twice as often as interruptions in phone service,'' said Kennan
Research &amp; Consulting Inc., which conducted the poll by telephone
during the week of Oct. 31. ``Survey data indicates consumers view
their local telephone company as more responsive and accessible to
their service needs.''
   It said four out of every five households reported problem-free
phone service during the previous year, while nearly half the cable
households had their cable service interrupted during the same
period.
   The poll said that while 30 percent of the respondents said that
being able to choose between cable providers would not affect them
at all, 53 percent felt it would be to their advantage. Only 4
percent predicted negative effects from the competition.
   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 1.2 percentage
points.
   Forty-nine percent said their cable service was out during the
previous year, while 48 percent said it wasn't. Seventy-one percent
said their service was restored promptly, and 7 percent said it was
not restored promptly.
   Nineteen percent said their phone service was out of order during
the same period, while 80 percent said it wasn't. Eighty-seven
percent said their phone service was restored promptly, while 13
percent said it wasn't.
   Sixty-eight percent said they believed their cable company would
provide better service if it had competition, while 17 percent said
they believed it would not.
   Fifty-seven percent said their local telephone company should be
permitted to offer cable TV service in competition with the local
cable TV company. Twenty-eight percent said the phone company should
not be allowed to compete.
</TEXT>
