<FIRST>r w AM-Tower-Goldwater     03-02 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower-Goldwater,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Barry Goldwater accused John
Tower's Senate critics of hypocrisy Thursday, claiming ``there'd be
no government'' if everyone guilty of drinking or womanizing was run
out of town.
   ``People who live in glass houses should never throw rocks,'' the
always outspoken Goldwater told reporters after he met with
President Bush and discussed the troubled Tower nomination.
   ``There are some strange things going on down in that old
Senate,'' said the former Arizona senator, who retired in 1986 after
a career spanning more than three decades.
   Goldwater, who served with Tower on the Armed Services Committee
and chaired the panel in 1985 and 1986, said that no one had yet
come forth with proof that Tower had ever been incapacitated with
alcohol.
   ``Yeah, he drank. I had a few with him,'' Goldwater said. ``That
he chased a few women? Hearsay. I don't give a damn whether he did
or not. But I don't like the Senate working on innuendo, on facts
that have never been proven.''
   ``I've been around this town a long, long time. If they chased
every man or woman out of this town who shacked up with somebody
else, or gotten drunk, there'd be no government. So I think that the
Senate better start looking at facts.''
   The 1964 Republican presidential candidate voiced particular
displeasure with Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee and a leading opponent of Tower's nomination.
   ``I'm amazed at Sam Nunn. I'm one of those Republicans who had
been hoping he'd run for president. But to come out as he has,
against Tower, and only on the basis of drinking, I can't believe
it.''
   ``I'm frankly shocked that they could allow partisan politics
creep into this thing,'' he added.
   ``I would say there's a lot of hypocrisy in it,'' Goldwater said.
   ``If they start investigating 100 members of that Senate as
they've investigated John Tower, you people are going to have a
ball,'' Goldwater told reporters outside the White House.
</TEXT>
