<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Jews 1stLd-Writethru a0606 03-02 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Jews, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0606,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refuseniks Stage Protest, Accuse Kremlin of Human Rights Violations</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT typo in ``being.'' SUBS 9th graf, `The
document...' to note that document is not legally binding. Pickup 10th,
`The uniformed...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Jews staged their first protest in half a
year Thursday, gathering within sight of the Kremlin to accuse their
government of violating international human rights agreements by
barring their emigration.
   A police major repeatedly told about 20 protesters they were
breaking the law by holding a demonstration without a permit, but
uniformed and plainclothes officers who swarmed around the steps of
Lenin Library made no move to halt the half-hour protest.
   ``We're hearing many words about how we are observing the Vienna
human rights agreements, but they are not being fulfilled in
deeds,'' said protest organizer Yuri Semenovsky, who has sought for
three years to obtain a Soviet exit visa. ``We have been deceived.''
   Semenovsky and other refuseniks who unfurled signs and banners at
6 p.m. on the library steps within sight of the Kremlin's towers
said Soviet Jews had not demonstrated for six months because of
hopes raised by increased emigration figures and the Vienna
negotiations that resulted in a 35-nation agreement on human rights
in January.
   ``But for us, nothing has changed,'' Semenovsky said.
   Although more than 20,000 Soviet Jews were allowed permission to
emigrate in 1988, Semenovksy said 80,000 others had their
applications refused.
   He and the other demonstrators are members of a Jewish refusenik
group called the ``Poor Relatives,'' who say their departure is
prevented because of a Soviet requirement that family members
certify that they have no financial claims on a would-be emigrant.
He said 700 people were members of the ``Poor Relatives.''
   The group says such a requirement violates the Vienna agreement
adopted by the Soviet Union, which mandates that ``acts or omissions
by members of the applicant's family do not adversely effect the
rights of the applicant (to emigrate).''
   The document was adopted in January at a meeting attended by
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and envoys from 34
other nations, including the United States. It is not legally
binding, but the 35 nations who adopted it undertook to abide by it.
   The uniformed police major, who gave his name as Lebedev, walked
up to the demonstrators seconds after they displayed their banners
and signs, one of which called for a world ``without missiles and
refuseniks.''
   Lebedev said authorities in Moscow's Kiev district had refused to
grant the protesters' request for a demonstration permit, and that
the city had outlawed all demonstrations at the library and nearby
Kalinin Prospekt, once the frequent site of protests by dissidents.
   ``I call on you to end this illegal demonstration,'' Lebedev said.
   But Semenovsky replied he had never received an answer to his
request from city authorities for a demonstration permit, which he
said he sent by registered mail 12 days ago.
   He told Lebedev that President Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``has said
that everything that's not forbidden is to be allowed.''
   Lebedev repeated his demand at least 10 times that the refuseniks
end the protest, then he walked away.
   That treatment was in sharp contrast to the way police dealt with
a refusenik demonstration in August, which was broken up in two
minutes. Seven Jews who were denied permission to emigrate were
sentenced to up to 10 days in jail or fined for holding an
unauthorized protest.
   Semenovsky said two other protests, held in September, also ended
with the arrest of participants.
   Semenovsky said the refuseniks decided it was time to protest
again because a new law easing emigration requirements has not
appeared. He said refuseniks were promised such a law would be
enacted last month by Yuri Reshetov, a Foreign Ministry official who
received a group of Jews in January.
   In February, Soviet authorities allowed 2,236 Jews to leave,
according to the Geneva-based agency that helps resettle them. That
figure marked the second straight monthly drop in emigration, but
was still sharply above the monthly average in 1988, according to
the Intergovernmental Committee for Migration.
   The number of Jews allowed to emigrate soared to an eight-year
high of 3,510 in December, and dipped to 2,616 in January. Last
year's exodus of Soviet Jews totaled 20,082, the most since 1980.
</TEXT>
