<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Eclipse     03-02 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eclipse,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partial Eclipse Next Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sun will be partly obscured for millions of
Americans next Wednesday morning, the U.S. Naval Observatory
reported Thursday.
   Residents of Hawaii and about the western two-thirds of the
United States and Canada will be able to see the eclipse, which will
be at its maximum at about 10 a.m. PST, according to the
Observatory's calculations.
   For residents of Alaska, about 70 percent of the sun will be
covered during the eclipse, while less of the sun will be obscured
for viewers in other areas, according to astronomers at McDonald
Observatory of the University of Texas at Austin.
   The eclipse will occur as the new moon passes between the sun and
the Earth.
   The amount of sun covered will vary widely, the Texas astronomers
reported. From the 70 percent obscured in Alaska it will diminish to
about half in the Pacific Northwest, with 30 percent covered along a
line from San Diego in southern California to Winnipeg in Canada.
   At the easternmost limit of the eclipse, along a line from
central Texas through Missouri, Illinois and Michigan, only a small
dent will appear in the sun.
   Even though a portion of the sun is obscured during the eclipse,
astronomers and eye doctors warn against looking directly at the
phenomenon. Staring at the sun for more than a couple of seconds can
burn and scar the retina, potentially leading to distorted vision or
blindness.
   For groups of people who want to watch, astronomers recommend
using a pinhole mirror system to cast an image of the sun on an
indoor wall.
   This can be done by cutting a one-quarter inch hole in a piece of
black paper and taping the paper over a small mirror.
   Open a south-facing window and use the mirror to reflect the
sun's image on the opposite wall of the room. Modeling clay can help
hold the mirror in place. The room should be as dark as possible.
   The spot reflected on the wall is am image of the sun and it will
show every aspect of the eclipse.
   It is a good idea to experiment with the paper and mirror ahead
of time, trying out different sizes of holes in the paper. A large
hole makes for a fuzzy but bright image, while a smaller hole makes
it sharp but dim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Menuhin     03-02 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Menuhin,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noted Violinist Says Lessons of Nazi Atrocities Apply Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violinist Yehudi Menuhin, in Bonn to be
honored for promoting German-Jewish reconcialition, urged the world
Thursday to condemn current atrocities as well as Hitler's slaughter
of European Jews.
   ``We will not draw the lesson so long as we condemn only the
Nazis, who should be condemned,'' he said. ``If we condemn them, we
must condemn by the same token many of the acts which are happening
now in many other countries.''
   As examples, the 72-year-old musician mentioned ``torture and
slaughter'' in parts of Africa, Central America and South America,
and events in the Middle East.
   Menuhin, dressed in a gray cardigan, well-worn trousers and a
fading paisley tie, spoke to The Associated Press in a cramped
lounge during a break in rehearsals for a concert he will conduct
Saturday.
   Soon after World War II, Menuhin came to Germany on a benefit
concert tour that included a heart-wrenching performance for fellow
Jews and other survivors of the Bergen-Belsen death camp.
   He also played for Germans, Americans and concentration camp
survivors in Berlin in 1947, two years after the war ended.
   On Sunday, West Germany's Societies for Christian-Jewish
Cooperation will give him the Buber-Rosenzweig medal for those
performances and his efforts to bring about dialague between Jews
and Christians. The award, established in 1968, commemorates the
Jewish philosophers Martin Buber and Franz Rosenzweig.
   Menuhin, who was born in New York City and became a British
citizen in 1985, spoke at length of the relationships among crimes
against humanity from various historical epochs.
   ``I think that, however tragic, terrifying, unspeakably horrible
the Third Reich was, that a nation that feels guilty, a nation that
knows it has committed a crime is a nation better for that,'' he
said.
   ``The only sad, sad thing today is that the crimes are going on,
not in Germany, but in many other parts of the world. And until we
can look upon them as crimes of mankind collectively, until we can
rise above the condemning of one people, we will never overcome
these crimes.''
   ``Unless we can ... join our neighbors in the act of sharing and
of protecting our children's future, we will all be destroyed,'' he
said.
   ``I feel we are living now in the last epoch of the caveman,
although I sometimes feel the caveman couldn't have been as horrible
as the modern man because he probably only killed to survive like
the animals do.''
   In his book ``Unfinished Journey,'' published in 1977, Menuhin
recalled the performances he gave at Bergen-Belsen.
   ``The inmates of the camp had been liberated some weeks earlier,
the prison huts burned down and the ex-prisoners transferred to the
adjoining SS barracks, which had, among other comforts, a theater,''
he wrote.
   ``Men and women alike, our audience was dressed in army blankets
fashioned by clever tailors among them into skirts and suits. No
doubt the few weeks since their rescue had put a little flesh on
their bones, but to our unaccustomed eye they seemed desperately
haggard, and many were still in hospital.''
   He wrote of facing ``boos, hisses and imprecations'' when he went
to the Deuttel Center, a Berlin camp for displaced persons in 1947,
but of winning over the audience with the declaration:
   ``We Jews don't beg; we work! We are the best cobblers, the best
tailors, the best doctors, the best musicians. That's what it means
to be a Jew! I have come to Germany to restore that image, to show
how false was Hitler's caricature.''
   Menuhin's benefit tours also took him to Italy, Austria, Hungary,
Britain and the Netherlands in 1946 and 1947. During the war, he
played more than 500 benefit for Allied soldiers and the Red Cross.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Solomonson     03-02 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solomonson,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Humphrey Son-in-Law Claims He's Broke, Seeks Delay in Prison Term
for Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son-in-law of the late Vice President
Hubert H. Humphrey has asked for a 30-day delay in beginning his
four-year prison sentence for fraud, claiming he can't afford to
appeal without assistance.
   C. Bruce Solomonson told U.S. District Judge Edward J. Devitt on
Wednesday that he owes his attorneys more than $250,000 and does not
have the $10,000 to buy a transcript of his December trial.
   He is seeking formal pauper status so the court will pay for an
appeal, including transcripts and future attorney's fees.
   Solomonson was convicted Dec. 7 on eight counts of mail fraud and
one count of bank fraud. The charges involved the diversion of more
than $1.5 million from his two Edina insurance businesses for
personal use.
   He is scheduled to report Monday to the federal prison in Duluth.
   Devitt requested additional written briefs from attorneys before
he rules on the matter.
   In court documents, Solomonson claims that he has a negative net
worth of $273,000. The net worth of his wife, Nancy, is set at
$99,400. In early 1987 the Solomonsons showed a combined net worth
of $861,700.
   Under questioning by Assistant U.S. Attorney Hank Shea,
Solomonson said he has been selling some of his property and
financial holdings to pay bills and debts.
</TEXT>
