<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Block     03-02 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Block,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marvin Block, Pioneer in Treatment of Alcoholism, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Marvin A. Block, a pioneer in persuading
physicians to treat alcoholism as a disease, has died. He was 86.
   Block, a retired professor at the State University of New York at
Buffalo, lectured and wrote widely on alcohol abuse and addressed
medical groups in Europe, Africa and Australia as well as throughout
the United States.
   He died Tuesday at Buffalo General Hospital.
   Block was on the board and was vice president of the National
Council on Alcoholism and also formed the New York State Council of
Committees on Alcoholism.
   His 1952 article ``Alcoholism _ the Physician's Duty'' was
acclaimed as one of the two most significant scientific articles
published during that year by the American Academy of General
Practice. In November 1953, he was appointed chairman of the
American Medical Association's Subcommittee on Alcoholism, designed
to educate physicians about the disease and to convince them that
alcoholism is an illness they were obliged to treat.
   After three years of intensive effort, the AMA House of Delegates
voted to declare alcoholism ``an illness which properly falls within
the purview of medical practice'' and urged all doctors and
hospitals to treat its ``victims.''
   Block's 1967 book, ``Alcoholism _ Its Facets and Phases,''
explained in non-technical language why people drink excessively and
helped guide family members of alcoholics.
   He retired from SUNY-Buffalo in 1973 as a clinical assistant
professor of medicine, but continued his private internal medicine
practice until a few months before his death.
   He is survived by three sisters. Funeral services were set for
Friday in Buffalo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-StatelyHome     03-02 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stately Home,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman Plans Something Different for Mansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoiated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bachelor who bought one of England's great
mansions has unusual plans for the 300-room estate on 83 acres:
he'll live in it.
   Most owners of stately homes turn them into inns or tourist
attractions. Wensley Haydon-Baillie said Thursday he has saved
Wentworth Woodhouse ``for posterity'' and will make it his private
residence.
   He bought the 18th-century mansion in south Yorkshire from his
distant cousins, the Fitzwilliam family, for an undisclosed price.
   The Fitzwilliams nearly sold the lease last year to a developer,
but when they learned of his plans to put a golf course on the deer
park and turn the building into a hotel, the deal fell through.
   ``I am delighted to be able to secure the future of Wentworth
Woodhouse,'' Haydon-Baillie said in a joint statement with the
Fitzwilliam Estate, which represents the family.
   Haydon-Baillie, 45, is an economist and chairman of two
companies, Optical and Medical International PLC, and Porton
International PLC.
   To provide for the restoration and maintenance of the house,
Haydon-Baillie has created an endowment trust, said the statement.
   Lord Montagu of Beaulieu, chairman of English Heritage, the
state-funded body for preserving historic houses and monuments,
described Wentworth Woodhouse as ``one of the greatest historic
houses in England.''
   ``The securing of its permanent future as part of Britain's
future will be welcomed by all as of outstanding importance,'' said
Montagu, who acted as an adviser to the deal.
   The statement said WentWorth Woodhouse, with its 660-foot-long
facade, is the largest classical house in England. The building near
Rotherham in central England is unique in that the back facade is in
the Baroque style.
   Haydon-Baillie told The Daily Telegraph he was unsure how many
rooms his new home had, saying ``it depends what you count as a
room.'' The estate official said there were about 300 rooms.
   In calling it home, Haydon-Baillie will follow in the footsteps
of the Earl of Strafford, minister to King Charles I, and the
Marquess of Rockingham, prime minister at the time of America's
Revolutionary War.
   The statement hinted Haydon-Baillie won't keep the mansion
entirely to himself, saying he intends to allow ``appropriate access
... when and where possible'' after restoration.
   The public will also be allowed to walk through the estate's 83
acres of parkland, which is owned by a Fitzwilliam family trust.
   Following post-World War II legislation enacting heavy taxes on
inherited wealth, many owners of stately homes have been forced to
open them to the public. Some turned over houses to the National
Trust charity while others turned them into museums, with commercial
attractions on the side, and lived in one corner.
   The Historic Houses Association, Britain's largest group of
private owners, doesn't criticize the commercial ventures.
   ``Using houses in this way is a way that collections can stay
together and be viable under private ownership,'' said Victoria
Merrill, executive secretary of the group. ``The great thing is to
have them used.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
