<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH HAVEN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average snowman is naked, once you
stop to think about it, except for maybe an old hat and scarf.
   But a naked snowman that appeared Monday on a Long Island lawn
was also more anatomically correct than usual.
   Someone complained to the North Haven Village Hall, but by the
time Building Inspector Albert Daniels went out Tuesday and got to
the specified address _ which was not made public _ the offending
body part was gone.
   ``It either melted or was knocked off,'' Village Clerk Janice
Hines said Thursday. ``We didn't see it with our own little eyes.''
   Ms. Hines said she doesn't believe the snowman violated any
village ordinance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call it ``The Fish Who Saved Pittsburgh, Part
II,'' but this tragedy wasn't a movie.
   Fire broke out in the office of Tony Pokora, an aide to the city
controller, who works in the City-County Building downtown.
   Pokora said the fire Sunday apparently was started by an
electrical malfunction. It ruined carpeting and scorched a wall.
   But Pokora said the flames also shattered his aquarium, and the
water doused the fire.
   That was the end of Pokora's two fish.
   ``They gave their lives to save the City-County Building,''
Pokora said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. CLOUD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was, of course, a better mouse
trap. But also featured were a gnat-combating hat, a parent alarm
and a special set of chopsticks for those who find it tough to get a
grip.
   The creations were among 199 entries Wednesday at a fair of the
Minnesota Student Inventors Congress as finalists were picked for
this summer's statewide competition.
   Fourth-grader Kyle Parsons, 10, designed a parent alarm for his
cousin, Eric, and other friends who get in trouble watching
television or playing home video games. The alarm is tripped when
unsuspecting parents step on air tubes placed underneath a rug
outside the door.
   ``You can hide and fake like you're asleep until they leave so
you don't get in trouble,'' Kyle said.
   Gnats irritate fifth-grader Leslie Northam. ``They just bug me a
lot,'' she said.
   So Leslie, 10, invented a ``gnat hat'' _ a baseball cap featuring
a glove attached vertically to its top. According to Leslie, this
will draw the pesky insects out of her hair because gnats hover
around the highest point.
   Sixth-grader Steph Anderson's ``Easy Chopsticks'' invention was
one of 12 picked to advance to the statewide Minnesota Inventors
Congress.
   ``Me and my brother can't use chopsticks,'' said Steph, 12, who
attached chopsticks to a clothespin to hold them together tightly.
This allows people to eat without getting mad, she said.
</TEXT>
