<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1938EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BennettConfirmation     03-02 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett Confirmation,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Casual Users Must Be Included in War on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett indicated Thursday that he
envisions a war on drugs against casual users as well as drug
dealers, but he assured senators that he would defend the civil
liberties of Americans.
   ``The so-called casual user ... has to realize he's an accessory
to everything that's going on in this country,'' Bennett, nominated
to become the first director of National Drug Control Policy, told
the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   During the second and final day of his relatively uncontentious
confirmation hearings, Bennett said he intends to enlist the help of
such people as television writers and commissioners of sports
leagues to change the country's attitude on drug use.
   He said he's bothered by sports announcers introducing a player
on the field who has just returned from his third round of treatment
for drug abuse.
   ``How many shots do you get to still continue to appear as a role
model to children?'' Bennett said.
   Committee Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., scheduled a
committee vote on the nomination next Thursday. Only two senators _
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and Paul Simon, D-Ill. _ have indicated
they might vote against Bennett.
   The former education secretary called for a hard line against
drug traffickers and defended his support of school officials who
set up metal detectors and take other measures to control violence
and drug abuse in the schools.
   ``This war is not for delicate sensibilities,'' he said. ``This
is tough stuff.''
   However, he assured Biden that he is concerned about civil
liberties.
   ``They are the base. They are the cement. They are the anchor.
They sometimes cause us difficulties in this war ... but these are
the ends. ... You can't destroy the fabric of the country in order
to defend the country,'' Bennett said.
   As education secretary, he said, ``I resisted some who were
arguing for universal (drug) testing of the students'' because ``I'm
sensitive to the Constitution, the Fourth Amendment,'' which
prohibits unreasonable search and seizure.
   Biden raised anew the issue of whether there should be a ban on
semiautomatic, combat-style weapons used by drug traffickers. The
subject was debated extensively Wednesday when Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., pulled out a memo Bennett wrote a year ago urging
consideration of legislation limiting access to such weapons.
   Bennett told Biden on Thursday that he believes there's a
correlation between easy access to weapons and the violence of drug
dealing.
   ``I don't think there's any doubt about it,'' Bennett said, but
added, ``You still have to take the people's right to bear arms
seriously.''
   A host of drug-related shootings and the killing of five
California schoolchildren earlier this year have prompted calls for
a ban on semiautomatic assault weapons with high-capacity ammunition
clips. President Bush has said he opposed such regulation, while
Mrs. Bush supports a ban.
   Bennett resisted taking a position on any specific legislation
pending completion of a comprehensive national drug control strategy
_ due six months after his confirmation. But he left open the
possibility that he ultimately may disagree with Bush's position.
   ``The fact that it's been spoken about by the president does not
mean it's off the table,'' he said, adding that Bush agrees with
that view.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., urged Bennett to examine closely the
State Department's method of certifying countries overseas for
foreign aid. That department determines whether those countries have
done all they can to battle illegal drugs, and the list of certified
countries issued Wednesday included Colombia, the base of several
notorious drug traffickers.
   Specter said the certification of Colombia is ``a shock to me
because Colombia has refused to negotiate with us an extradition
treaty, in effect saying the drug cartels have taken over the
country.''
   Bennett said he would look into the certification procedures, but
defended the inclusion of Colombia on the list.
   ``The government (in Colombia) has made some efforts,'' he said.
``We know what happened to the supporters of the extradition treaty.
They got most of the members of the Supreme Court blown away by
machine-gun fire.''
   Specter said continuing foreign aid to Colombia probably would
encourage its anti-drug efforts, ``but I think we have to expect
some results. ... Colombia is really in a state of anarchy. How they
can qualify for foreign aid is a mystery to me.''
   The hearing concluded after representatives of the League of
United Latin American Citizens and the Association for Supervision
and Curriculum Development offered testimony critical of Bennett's
nomination, although a LULAC spokesman said he believed committee
approval of Bennett was inevitable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
