<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1810EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     03-02 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Optimistic After Meeting With Interior Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Thursday
he is ``a bigger optimist'' after a meeting with the interior
minister to iron out problems that have arisen during three weeks of
negotiations.
   The meeting came at a key moment in the unprecedented talks that
began Feb. 6 between the government and the opposition aimed at
reaching national accord and legalizing the banned Solidarity union
after more than seven years.
   Participants agreed the talks' various committees and
subcommittees should speed up their work, allowing the final plenary
meeting to be held in late March, a joint statement said afterward.
   Then, ``the process of implementing key decisions ... could start
as soon as possible,'' the statement carried by the official PAP
news agency said.
   The two sides have brought their positions closer together in
many areas although ``controversies and difficulties'' remain, the
statement said.
   The meeting of Walesa and Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak
began at 9:30 a.m. at the Magdalenka governement villa in a forest
south of Warsaw and ended after 6 p.m. Walesa appeared weary but
satisfied on his return to Warsaw.
   ``We were successful with some things and less successful with
others,'' he said. ``But I hope that we are moving forward.''
   He said the session left him, ``a bigger optimist than before I
went to it.''
   According to the Solidarity leader, the meeting with Kiszczak was
``to remove some barriers ... some political obstacles.'' He
declined to elaborate.
   Walesa was accompanied by advisers including historian Bronislaw
Geremek, journalist Tadeusz Mazowiecki, union organizers Zbigniew
Bujak and Wladyslaw Frasyniuk, the Rev. Alojzy Orszulik and Gdansk
bishop Tadeusz Goclowski.
   Among those on the government side with Kiszczak were Deputy
Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula, Sports Minister Aleksander
Kwasniewski and Communist Party Politburo member Janusz Reykowski.
   After three weeks of talking, both sides appear eager for
agreement.
   Walesa, faced with a rising tide of worker and student
discontent, has been traveling the country pleading with people to
hold back protests and give the talks three more weeks to succeed.
   Although the talks have yielded progress in some areas, including
agreement in principle to legalize Solidarity and the farmers'
independent union Rural Solidarity, several sticking points have
arisen, including the form of upcoming elections to the Sejm, or
parliament, this year.
   Solidarity has accepted the notion that a majority of seats would
be reserved for the party and its allies _ as a temporary step on
the road to full democracy _ but it wants the rest to be freely
contested. The party would like to see the remaining seats assigned
to opposition-independent candidates.
   Another sore point is legalization of the banned Independent
Students Association. Students are increasingly agitated about the
fate of the group, known by the Polish initials NZS.
   Authorities seem to regard NZS as a greater threat than
Solidarity or Rural Solidarity, especially in light of the Communist
Party's weak support among youth, and have mounted a strong
propaganda campaign against the group in the past week based on
protests in Krakow.
   A group of Krakow students met with local Solidarity activist
Mieczyslaw Gil on Wednesday and asked him to speak up for NZS at the
meeting with Kiszczak.
   At a meeting with students Wednesday at Warsaw University, Walesa
said he would defend NZS. ``No table can stand on less than three
legs. And those three legs are: Solidarity of workers, NZS and Rural
Solidarity,'' he said.
   NZS was banned along with Solidarity and other independent groups
after the Dec. 13, 1981, martial-law crackdown in Poland.
   The two sides also remain apart on creating a state presidency
that would help guarantee continuation of a communist system in
Poland; on the degree of opposition's access to the mass media; and
on the framework for an economic reform program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
