<FIRST>r a AM-Pilecki     03-02 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilecki,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former College President Capable of Returning to Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college president who resigned after two male
students accused him of sexual assault continues to draw a $63,000
salary while on extended salary, despite being certified capable of
returning to work.
   Former Westfield State College President Francis J. Pilecki plans
to appeal the doctor's ruling, according to officials at Fitchburg
State College, where Pilecki worked after leaving Westfield.
   Pilecki, 55, was examined by a doctor at the request of the
school's faculty union and was judged fit to return to work,
Fitchburg spokesman Michael Shanley said.
   Pilecki went on sick leave in 1987 and has exhausted the benefits
he was entitled to as a professor. Faculty members complain that now
his pay is depleting a college ``sick bank,'' which was created by
deducting days from each employee's unused sick time and pooling
them for the use of colleagues suffering from extraordinary ailments.
   Under the appeal process, Pilecki will be examined by three
doctors, one of his choice, one selected by the college and another
agreed upon by the school and Pilecki.
   A grand jury indicted Pilecki in 1986 and at trial he was found
innocent of the sexual assault charge leveled by one student. The
remaining charges were dropped after a settlement was reached in a
civil lawsuit brought by the other student.
