<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ComputerChips     03-02 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Chips,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Trade Group Urges New Effort in World Semiconductor Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electronics industry group said Thursday it
was urging large-scale re-entry by U.S. companies into the global
market for computer memory chips.
   The initiative, which could involve outlays of billions of
dollars to regain a significant share of a market that up to now has
been largely conceded to the Japanese, was announced by the board of
the Semiconductor Industry Association
   ``A stable and reliable source of DRAMs (dynamic random-access
memory chips) is essential to meet the critical technology needs of
the U.S. electronics and defense industries,'' the group said in a
statement.
   It added that ``re-entry of the U.S. semiconductor industry into
large-scale DRAM production is important to the nation's economic
and security interests.''
   Gordon Moore of Intel, the board's chairman, told a news
conference that the initiative represented ``a significant and
important change from the level of rhetoric we've had previously.''
   The action called for developing ``a plan and structure for
recommended collective efforts'' by the U.S. semiconductor industry.
   Asked whether that could mean formation of a consortium on the
model of Sematech, Moore said ``collective efforts could well
involve something like consortia.''
   The board of the association, which is based in Cupertino,
Calif., also approved a resolution saying ``we request that access
to the Japanese semiconductor market be among the highest
administration trade priorities.''
   It complained that the Japanese are still failing to comply with
market-access provisions of the September 1986 U.S.-Japanese
Semiconductor Agreement, under which Tokyo agreed to boost American
companies' share of the Japanese semiconductor market.
   ``We express deep concern that foreign participation in the
Japanese market may be declining from already depressed levels,''
the U.S. electronics group said.
   In April 1987 the U.S. government imposed $300 million in tariff
sanctions against Japanese computers, power tools and televisions.
Seven months later, $135 million of the sanctions were lifted after
the Japanese stopped dumping low-priced computer chips in the United
States and third countries.
   In addition to Intel, other companies represented on the
Semiconductor Industry Association board are Advanced Micro Devices,
AT&amp;T, Digital Equipment, Harris, Hewlett-Packard, IBM, LSI Logic,
Micron Technologies, Motorola, National Semiconductor, Rockwell,
Texas Instruments and VLSI Technology.
</TEXT>
