<FIRST>r a AM-Busey-Reax     03-02 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Busey-Reax,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Busey Sharply Criticized For Opposition To Motorcycle Helmets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gary Busey was sharply criticized by an
injury control authority Thursday for continuing to oppose
motorcycle helmets even after receiving a serious head injury in a
motorcycle crash.
   ``Mr. Busey is darn lucky to even be alive to make the statements
he makes,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Sacks, a medical epidemiologist at the
injury control division of the U.S. Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta.
   ``I'm assuming that he doesn't have residual brain damage that
led to what he said,'' Sacks said.
   Each year, 4,000 people are killed in motorcycle accidents and
360,000 injured seriously enough to require medical care, Sacks said
in a telephone interview.
   Busey, who said he plans to help raise money to fight mandatory
helmet laws, met reporters Wednesday for the first time since
receiving a serious injury Dec. 4 that required brain surgery to
remove two blood clots.
   Busey said that if he had been wearing a helmet he could have
broken his neck.
   Sacks said, ``I'm reminded of how people say wearing a seat belt
may be dangerous because maybe I'll get thrown clear of a car that
gets crushed if I don't wear it.
   ``I think the same kind of logic applies here. There may be rare
instances where wearing a helmet or wearing a seat belt may do harm,
but in the vast majority of situations they're going to save lives.''
   Sacks said ``the case is clear, compelling and overwhelming that
helmets reduce head injuries not only in motorcycling but also for
many sports and even for bicycling.''
   In July, Dr. Frederick Rivara of the University of Washington in
Seattle reported that it costs an average of $25,764 to care for a
motorcyclist hospitalized for injuries sustained on a motorcycle.
   Rivara studied 105 hospitalized motorcyclists and found that
public funds covered more than 63 percent of their $2.7 million in
medical costs.
   ``Several studies have shown that a very high proportion of
motorcyclists lack insurance to pay for their medical care, which
means taxpayers pay for it,'' said Sacks.
   Busey ``may well be able to afford his medical care and see that
he gets the best, but such is not the case for many of those who
will suffer a serious head injury for which we, the public, will
have to pay,'' Sacks said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
