<DOCNO> AP890302-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     03-02 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little Progress in Talks Between North Korea, South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea and North Korea failed
Thursday to set terms for an unprcedented meeting between their
prime ministers, but both sides agreed to try again in April,
officials said.
   The five-member delegations exchanged hostile statements after
North Korea refused to withdraw demands for an immediate halt to
annual joint U.S.-South Korea military exercises.
   They agreed to meet again on April 12.
   ``Korea showed no sincerity at all in considering our just
proposal for an end to the exercises,'' North Korea's chief
delegate, Paik Nam Jun, said after the meeting.
   The Seoul delegation canceled a scheduled news conference and
chief delegate Song Han-ho, said he had ``nothing to add'' to the
meeeting, which he described as ``self-explanatory.''
   The meeting held at this border village, 35 miles north of Seoul,
was a repeat of the Feb. 8 talks, which collapsed after the
communist delegation made the same demands.
   Paik said there would be no progress toward a meeting between
presidents of the two nations unless Seoul agreed to cancel the
maneuvers. Paik said the military exercises were preparation for a
nuclear attack on the communist nation.
   He said South Korea could hold reduced exercises, but without
U.S. participation, and he said any American military units en route
to South Korea for this year's maneuvers should turn back
immediately.
   Song has said the exercises, known as ``Team Spirit,'' are
defensive and no threat to North Korea.
   ``I urge that your side discuss procedural matters in a sincere
manner for the sake of the early realization of a South-North
high-level officials' meeting,'' he said.
   The ``Team Spirit'' exercises have been conducted annually since
1976 to test joint military preparedness in the event of a North
Korean attack. North Korea invaded South Korea in 1950, starting a
three-year war.
   The two nations, archrivals since the division of their land,
have made efforts recently to improve relations, although neither
side so far has been willing to make substantial concessions.
</TEXT>
