<FIRST>r i AM-Havel     03-02 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Havel,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators in Hungary Nominate Havel For Nobel Peace Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 demonstrators rallying in
downtown Budapest on Thursday demanded the release of jailed
Czechoslovak playwright Vaclav Havel and said they would nominate
him for the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
   The protesters in Voeroesmarty Square denounced human rights
abuses in neighboring Czechoslovakia.
   Police did not interfere in the peaceful rally, which has only
recently become permitted in Hungary.
   Writer Gyoergy Konrad compared the banning of Havel's books and
his jail sentence to Iran's death threat against Salman Rushdie for
his book ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``The Czech government must free Vaclav Havel from prison, and
the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize should be given to him!'' one speaker
said to the cheers of the assembled crowd. He said organizers of the
rally would send the nomination to the Nobel committee in Norway.
   Havel was convicted last month on charges of incitement and
obstructing police for his role in a January rally in Prague, and he
was sentenced to nine months in jail. The January rally honored Jan
Palach, a student who set himself afire to protest the Soviet-led
invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
   Organizers read a letter addressed to the Czechoslovak Embassy in
Budapest calling on the government in Prague to adopt political
reforms similar to those under way in Hungary and Poland.
   ``A government that imprisoned a man who was taking flowers to
the place where Jan Palach died cannot have a future in present-day
Europe,'' the speaker said.
   Pictures of Havel were pinned to loudspeaker cables throughout
the square.
   Speakers also read letters sent to demonstration organizers by a
Czechoslovakian human rights group and by Havel's wife, Olga.
   She thanked the protesters for their ``show of solidarity'' with
her husband and with others who ``have been imprisoned or are
persecuted for their views.''
</TEXT>
