<FIRST>r a AM-People-Getz     03-02 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Getz,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jazz Great's Celebrity Status Not An Asset In Divorce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associates Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The celebrity status of Grammy
Award-winning jazz saxophonist Stan Getz is worth little because of
his ill health, and his ex-wife is not entitled to any payment for
it, a judge has ruled.
   In a decision rendered last month and made public Thursday, state
Supreme Court Justice Nicholas Colabella denied a motion by Getz's
ex-wife, Monica, that his celebrity status constituted marital
property.
   Getz gained gold record status with his 1966 hit ``The Girl from
Ipanema.''
   According to the court papers, Getz, 60, suffers from liver
cancer, lymphoma and cirrhosis of the liver.
   Getz's physician, Avram Cooperman, testified that Getz probably
has two years to live and ``it is unlikely plaintiff will be able to
pursue his livelihood as a performer in any substantial way.''
   Colabella's ruling came more than a year after Getz was granted a
divorce from his wife of 31 years in a trial in which the couple
traded allegations of adultery and abuse.
   Getz, an admitted alcoholic, testified that his wife put
Antabuse, a drug used in treating alcoholics, into his food without
telling him, causing him to become violently ill. A person consuming
alcohol with the drug can suffer nausea and headaches.
   Mrs. Getz, 54, testified she administered the drug because she
loved him.
   Colabella ruled that Mrs. Getz did not sacrifice a medical career
to help her husband, as she testified, and that she was entitled
only to equal distribution of marital property, including the sale
of their $1.8 million Tarrytown estate, property in Spain and
royalties due for records made 1956, when the couple wed, to 1981,
when Getz filed for divorce.
   Getz is currently an artist in residence at Stanford University,
receiving $45,000 a year.
</TEXT>
