<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     03-02 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 25 killed in Tamil-Sinhalese Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 25 people were killed in
disputes between Tamil guerrillas and Sinhalese extremists as Sri
Lankan and Indian forces prepared an offensive against the
separatists, military officials said Thursday.
   Military forces were preparing to flush out Tamil guerrillas
hidden in jungle caves after Monday night's massacre of 38 Sinhalese
civilians, the government announced Thursday.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam, the largest Tamil separatist group, were responsible
for the mass murder of men, women and children in Welikande, located
100 miles northeast of Colombo.
   The Tigers have denied they were responsible for Monday's
massacre or two others that occurred over a 16-day period last
month. A total of 81 Sinhalese villagers, including 29 children,
were shot, stabbed or hacked to death in the three attacks.
   Wijeratne said the Tigers, pushed out of the northern Jaffna
peninsula by Indian peacekeeping troops, had moved south and were
hiding in rock caves in the dense jungles near areas the massacres
occurred.
   He declined to give details of the joint Indian-Sri Lankan
offensive against the Tigers, which he said would be ``one of the
biggest flushing-out operations'' ever seen in the country.
   ``The military strategies are being worked out by the commanders
of both armies,'' he said.
   Tamil guerrillas were blamed for 12 of the 25 killings in the
past 24 hours, while Sinhalese extremists were responsible for six
deaths, officials said Thursday, speaking on condition of anonymity.
Indian troops shot and killed one Tamil militant and it was not
known who was responsible for the deaths of six others, suspected to
be Sinhalese extremists.
   More than 8,500 people have been killed since the Tamil
insurrection for an independent Tamil state started in 1983. Most of
the victims have been Sinhalese civilians.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people. They say they are discriminated against in jobs,
education and culture by the mostly-Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise
75 percent of the population, and hold most top government and
military jobs.
   Indian peacekeeping troops have been deployed in Sri Lanka since
July 1987 to help mediate an end to the Tamil insurgency, provoking
a Sinhalese-militant backlash.
   Sinhalese militants have killed more than 1,500 people, mostly
government supporters, in their campaign against government efforts
to end the Tamil insurgency. They claim the government makes too
many concessions to Tamil separatists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     03-02 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Local Officials In Kosovo Detained In Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested three local
officials and several other people accused of inciting unrest by
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province, authorities and news reports
said Thursday.
   The arrests followed widespread protests against planned
constitutional changes that ethnic Albanians fear will limit their
autonomy in the southern province, which borders Albania.
   The official Tanjug news agency said authorities arrested Azem
Vlasi, one of the most popular Communist Party leaders among ethnic
Albanians in the province, and two directors of a mine whose
workers' strike helped set off the wave of protests. The report did
not say when they were detained.
   Tomislav Sekulic, the secretary of Kosovo's Communist leadership,
announced Thursday that police began arresting an unspecified number
of ethnic Albanians who allegedly organized the recent protests
there.
   Officials in the republic of Serbia, of which Kosovo is an
adminstrative part, have claimed that the protests were orchestrated
by alleged Albanian separatists whose ultimate aim, they say, is for
the region to secede from Yugoslavia in order to join neighboring
communist Albania.
   Serbia claims it needs closer control over Kosovo in order to
protect the Slav minority there which alleges constant persecution
and harassment by ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the
region's population.
   The situation in Kosovo, where emergency measures were introduced
Monday in an attempt to prevent possible intercommunal clashes
between ethnic Albanians and Slavs, appeared to have returned to
normal on Thursday.
   The strikes that have plagued the region for the past two weeks
ceased as authorities ordered about 23,500 employees in essential
services back to work.
   Serbia's ambitious Communist party boss, Slobodan Milosevic,
vowed on Tuesday at a counterdemonstration by over 500,000 Serbs in
Belgrade that organizers of the recent ethnic Albanian protest and
strikes in Kosovo would be ``punished and arrested.''
   Vlasi, 41, an ethnic Albanian who headed the provincial party's
ruling Politburo from 1986 to 1988, was the chief opponent of
Milosevic's push for more centralized government.
   For his consistent opposition to Serbia's policies towards Kosovo
he was voted out of the country's 165-member policy-setting Central
Committee. He is still a member of Kosovo's Central Committee.
   Also detained were two directors of the Trepca lead and zinc
mine, Aziz Abrasi and Burhan Kavaja, the state Tanjug news agency
reported.
   The mine was the scene of an eight-day sit-in last week by over
1,300 ethnic Albanian miners who protested planned changes in the
constitution which would bring Kosovo under tighter control of
Serbia.
   The miners agreed to come out of their pits only after three
leading Kosovo officials, including the current provincial party
boss Rahman Morina, resigned.
   The trio, although ethnic Albanians, are considered supporters of
Milosevic's policy of seeking tighter Serbian control of the
province.
   A brief Tanjug dispatch said that Vlasi, Abrasi and Kavaja had
been arrested ``on the basis of data indicating that by their
activities in November 1988 and February 1989 they have committed
crimes punishable under Yugoslav laws.''
   The three ``would be handed over to judicial organs for further
investigation and possible trial,'' Tanjug said.
   In November, up to 100,000 ethnic Albanians demonstrated in the
provincial capital of Pristina, protesting Vlasi's ouster from the
Kosovo Politburo as demanded by Serbian leaders.
   The direct reason for Vlasi's arrest was believed to be his
secret visit to the Trepca mine protesters.
</TEXT>
