<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sudan     03-02 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sudan,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Says Soviets Involved In Sudan Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has conveyed a U.S. request
that Ethiopia press Sudanese rebels to allow free passage for
international food convoys to avoid mass starvation, a senior
American diplomat said Thursday.
   Kenneth Brown, deputy assistant secretary of state for Africa,
also urged the embattled Sudanese government to sign a cease-fire
with the rebels so food supplies can get to as many as 2 million
needy people in government-controlled areas.
   Brown spoke to a joint session of the House Select Committee on
Hunger and the subcommittee on Africa, which adopted a resolution
calling on the administration to enlist Soviet help in resolving the
Sudan crisis.
   The resolution, and a similar one adopted by the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, also urged the administration to reassess its
aid to Sudan unless the government facilitates food deliveries and
negotiates peace with the rebels.
   Brown told the hearing Secretary of State James Baker III is
aware of demands by members of Congress that the State Department
appoint a special envoy to mediate between the Ethiopian-backed
rebels and the U.S.-backed government.
   ``That may well be the way to go,'' Brown said, ``but right now
it would not have the effect we want.''
   The State Department will not take any action until the
government crisis is resolved in Sudan, he indicated. The Sudanese
military has given Prime Minister Sadiq Mahdi an ultimatum to sign a
proposed cease-fire agreement with the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army.
   The military did not say what it would do if Mahdi failed to
comply, but Mahdi threatened to resign next week unless the army
promises not to overthrow him and leaders of trade and professional
unions pledge not to strike.
   The SPLA, predominantly Christian, has been fighting for six
years for economic and social concessions from the Moslem-dominated
northern government.
   Critics have accused the government of a plan to starve the
southerners to death, whether in rebel-held areas or in refugee
encampments in the central sector and around Khartoum.
   The State Department, which officially attributes the problem to
government inefficiency, has privately expressed increasing
frustration with the government's neglect of southern refugees in
areas it controls.
</TEXT>
