<FIRST>r w AM-SovietEmigres     03-02 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Emigres,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Reviewing Refugee Policy Because of Numerous Soviet Applicants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday it is
reviewing its immigration policy in order to accommodate the large
number of Jewish and other applicants from the Soviet Union.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman said 13,000 Soviets arrived
in Vienna during the four-month period starting on Oct. 1 and the
vast majority have requested resettlement in the United States.
   Many of these individuals have already proceeded to Rome where
they may make formal refugee applications, he said, adding that no
one is being denied entry to the United States.
   ``As of Jan. 31, some 3,400 individuals were awaiting their
refugee interviews in Rome,'' he said. ``An additional 1,850 were
approved and pending departure to the United States.''
   He said the overall backlog at the end of January was less than
7,000.
   The administration is reviewing its refugee policy and examining
several options to address the increase in Soviet emigration as well
as other refugee issues, he said.
   ``We will consult with the Congress when we have specific actions
to propose,'' he added.
