<FIRST>r w AM-Long-TermCare     03-02 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Long-Term Care,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Needs Can Be Met</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Health Insurance Association of America
said Thursday the private sector can meet the demands of the
country's long-term health care needs with a minimum of government
involvement.
   The association released two surveys it says show the insurance
industry can meet long-term care needs at a cost that most Americans
are willing to pay.
   Long-term care services, which cost about $50 billion annually in
1987, are expected to grow to $120 billion in 2018 as the U.S.
population ages, the association estimated.
   In one of the surveys, the association determined that the number
of companies offering coverage for long-term care has grown sixfold
over four years, from 16 in 1984 to 105 last year.
   Since 1986, the number of policies sold has risen from 150,000 to
more than 1.1 million as of the end of 1988, the association said.
   Another survey, conducted by the University of Maryland's Center
on Aging, found that 60 percent of those polled said
government-funded long-term care programs should be restricted to
the most needy. However, three-quarters said they would favor the
government helping people buy private long-term care coverage, the
survey said.
   The survey polled 1,003 adults living in residential households
in the continental United States. They were questioned by telephone
last year between Oct. 13 and Nov. 28.
</TEXT>
