<FIRST>r i AM-China-Cartoon     03-02 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Cartoon,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Television to Continue Showing U.S. Cartoon Despite Criticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beijing TV bowed to popular demand and will
continue showing the American cartoon program ``The Transformers,''
even though legislators criticized it as too violent and commercial,
a newspaper said Thursday.
   The People's Daily said the station decided to keep ``The
Transformers'' on the air after conducting a survey of viewers.
   Last month 20 members of the National People's Congress, China's
legislature, urged a ban on the cartoon, saying ``the absurd
ideological content of `The Transformers,' especially its promotion
of war as something good, will poison the next generation.''
   The lawmakers also said the program contains ``disguised
advertising,'' and called for a ban on ``transformer'' toys, robots
that can be altered into cars, planes and other shapes.
   Toy robots modeled after characters in the cartoon are now hot
items in stores despite prices ranging up to $270 per set _
equivalent to a Chinese worker's annual wage.
   The cartoon is shown in translation in Beijing and Shanghai, and
several publishing houses have issued picture books of characters
from the program, which features good robots in battle against their
evil counterparts.
   The newspaper quoted a TV station official as saying the station
attaches importance to the advice of the legislators, but that they
found the cartoon is popular amoung young viewers and many people
consider it helpful for developing a child's intelligence and
imagination.
   Shanghai's Xinmin Evening News said the cartoon was full of
``wisdom, enthusiasm and advice'' to young viewers ``about the
distinction between justice and hegemony, kindness and bellicosity.''
</TEXT>
