<FIRST>r w AM-DetroitNewspapers 420   03-02 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers, 420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit JOA Foes Ask Supreme Court to Delay Newspapers' Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court was asked Thursday to delay
the partial merger of The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press to
give opponents of the business agreement time for further appeal.
   Attorneys for Public Citizen, a Washington advocacy group founded
by Ralph Nader, said in their motion a delay is justified because
they have ``a strong chance of success in their petition'' asking
the Supreme Court to consider the case, which would be filed within
30 days.
   The motion was filed with Chief Justice William Rehnquist on
behalf of Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press, a coalition of
newspaper readers and advertisers who have been battling the
proposed agreement.
   Bill Schultz, an attorney for Public Citizen, said the court
likely would decide in June whether to hear the case. If the court
accepts the appeal, a final decision on the newspapers' joint
operating agreement could come as late as next spring, Schultz said.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
last week rejected opponents' request for a rehearing. The court
ruled the newspapers' joint operating agreement could go into effect
late Monday or afterward.
   Under the proposed agreement, an exemption to anti-trust laws
under the Newspaper Preservation Act, the News and the Free Press
would combine their business and production departments while
maintaining separate news and editorial operations.
   The profits from the combined newspapers would be split 50-50 for
most of the 100-year life of the agreement.
   Attorneys for the newspapers said they would file an early
response to the motion.
   The owner of the News, Gannett Co. Inc. of Arlington, Va.,
declined comment on the opponents' motion. A spokesman for the Free
Press' owner, Knight-Ridder Inc. of Miami, was unavailable for
comment.
   In their motion, the opponents argued the case was important
because the precedent it sets ``will determine the fate of
newspapers in the 25 American cities that have competing daily
newspapers.''
   They also argued the case would have an impact on the extent to
which a court can review administrative actions by federal agencies.
   The newspapers proposed the agreement in 1986 shortly after
Gannett purchased the News.
   Then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved the anti-trust
exemption last year, and it has since survived a federal district
court challenge and an appeal.
   Knight-Ridder has said lack of a joint operating agreement would
force it to close the Free Press.
</TEXT>
