<FIRST>r a AM-Cheerleader-Surgery     03-02 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheerleader-Surgery,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNLV Student Who Captured Hearts Has Bone Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A university cheerleader who has waged a
dramatic battle against cancer returned to class Thursday, 24 hours
after ``the worst pain she's ever felt'' in surgery to save bone
wracked by years of radiation.
   Doctors say they will know within a month whether the hourlong
surgery endured by Valerie Pida succeeded in restoring blood flood
into bone in both her legs.
   She hobbled home from the City of Hope Hospital in Los Angeles on
crutches Wednesday night and was back in class Thursday at
University of Nevada-Las Vegas.
   ``How she does it, Lord knows,'' said her father, Bob Pida. ``She
hopes that her courage will inspire others.''
   Ms. Pida, now 21, was diagnosed as having Hodgkin's disease at
age 13.
   She underwent a life-saving but painful bone marrow transplant at
City of Hope in early 1987. Doctors told her she had no chance of
living without the transplant and a 20 percent to 30 percent chance
of survival with it.
   Las Vegans contributed more than $150,000 to help defray costs
and her brother was the donor.
   Wednesday's surgery was needed because eight years of radiation
and other therapy had blocked the blood flow into certain areas of
the femur or thigh bone, in both legs, effectively killing the head
of the bone. Doctors drilled holes in the bones in an effort to
restore blood flow.
   Pida said his daughter refused general anesthesia or spinal tap
to block the pain, opting for local anesthetic.
   ``She has bad feelings about being put to sleep,'' Pida said.
``She said it was the worst pain she's ever felt.
   ``But she's been through so much pain in her life, she probably
doesn't realize how much she went through. She said later she must
have broken the nurse's hand she was holding.''
   Pida said doctors told Valerie that if she continues to have pain
in a month, they will know the surgery failed. The next step would
be to replace the bone with plastic parts.
   The second anniversary of the marrow transplant _ considered a
significant date in the success of the procedure _ is a few weeks
away.
</TEXT>
