<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Massacre     03-02 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Massacre,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Blame Leftist Rebels For Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guerrilla's confession and a captured
rebel communique showed that insurgents were responsible for killing
an emerald dealer and 18 other people at a ranch this week, police
said Thursday.
   The emerald dealer, Gilberto Molina, was reputedly a vehement
anti-communist who allegedly organized death squads to kill peasants
who sympathized with guerrillas.
   Authorities say Molina was the target of two previous rebel
assassination attempts.
   National police said they captured one of the approximately 50
guerrillas who were disguised as national policemen when they showed
up at Molina's ranch on Monday.
   The police have not allowed reporters to see a rebel communique
that they say points to insurgent involvement in the slaying, or to
interview the alleged guerrilla said to belong to the Colombian
Revolutionary Armed Forces.
   Killed along with Molina were 14 of his bodyguards, his chief of
security, a business partner of Molina's, a musician and Molina's
chauffeur, national police said in the communique issued Thursday.
   The attackers showed up at Molina's ranch at 2 a.m. Monday saying
they were searching for a reputed drug trafficker, Gonzalo Rodriguez
Gacha.
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration says Rodriguez is one of
the country's biggest drug traffickers. Leftist guerrilla groups
have said Rodriguez helped Molina organize right-wing death squads.
   Within 24 hours of the massacre two communist leaders were slain
in Bogota in what newspapers in the capital said was revenge for the
massacre. The two were Teofilo Forero, the secretary of Colombia's
communist party, and Antonio Stelo Pineda, a member of the party's
central committee.
