<FIRST>r a AM-AlienTransport 1stLd-Writethru a0598 03-02 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alien Transport, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0598,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Day In The Life Of A Shuttler: Sending His `Cousins' East</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf, `And on ...' with additional
arrests.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Luis Hernandez put three ``cousins' on
Eastern Airlines Flight 80, a red-eye bound for New York via
Atlanta. A little later he boarded six more.
   ``Oh, they're my cousins, too,'' he told a Los Angeles Times
reporter. But he also admitted shuttling illegal aliens.
   In all Tuesday night, Hernandez boarded 12 ``cousins,'' young men
arriving in twos and threes, most carrying no luggage. Some held
grocery bags filled with belongings. All spoke Spanish.
   They were bound for a better life in New York, using Eastern
Airlines as what immigration officials call an unknowing conduit in
a transcontinental smuggling operation.
   Those 12 apparently made it to their destination. They were
luckier than 69 suspected illegal immigrants from Central and South
America who boarded the same flight just 24 hours before only to be
apprehended by Immigration and Naturalization agents.
   Earlier that same day, 79 others who had taken Flight 80 were
picked up when the plane stopped for refueling in Atlanta.
   And on Wednesday, agents arrested 27 allegedly illegal aliens
aboard a Piedmont Airlines flight during a morning stop in
Charlotte, N.C., between Phoenix and New York.
   By Thursday, 206 suspected illegal immigrants being smuggled east
on airlines had been taken into custody at airports in Los Angeles,
Atlanta and Charlotte, federal authorities said.
   Some of those arrested in the Eastern raids said they paid as
much as $4,000 for a package deal that included transportation from
home, housing, the plane ticket and a job in New York.
   Hernandez, a Salvadoran who says he lives in Orange County, meets
illegals who have crossed the border at Tijuana. He says he escorts
them to Los Angeles International Airport and makes sure they board
Eastern Flight 80.
   ``Yes, I'm a smuggler,'' Hernandez told the newspaper.
   Six of the men admitted they were illegal immigrants headed for
New York, the newspaper said.
   ``I don't have a job there yet, but I hope to,'' said one alien,
who said he was from the Mexican state of Zacatecas. ``We're not
looking for trouble,'' one of the others interjected. ``We just want
to feed our families.''
   Hernandez said the recent INS attention to the flight caused no
alarm.
   ``What are they going to do to me?'' he said. ``Send me home? I
could be back in no time.''
</TEXT>
