<FIRST>r w AM-FruitOutlook     03-02 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fruit Outlook,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says Supplies Keeping Grower Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larger supplies of most citrus fruit are
keeping grower prices down from a year ago, although the possible
effects of recent freeze damage in some areas have not been
determined, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   The department's Economic Research Service said that ``U.S.
season-average grower prices for oranges and grapefruit are expected
to be lower than last season, while the average lemon price may be
slightly higher.''
   Total citrus output in 1988-89 ``will likely show a modest
increase from 1987-88, primarily reflecting the recovery from the
freeze damage Florida and Texas suffered in the early 1980s,'' the
report said.
   ``However, the forecast, which is based on conditions around Feb.
1, did not reflect the subfreezing temperatures'' reported in
Arizona and California.
