<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CBODirector     03-02 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CBO Director,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Agree on Reischauer to Head Congressional Budget Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats named economist Robert
D. Reischauer on Thursday to head the Congressional Budget Office,
placing him in the middle of this year's budget jousting between
Congress and the Bush administration.
   Reischauer, a former CBO official who is currently senior fellow
at the Brookings Institution in Washington, is considered moderate
and pragmatic by Democrats and Republicans. His selection ended a
search that pitted House and Senate Democrats against each other,
resulting in a stalemate that left the position unfilled for two
years.
   CBO is expected to perform as a non-partisan advisor to Congress,
even though in this case its director is being appointed by the
leaders of a House and Senate that are both controlled by Democrats.
   Reischauer will begin work in the $82,500-a-year job on Monday.
   The 48-year-old Reischauer advised Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis during his presidential campaign last year. He is credited
with the Democrat's proposal to create special savings accounts for
families wishing to accumulate money for college expenses.
   Reischauer joined CBO when it was created in 1975. By the time he
left the agency in 1981, he had become deputy director. He worked
for the Urban Institute from 1981 to 1986, when he joined Brookings.
   He has a Ph.D. in economics from Columbia University, and has
written about the federal budget, state and local fiscal problems,
the economics of education, revenue sharing, and welfare policy.
   CBO has been without a director since March 1987, when Rudolph
Penner left. Edward M. Gramlich became acting director and was
succeeded by James L. Blum, who will now return to his job as an
assistant director of the office.
   During the two years, the former chairmen of Congress' two budget
committees, Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., and Rep. William H. Gray
III, D-Pa., championed their own candidates for the director's job
but failed to agree on a single individual.
   Chiles left Congress and Gray is no longer chairman. Sen. Jim
Sasser, D-Tenn., and Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., became the new
chairmen in January, and quickly agreed to Reischauer's appointment.
</TEXT>
