<FIRST>r w AM-TridentSubmarines     03-02 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trident Submarines,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Navy Must Slow To Meet Goal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee chairman said Thursday he
won't try to block the Pentagon's request for a Trident nuclear
submarine this year, but warned the Navy must slow its one-a-year
purchase rate of the missile-firing sub if it wants to create a
600-ship Navy.
   ``I'm in no way running down the Trident,'' Rep. Charles E.
Bennett, D-Fla., told Navy officials. ``I'm just trying to get the
Navy to reach its 600-ship goal. ... We're very short in other
ships.''
   An 18,500-ton Trident, at $1.3 billion, is much more expensive
than most Navy ships. Delaying a Trident for a year could free money
for several surface ships.
   Bennett, chairman of the House Armed Services seapower
subcommittee, last year successfully had the Trident scratched from
the budget and added two Aegis destroyers with the extra money, but
Trident money was eventually restored.
   Last month, Bennett said he would look at eliminating money for
the nation's 17th Trident from the fiscal 1990 budget, but he said
Thursday that the timing of an elimination was wrong and he said he
will support the program. The pledge virtually eliminated any threat
to the Trident this year.
   Vice Adm. Daniel Cooper, assistant chief of naval operations for
undersea warfare, told the subcommittee a one-year delay in the
Trident would result in $150 million to $170 million in added costs
in fiscal 1991.
   Cooper attributed the projected increase to the added cost of
breaking the ``learning curve'' and halting the government's
contractual agreements with the Electric Boat Division of General
Dynamics Corp. Electric Boat is the sole builder of Tridents.
   Bennett said the Navy should avoid long-term contract options so
the government can skip a Trident purchase without suffering
financially.
   Rep. John G. Rowland, R-Conn., estimated that striking the sub
funding would result in the loss of 3,000 jobs at Electric Boat's
plants in Groton, Conn., and North Kingstown, R.I.
   Cooper assured lawmakers that despite technological gains by the
Soviets, the U.S. submarine force remains ``the best ... in the
world today.''
   The Navy official defended the Pentagon's newest submarine, the
SSN-21 Seawolf attack submarine, against critics who say it may not
be able to compete against advanced Soviet subs.
   The Navy ordered the first Seawolf from Electric Boat in January.
   Cooper said Navy officials scrapped plans to order two more
SSN-688 Los Angeles class attack submarines in 1991 and a final
SSN-688 in 1992 in part to show their commitment to the Seawolf. The
Navy's plan now calls for the final two SSN-688 subs to be purchased
in the fiscal 1990 budget now under consideration by Congress.
   The Seawolf will be faster, quieter, have the ability to dive
deeper and have more fire power than the Los Angeles class sub, plus
it will be big enough for future improvements, Cooper said. The Los
Angeles class sub is so packed now that any added improvements would
entail removal of systems already in the sub, he said.
</TEXT>
