<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-NuclearShip     03-02 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Nuclear Ship,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear-Powered Ship Stirs Alarm, Concerns in Soviet Far East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear-powered merchant ship bound for the
eastern Soviet Union is spreading alarm and opposition in the region
where it is heading, a newspaper said Thursday.
   The 850-foot-long ship Sevmorput is on its way to the port of
Vladivostok, the government daily Izvestia said. It said people
there ``do not conceal their alarm, linked first of all to the
(ship's) type of propulsion.''
   Government authorities in another port city in the eastern Soviet
Union, Nakhodka, supported residents' calls to close the harbor to
the vessel, which cost $260 million to build and ``has no parallel
in the world,'' Izvestia said.
   It said port authorities in Nakhodka had not yet been told what
plans exist to counter possible accidents aboard the vessel.
   Izvestia quoted the government official in the Magadan region of
the far eastern Soviet Union, located to the north of Vladivostok
and Nakhodka, as opposing the decision of the Ministry of Merchant
Marine to dispatch the newly built ship to the area.
   ``It seems to me the ministry has allowed a mistake by deciding
to send the Sevmorput without asking the advice of the territory,''
G. Dorofeyev was quoted as saying. Local coastal zones, he said,
``are practically not ready to receive it.''
   ``Anything can happen,'' Dorofeyev said. ``In our land, the
extreme north, natural cataclysms are not rare.''
   The Soviet Union has other atomic-powered merchant ships,
including a fleet of icebreakers based in the port of Murmansk 1,000
miles north of Moscow.
   The icebreakers have functioned safely for decades, authorities
say, but in Murmansk some residents now are calling for the vessels
to be moved to a port further away from the city of 440,000 people.
   Opposition to nuclear power has swelled in the Soviet Union since
the April 1986 accident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in the
Ukraine. In Armenia, for example, the government has begun shutting
down the republic's nuclear power plant because of the danger it
might be damaged in an earthquake.
   Izvestia quoted a Soviet nuclear power official, A. Zhuravkov, as
saying the power plant aboard the Sevmorput was of a different
design, and less liable to operator error, than the reactor that was
ruptured by a fire and explosion at Chernobyl.
   ``Sevmorput'' is a Russian-language phrase standing for
``northern sea route,'' the sea lane followed by some Soviet ships
along the northern Siberia coast between Europe and Asia. Izvestia
did not give details of the giant ship's envisioned role, but said
it was a lighter carrier, meaning it was designed to transport
smaller vessels.
</TEXT>
