<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Crisis     03-02 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Crisis,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parties Meet To Salvage Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's major political parties met on
Thursday in an effort to end a political and economic crisis that
threatens to topple the nearly 3-year-old regime of Prime Minister
Sadek Mahdi.
   Mahdi has given the the military one week to endorse his
government or face the consequences of his resignation. He has
announced a news conference for Sunday, when the week ends.
   Foreign Minister Hassan Turabi told the Sudan News Agency that
talks were going on between his Moslem fundamentalist National
Islamic Front, Mahdi's centrist Umma party and the Democratic
Unionist Party on the formation of a new government.
   But he said the positions of the rival parties remained far apart.
   The Democratic Unionists quit the three-party coalition
government in December to protest Mahdi's economic policies and his
refusal to approve a tentative peace treaty signed by the Democratic
Unionists and the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   Mahdi formed a new government with the National Islamic Front.
But last month, Defense Minister Abdel-Magid Khalil resigned and the
army presented Mahdi with a one-week ultimatum to form a new
broad-based government and take active steps to resolve the
6-year-old rebellion in the south.
   The army's ultimatum passed with no action, but the armed forces
remain on full alert and military leaders have insisted their
demands be carried out.
   Mahdi countered the army's demands with a threat to resign unless
the military gives him a mandate to continue leading the government.
   Both the armed forces and the Democratic Unionists want a
government that will include all political parties as well as
powerful trade and professional unions. The Democratic Unionist
Party already has urged Mahdi to step down.
   But Turabi on Thursday reiterated that his party rejected such a
government, and would accept only the Democratic Unionists in a
coalition.
   Turabi predicted that the political crisis will continue as long
as the armed forces refuse to heed Mahdi's requests.
   Mahdi was elected prime minister following general elections
April 25, 1986, exactly a year after the military overthrew
President Gaafar Nimeiri and then handed over the rule to civilians.
   He took over a government saddled with a $13 billion foreign debt
and a civil war that cost $1 million a day. His inability to take
decisive steps either in the economic or military fields has
prompted criticism both internally and externally.
   In Washington Thursday, a senior diplomat said the Soviet Union
had conveyed a U.S. request that Ethiopia press Sudanese rebels to
allow free passage for international food convoys to avoid mass
starvation.
   Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for Africa Kenneth Brown also
urged the Sudanese government to sign a cease-fire with the rebels
so food supplies could get to as many as 2 million needy people in
government-controlled areas.
   Brown spoke to a joint session of the House Select Committee on
Hunger and the subcommittee on Africa, which adopted a resolution
calling on the administration to enlist Soviet help in resolving the
Sudan crisis.
   The United States has given Sudan, the largest country in Africa,
about $1.7 billion over the past 10 years, but aid levels have
dropped sharply since the 1985 peak of $350 million after the ouster
of Gaafar Nimeiri, a strong pro-Western leader who was a personal
friend of President Bush.
</TEXT>
