<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Strike     03-02 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Strike,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Strike Halts Key Public Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2 million workers demanding higher
wages went on strike Thursday, shutting down public transportation
and paralyzing scores of other services.
   Airports, sea ports, banks, hospitals and private schools were
closed during the 24-hour walkout. Skeleton crews were working at
the state-owned public telephone, power and water corporations.
   Although most employee groups said the strike would last one day,
bank employees announced they would extend their walkout through
Friday.
   On Thursday, more than 10,000 demonstrators marched through
central Athens shouting ``No to austerity ... We want substantial
raises!''
   The General Confederation of Greek Workers, which represents most
of the country's 3.7 million workers, said the strike was
successful, ``especially in the state-owned corporations and in
industries.''
   It called the strike to protest the Socialist government's tight
income policies and to demand that wages be linked to inflation,
which ran at a 14 percent rate in 1988, the highest in the 12-member
European Economic Community.
   The confederation said industry and government offered a 2.5
percent wage increase this year and that the wage increase in 1988
was to 1.4 percent.
   The average monthly take-home pay for Greek workers is about
70,000 drachmas, or $450, it reported.
   The Socialist government has been plagued by strikes since the
year began.
   A Feb. 22 walkout by more than 6,000 municipal sanitation workers
continued on Thursday. The strike has left tons of garbage rotting
on city streets. The workers also are demanding wage increases to
keep up with inflation.
</TEXT>
