<FIRST>r a AM-Networks-Sweep     03-02 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Networks-Sweep,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC, CBS Rebound from Strike; ABC Still Struggling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS declared Thursday that it has shaken off the
worst effects of last summer's strike by the Writers Guild of
America, but ABC says it is suffering something of a delayed
reaction.
   NBC, thanks to the Summer Olympics and the World Series, was not
seriously affected by the 4{-month strike last summer and remains
ahead of the competition in the 1988-89 prime-time television season.
   By the end of the February sweep, one of four months a year when
local TV ratings are measured for purposes of determining
advertising rates, NBC led with an average A.C. Nielsen Co. rating
of 16.3. CBS had a 14.7 and ABC a 12.4. The rating is a percentage
of 90.4 million U.S. homes with televisions.
   The writers' strike ended in August, and the sporting events
allowed NBC to delay production of new series episodes the other two
networks had counted on.
   CBS started the season late in a weak position, having finished
third the previous season. ABC started late, too, but was soon flush
with the top-10 success of its new ``Roseanne.''
   ABC then suffered a 28 percent decline in February compared to
February 1988, when it had the Winter Olympics. NBC and CBS showed
increases this February over last.
   The four-night hit miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' boosted CBS above
ABC in the February sweep and helped put it in a virtual tie with
its rival for second place this season.
   ``This is the first time in about six of these (sweeps) where we
can say we're closer to the first-place network than the third-place
network,'' said CBS Vice President for Marketing David Poltrack.
   ``We were the most negatively impacted by the strike. We got off
last,'' Poltrack said. ``We made some changes, made some adjustments
and we think we've turned things around and are going in the right
direction.''
   ABC got through the November sweep with help from the first 18
hours of the 32-hour miniseries ``War and Remembrance.'' It was
hardly a ratings blockbuster, but it did better than ABC's regular
programming would have. The decision to program ``War and
Remembrance'' as a November fill-in came back to haunt the network
in February when ``War and Remembrance'' was to have run.
   ``Clearly we had a disappointing sweeps,'' said Alan Wurtzel,
ABC's senior vice president for marketing and research.
   ``We did not have an enormous inventory, because we had to play
`War and Remembrance' early, and we had planned to play it in
February,'' he said. ``The other two networks knew that and planned
accordingly.''
   ``Lonesome Dove'' and the competition it attracted kept the
networks' aggregate rating in February from looking like yet another
example of audience erosion. This sweep was about four rating points
lower than last year's, but last February there were 16 nights of
Winter Olympics.
   CBS got a big push, both in ratings and morale, from ``Lonesome
Dove,'' the highest-rated network miniseries in more than four
years. But the Western miniseries' success pleased ABC and NBC, too.
   ``I think `Lonesome Dove' was beneficial to everybody,'' Wurtzel
said. ``Network television needs to have exciting, well-made
programming.''
   ABC and CBS are looking ahead to a spring when they and their
viewers can expect to reap one benefit from the effects of last
summer's strike _ fewer reruns.
   Then the networks can begin to worry anew. The Screen Actors
Guild contract is up at the end of June and there is talk of a
possible strike.
</TEXT>
