<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Rebels     03-02 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Ethiopians: Prepare For War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Mengistu Haile Mariam's
government made its first public response to recent rebel victories
by telling citizens Thursday to prepare for all-out war against the
insurgents.
   ``No nation can tolerate violence and there is no alternative now
except to join hands and defuse the aggression launched against the
Ethiopian people,'' the Council of State said in a statement carried
by the official Ethiopian News Agency.
   It said people should ``be ready for an active involvement in
every area of the armed struggle,'' the official news agency
reported.
   The council is the executive committee of the Shengo, or
parliament. Its statement made no reference to claims by the rebel
Tigre People's Liberation Front that the army had evacuated the city
of Mekele ``fearing humiliating and shaking defeat ...''
   Diplomats in Addis Ababa said the soldiers left Mekele, capital
of Tigre province, on Monday without firing a shot. Mekele is about
475 miles northwest of Addis Ababa.
   Yemane Kidane, the Tigre rebel spokesman in Khartoum, Sudan, said
Tuesday ``the whole of Tigre now is liberated.'' He named the towns
taken by rebels in an offensive that began Dec. 28 as Adigrat,
Humera, Axum and Enda Sellasie, all north and northeast of Mekele.
   Thursday's council statement said: ``The seccessionist TPLF and
the Eritrean People's Liberation Front had coordinated attacks
against the Ethiopian army along the Adwa, Akswum and Enda Sellasie
route with the view to cut off the Ethiopian Red Sea area from the
rest of the country.''
   Rebels in Tigre province have fought the government for 14 years
and the Eritreans began fighting for independence nearly 30 years
ago.
</TEXT>
