<FIRST>r a AM-PostOfficeSiege     03-02 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Post Office Siege,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worker Convicted in New Orleans Post Office Siege</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former postal worker was convicted Thursday
of holding his former girlfriend hostage and shooting at his
co-workers during a 13-hour siege at a post office in December.
   The federal jury found Warren Murphy, 39, guilty of one count of
kidnapping and three counts of assault with intent to kill fellow
post office employees and FBI agents who tried to end the standoff.
Four people were injured during the incident.
   U.S. District Judge Veronica Wicker said sentencing would be
scheduled later. The kidnapping charge carries a maximum sentence of
life in prison, with a maximum of 20 years on each of the three
assault charges.
   One postal worker lost an eye from a shotgun blast during
Murphy's Dec. 14 rampage at the downtown New Orleans post office.
Two other postal workers were hit by the same blast of birdshot.
   An FBI agent was hit by a round fired through a door during the
standoff that followed after Murphy barricaded himself inside the
building. Another round was fired under a door at another agent, but
it was not clear whether he was hit.
   In a tape played to jurors, Murphy said he sawed off the shotgun
and stuck it down a leg of his pants to get it into the building. He
wore a work apron over his pants to further conceal the gun.
   The siege ended when New Orleans Police Superintendent Warren
Woodfork talked Murphy into giving up.
   Woodfork and federal authorities said Murphy was upset over
problems at work and his relationship with his girlfriend. He also
was concerned about the welfare of his children in the custody of
his estranged wife, the police chief said.
</TEXT>
