<FIRST>u a AM-INS-Snowbirds     03-02 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS-Snowbirds,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retirees Miffed Over Immigrant Shelter Next Door</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BENITO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retirees who spend their winters at a
trailer park here are angry over a plan to convert a nearby
warehouse into a detention center for hundreds of Central Americans
trying to enter the United States.
   The Justice Department's Community Relations Service is turning a
metal building next to the Snowbird Court trailer park into a
shelter because space is running out at a center 20 miles away in
the border city of Brownsville, said American Red Cross spokeswoman
Patty Garner.
   The Red Cross, under a contract with the government, is caring
for the immigrants. But the residents of the Snowbird Court RV park,
primarily retirees from Canada and the Midwest, do not welcome the
prospect of the new shelter.
   ``You save all summer to come down here and relax and have a good
time, and they pull this kind of number on you,'' said Hilda Lee, a
Snowbird resident from East Dubuque, Ill. ``We're being robbed of
our vacation.''
   She and other park residents said they were worried the often
destitute Central Americans might bring an increase in thefts to the
area.
   ``You know as well as I know if people are hungry they may go
ahead and take something that's not theirs,'' said Tom Wright of
Ontario, Canada.
   The Red Cross shelter in Brownsville is nearing its capacity of
800 people, Ms. Garner said.
   ``If we reach capacity here (in Brownsville), we will be able to
begin housing people there (in San Benito) also,'' Ms. Garner said.
Officials are not sure how soon they can open the new facility.
   The San Benito building, a 31,000-square-foot structure
resembling a large airplane hangar, will be equipped to house up to
600 people, she said.
   Increased Border Patrol activity and new Immigration and
Naturalization Service policies have put the INS in a bind for space
recently.
   The INS on Feb. 21 started holding applicants seeking political
asylum whose cases were denied in a new one-day adjudication
procedure. It also has stopped releasing those apprehended by the
Border Patrol on their own recognizance.
   The Brownsville shelter and the new one being prepared at San
Benito are for family groups who must report for daily roll calls
but are not locked up.
   Pat Thompson, owner of Snowbird Court, said she fears the new
neighbors will scare her business away.
   ``This (Lower Rio Grande) Valley's crawling with (mobile home)
parks,'' Ms. Thompson said. ``They don't have to stay here.''
   Others are concerned about sanitation problems that prompted the
city of Harlingen to evict the INS from a building last month.
   Jeffrey Weiss, associate director for immigration and refugee
affairs with the Justice Department, said the government will have
to satisfy county health authorities before moving into the San
Benito building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
