<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--BeeAttack     03-02 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bee Attack,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Dies After Attack By Bees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man attacked by a swarm of bees while
fishing in Panama drowned when, his eyes swollen shut by bee stings,
he could not find his life jacket and jumped into a lake to escape
the insects, his father said.
   Gary E. Hauser, 42, was fishing with two friends in Gatun Lake in
Panama, on Sunday when the swarm descended on them, according to his
father, Donald Hauser. Panama has been overrun by so-called ``killer
bees'' for several years.
   The three men jumped into the water and hung on to the boat, but
the bees still swarmed over them. They got back into the boat to try
to flee but couldn't get the motor started, Hauser said.
   The men then went back into the water. Two swam to shore, but
Hauser drowned, his father said.
   One of the men was in critical condition in a Panama hospital,
the elder Hauser said, and the second survivor was in shock.
   Gary Hauser, formerly of North St. Paul, headed the athletic and
sports programs at the Department of Defense Dependent School in
Panama.
</TEXT>
