<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     03-02 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Stroessner Aide Denies Corruption Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former private secretary of ousted
President Alfredo Stroessner declared himself innocent on Thursday
of corruption charges.
   Mario Abdo Benitez appeared in court to face accusations he
committed ``offenses against public administration'' including
embezzlement, bribery and fraud.
   Prosecuting Attorney Pedro Abilio Rolon said that on a salary
reported by the Treasury Ministry to be $665 a month, Abdo Benitez
reportedly owns 15 pieces of property, luxurious homes and a
twin-engine airplane.
   ``That's totally untrue. He only has savings accounts in
different banks amounting to some $10,000,'' said Abdo Benitez's
lawyer, Oscar Cuevas.
   In his lawsuit, Rolon accused Abdo Benitez of using his position
to extort money and favors in the name of Stroessner.
   Cuevas called the allegations ``totally false'' and said his
client ``didn't use his influence to receive gifts, money or other
things.''
   Abdo Benitez proclaimed his innocence to reporters and vowed to
prove it ``with documents I have at hand.''
   A lawsuit filed by Rolon was combined with one filed by the
attorney general against former Stroessner Cabinet ministers.
   The accused former ministers are Jose Eugenio Jacquet, labor and
justice; Adan Godoy Jimenez, health; Carlos Ortiz Ramirez,
education; Delfin Ugarte Centurion, commerce, and Sabino Augusto
Montanaro, interior.
   Except for Montanaro, who has taken shelter at the Honduran
Embassy, the former ministers are in custody at the Central Police
Station. Court hearings for them are due to start next week.
   Abdo Benitez became Stroessner's private secretary in 1963 and
continued in that post through last Feb. 3, the day Stroessner was
toppled in a coup by Gen. Andres Rodriguez, now Paraguay's
provisional president.
   Elections are set for May 1. Rodriguez is the presidential
candidate of the governing Colorado Party.
</TEXT>
