<FIRST>r i AM-Europe-Airlines     03-02 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Airlines,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europe Wants United States To Amend Computer Reservations System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European aviation officials on Thursday
accused the United States of using a computerized airline
reservation system that discriminates against European airlines.
   The officials said the system favors U.S. carriers even though
European airlines fly the same routes to Europe in less time.
   ``Consumers suffer from not always being given ready access to
the best (flight) information,'' by the U.S. systems, Edward Hudson,
secretary of the 22-nation European Civil Aviation Conference, told
reporters.
   He said he will raise the issue this month in a meeting with U.S.
Department of Transportation officials.
   ``There has been a marked reluctance from the U.S. government to
open its ears to what has been said by the Europeans,'' Hudson
complained.
   He said reservations made through U.S. computerized reservation
systems often involve ``unnecessarily lengthy journey times with
long overlays at connecting points'' because the computers favor
U.S. carriers.
   He said they list U.S. carriers on the first screen while flights
of European carriers are tucked away on remote screens that booking
agents do not switch to unless travelers specify what hour they want
to leave.
   ``It is a well-known fact that the great majority of bookings are
made from the first screen,'' Hudson said.
   The five U.S. systems are known as APOLLO, SABRE, PARS, DATAS-2
and SYSEM-1. Hudson said none give priority to flights to Europe
where warranted.
   As an example, he cited a direct, non-stop San Francisco-to-Paris
flight on France's UTA airline that is up to 5{ hours faster than
flights on major U.S. carriers which make stopovers.
   Yet SABRE puts the UTA flight on screen No. 9 rather than on the
first screen.
   Flights of Air France, British Airways, Lufthansa, Alitalia and
SAS get similar treatment though they get travelers from California
to Europe hours faster than U.S. carriers, he said.
   Hudson said the U.S. systems also list ``a service involving a
change of aircraft or change of carrier ... as a direct flight'' or
list connecting flights on U.S. carriers to Europe ``ahead of faster
and more direct'' services by European carriers.
   He called that ``misleading'' passengers.
   ``International services deserve better treatment'' in the United
States, the conference's deputy secretary, Kevin Kealy, said.
   Hudson said the 22 conference nations will issue next week the
organization's rules of conduct for West Europe's two main computer
reservation systems, known as Amadeus and Galileo. These rules, he
said, give non-European carriers first-screen priority if their
flights are more convenient.
   He asked the U.S. government to do likewise. ``The rules of the
game should be set at the government level,'' Hudson added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
