<FIRST>r a AM-Eggs-Divorce     03-02 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eggs-Divorce,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Wants Joint Custody Of Fertilized Eggs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>MARYVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man divorcing his wife has gone to
court to keep her from becoming pregnant with fertilized eggs they
had placed in frozen storage.
   Junior Lewis Davis, 30, said in a divorce complaint last week
that he does not want his wife, Mary Sue Davis, 28, to have the
embryos he fertilized implanted in her.
   The embryos are ``property jointly owned by the parties'' Davis
said, adding that Mrs. Davis ``has no legal right to make any
disposition (of them) without (his) express consent.''
   Blount Circuit Judge W. Dale Young signed an order last Thursday
temporarily keeping Mrs. Davis from having any of her in vitro
fertilized eggs implanted.He also barred her from removing them from
frozen storage, pending further hearings on the matter.
   In the complaint, Davis said he and his wife, both of Maryville
about 20 miles south of Knoxville, participated in an in vitro
fertilization program at a Knoxville hospital during the past
several years.
   He said his wife's eggs were fertilized outside the womb in a
laboratory with his sperm and then frozen so that she could have
them implanted inside her and possibly become pregnant at a later
time.
   Despite Davis' divorce petition and his objection to becoming a
father, Mrs. Davis said she eventually plans to have the eggs
implanted, according to the complaint.
   Davis said he had no comment on Thursday. Mary Sue Davis did not
return a telephone call made to the Knoxville company where she
works.
   Charles M. Clifford, Davis' attorney, said he would not comment
on the case.
   In vitro fertilization involves removing the woman's eggs and
fertilizing them with sperm outside the womb and then replacing them
inside the woman's body.
   The practice was pioneered in Great Britain, where in 1978 the
world's first so-called test-tube baby was born using the method.
   Since then, other infertile couples have used to the method,
which costs between $4,000 and $10,000 and has an approximately 15
percent success rate for each implant.
</TEXT>
