<FIRST>r w AM-Security-Benefits 1stld-writethru a0722 03-02 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Security-Benefits, 1st ld-writethru, a0722,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feisty 97-Year-Old Goes Up to Hill Seeking More Aid for Infirm</HEAD>
<HEAD>Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT spelling of feisty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 97-year-old woman, imploring Congress for a
boost in aid for the elderly and infirm, cut short lawmakers'
questions Thursday by shouting from her wheelchair, ``I'm asking
you, are you going to increase my payments?''
   Blanche Brown-Bey of Indianapolis told a House panel that she
lives on $13 a day while ``everything is going up. ... Everything is
so high, it almost takes my breath.''
   Her testimony, sometimes whispered and other times feisty and
loud, came at a hearing by two congressional panels on the
Supplemental Security Income program, a government ``safety net''
for the aged, the blind and disabled children.
   She was joined on a panel that included the director of the SSI
program and several social workers before a joint hearing of the
House Select Committee on Aging and the Ways and Means human
resources subcommittee. SSI is operated within the Social Security
Administration.
   Rep. Edward Roybal, D-Calif., chairman of the Aging Committee,
said SSI's top beneficiaries live on just $368 a month, which is
about 75 percent of the government's poverty level.
   The program, he said, ``is in fact characterized by inadequate
benefit levels, large gaps in service, insufficient outreach
activities and overly rigid requirements.''
   He cited testimony from witnesses who said many elderly people
were getting far less than the maximum payment and families with
severely disabled children were being routinely rejected because of
rigid standards.
   Michael Carozza, deputy commissioner of the Social Security
Administration, defended the ``successful, effective program. ...
SSI is an effective safety net, providing the aged, blind, and
disabled with a floor of income, the value of which is enhanced when
combined with Medicaid, food stamps and other assistance.''
   The poorest SSI recipients have income between 75 percent and 90
percent of the poverty level, he said.
   ``I believe this is appropriate when you consider that SSI tends
to be an income of last resort,'' he added.
   But Mrs. Brown-Bey, her frail frame sunk deep in her wheelchair
in the middle of the cavernous committee room, detailed in a
near-whisper how SSI benefits leave her barely able to cover her
monthly expenses.
   ``I pays $2.10 for my gas and pays $50 for my electricity,'' she
said, holding a magnifying glass to a handwritten paper.
   ``I have life insurance. My life insurance is 35 cents a week.
And my house insurance is $2.86. I pay that in November.''
   Frustrated finally by trying to read the paper, she dropped her
clipboard to the table and said, ``I'm telling you my experience.
... But I can't remember everything.''
   ``I'm telling you the truth so's you can know about me,'' she
continued.
   She paused before quietly concluding her testimony: ``I have my
plot paid for in Crown Hill. That's all.''
   Roybal, who has introduced one of three bills now in the House to
strengthen the SSI program, tried to assure her that he and others
on the two committees want to boost the benefits. But Mrs. Brown-Bey
cut him off.
   ``Are you going to increase it? That's what I'm asking you.''
   ``If it were up to me ...'' Roybal tried to assure her.
   ``I'm asking you, are you going to increase my payments,'' she
interrupted.
   SSI provides benefits to about 4.5 million elderly, blind and
disabled adults and blind and disabled children. Carozzi said the
average monthly SSI payments to recipients was about $188 as of last
December.
   One of the three bills the House is considering would raise the
SSI benefit level to the poverty level over three years and loosen
some eligibility standards. Another bill would change the way SSI
considers elibility for disabled children, and the third would
change the way such income as unemployment compensation is
considered under the program.
</TEXT>
