<FIRST>r a AM-SHOil-Fraud     03-02 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SH Oil-Fraud,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smith Pleads Guilty, Sentencing Delayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of bilking 700 people and three
banks out of $125 million by falsely claiming they were investing in
oil and gas drilling projects pleaded guilty Thursday to 98 counts
of fraud and state securities violations.
   During a half-hour hearing, Stephen L. Smith, owner of the
defunct SH Oil and Gas Exploration, switched his plea to guilty and
Polk Circuit Judge J. Tim Strickland ordered a pre-sentence
investigation. No sentencing date was set.
   Smith, 38, remains free on $225,000 bond. He had no comment after
the hearing, but his attorney, Richard D. Mars, said: ``It was a
fair disposition of the case.''
   State sentencing guidelines call for a sentence of 12 to 17 years
in prison for the charges to which Smith pleaded guilty: two counts
of organized fraud, 48 counts of unregistered securities sales and
48 counts of securities sales by an unregistered dealer.
   Each of the 98 charges carries a maximum penalty of 30 years in
prison and a fine of $10,000.
   At sentencing, prosecutors are expected to seek dismissal of the
remainder of 262 state criminal charges brought last year, which
include racketeering, grand theft and other securities violations,
Mars said. He could have faced up to 99 years in prison.
   Investigators claimed that Smith, over a nine-year period, used
money from new investors in SH Oil and Gas to pay dividends to
previous investors. They said Smith never owned any significant
interest in oil wells and had no legitimate business to operate.
   Investors included many prominent people in Winter Haven, such as
a former mayor, top businessmen, bankers, attorneys and doctors as
well as retirees.
   Smith's attorneys said they expect federal prosecutors to charge
Smith with grand theft and fraud in connection with about $2 million
owed Barnett Bank, which has offices across the state.
   More than 170 investors have sued Barnett Bank, claiming it
failed to scrutinize Smith before advising that his company was a
sound investment. No trial dates have been set.
   On Monday, Polk Circuit Judge Dennis P. Maloney ruled in a civil
case filed by the state against Smith that SH Oil and Gas was a
fraud. The action, which Smith's lawyers had sought to block because
of the criminal charges pending, was intended to pave the way for
the controller to seek a court order to distribute assets that are
in receivership.
   Authorities closed down Smith's 9-year-old business Dec. 30,
1987, and asked for appointment of a receiver to manage the assets
of the company and Smith. Attorney William H. McBride, the acting
receiver, said he has so far located about $5.5 million in assets
from the defunct company.
   ``This case will not be concluded until we have recovered every
possible penny for the victims,'' said state Comptroller Gerald
Lewis.
</TEXT>
