<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snowstorm Hits the Pacific Northwest, Moving East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A major winter storm brought strong winds, heavy rain and snow
Thursday to parts of the Pacific Coast, with heavy snow forecast for
much of the western states through Friday.
   Heavy snow in the Seattle area shut down the Seattle-Tacoma
airport for about 15 hours, but it reopened by mid-morning Thursday.
Snowfall ranged from 8 inches to 16 inches in the Auburn area, just
south of Seattle.
   Heavy rainfall fell on parts of Northern California, with more
than 3{ inches recorded at Ross, just north of San Francisco, and
more than 2{ inches at Redding.
   More than a foot of snow fell in the Sierra Nevada, where winds
gusted to 50 to 70 mph, and the higher elevations of extreme western
Nevada.
   Heavy snow also fell on portions of the northern Rockies, where
about 12 inches fell overnight in the ski areas near Jackson Hole,
Wyo.
   Winter storm warnings were in effect for southern and eastern
Oregon, central Idaho, northwest Wyoming, much of the Sierra Nevada
in California and higher elevations of northern and central Nevada.
   Winter storm warnings for heavy snow were expected by Friday
across most of the mountains of Idaho and western Wyoming. Winter
storm watches were posted for south central Montana, northern and
central Wyoming and the mountains of Colorado.
   High wind warnings for wind gusts to over 60 miles an hour cover
all of Nevada.
   Frigid weather covered the northern Plains, where temperatures
were below zero Thursday in parts of Montana, North Dakota and
Minnesota, for wind chills ranging as low as 40 below zero.
   Freezing drizzle was mixed with snow over southern Nebraska.
   In western New York, snow continued to be locally heavy east of
Lake Ontario, with 22 inches of snowfall recorded at Barnes Corners,
N.Y., since snow began wednesday,
   Rain covered the South Atlantic and Gulf coastal states.
Thunderstorms over the Gulf of Mexico dumped marble-size hail near
Gulf Shores, Ala.
   Partly cloudy skies and dry weather prevailed from New England
and the mid-Atlantic states across the Ohio Valley to the southern
half of the Great Plains.
   Dense fog was reported this morning from western texas across
western kansas and eastern colorado to southeast wyoming.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees below zero at Warroad, Minn., to 84 degrees at Fort Myers,
Fla.
   The national weather forecast for Friday predicted snow
widespread from the northern and central Plateau across the northern
and central Rockies, the northern half of the Great Plains, upper
Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes to much of New England. Snow
will be mixed with freezing rain for Iowa and eastern Nebraska. Rain
will occur over much of California, Arizona and northern New Mexico,
and from Kansas and Oklahoma to the middle Mississippi and Ohio
valleys. Rainshowers will be scattered across the Carolinas, with
thunder storms over Florida. Widely scattered thunderstorms will
occur over the lower Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures will be in the teens and 20s from eastern
Washington state across Montana, the northern half of the Great
Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes,
and across northern New England.
   Temperatures will reach the 50s and 60s in California, the desert
Southwest, New Mexico, southern Kansas and the middle Mississippi
and Ohio valleys to the middle and south Atlantic coastal states;
the 80s over much of Texas, the 70s over the lower Mississippi
Valley, and the 70s to mid-80s in Florida. Elsewhere, highs will be
in the 30s and 40s.
</TEXT>
