<FIRST>r a AM-BusinessmanArrest     03-02 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Businessman Arrest,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Threat Charges Against Businessman Will Be Dropped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radio station executive has been cleared of
making bomb threats to two airlines, a newspaper and a police
station, and the charge against him will be dropped, a prosecutor
said Thursday.
   Robert A. Costello, 54, was cleared after the FBI said it
suspected an inmate at the state prison in Concord of committing the
crime, said Suffolk County District Attorney Newman Flanagan.
   Witnesses said they heard Costello placing the calls, Flanagan
said. But the FBI's chief suspect is the inmate, who allegedly
billed the calls to the station, WCAP-AM, in Costello's name, he
said.
   The witnesses, whom authorities have not identified, were being
questioned Thursday, Flanagan said. He added that Costello deserved
no apology.
   ``He should be very grateful,'' he said. ``We're not embarrassed.
In fact, we feel very proud of the fact that we took steps (toward
his vindication).''
   Costello, a sales manager at WCAP, was arrested last Friday,
about 24 hours after the bomb threats were made to Continental
Airlines, American Airlines, the state police station at Logan
International Airport and the Boston Herald.
   The threats reportedly were in protest of Salman Rushdie's
controversial novel, ``The Satanic Verses.'' But Flanagan refused to
comment on whether the threats were related to the book.
   The charge against Costello would have been dropped Thursday but
his attorney, Joseph Tosney, was not available to appear in East
Boston District Court for the formal dismissal until Friday,
Flanagan said.
   Costello could not be reached for comment at his home, his office
or his attorney's office. ``My client's not making a statement
today,'' Tosney said.
   ``How does he express his gratitude for being handcuffed and
dragged from his place of work Friday evening?'' Tosney asked. ``How
does he express his gratitude at hearing an assistant district
attorney ask for $100,000 bail on Monday morning? How does he
express gratitude for being told the state police have an iron-clad
case against him?''
   The attorney said his client was distraught and didn't go to work
this week.
   Flanagan said Costello would be within his rights to sue for
wrongful prosecution.
   Costello, of Lowell, is a Marine veteran who serves in the
Massachusetts National Guard and is chairman of the Downtown Lowell
Business Association.
</TEXT>
