<FIRST>r i AM-StealthMissile     03-02 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Missile,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>First U.S. Cruise Missile Tested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLD LAKE, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A B-52 bomber carried a cigar-shaped
missile across northern Canada on Thursday in the first test of a
U.S. cruise missile designed with stealth technology, officials said.
   Maj. Jan Martinsen of the Canadian Forces Cold Lake air base in
northeastern Alberta said the bomber crossed an imaginary target at
the nearby Primrose Lake evaluation range at 11:15 a.m. and then
returned Edwards Air Force Base in California.
   ``As far as we know everything proceeded smoothly,'' she said.
``The Americans will obviously be analyzing the data they've
collected from this test.''
   The test had initially been set for Wednesday, but was delayed
because of severe blizzard conditions in the Northwest Territories.
   The missile remained attached to the bomber in what is called a
captive-carry test. Such flights are used to check guidance systems.
   The stealth cruise is an improved version of the air-launched
missiles that have been tested over northern Canada for years. It
has stealth technology so it can better avoid detection and also has
increased range and better accuracy.
   ``It's standard procedure prior to doing any free-flight rest to
do a captive-carry mission where the unarmed missile remains
attached to the B-52,'' Martinsen said.
   Canada's decision to allow testing of the advanced cruise drew
protests from peace groups. They said the missile is an offensive
weapon that will fuel the arms race between the superpowers and
ultimately create a need for a costly and complex Canadian air
defense system.
   The Canadian and U.S. governments say the weapon is too slow to
be a first-strike, offensive weapon.
   Cruise testing here is carried out under an agreement signed with
the United States in 1983 and renewed last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
