<FIRST>r w AM-BaseClosings 430   03-02 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Base Closings, 430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Co-Chairmen Defend Base-Closing Selections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should quit complaining about plans to
close 86 U.S. military installations and provide the money to
dismantle them, the co-chairmen of a commission which came up with
the plan said Thursday.
   In testimony before House and Senate defense appropriations
subcommittees, former Sen. Abraham Ribicoff, D-Conn., and former
Rep. Jack Edwards, R-Ala., urged lawmakers to accept the
base-closing package even if it does have shortcomings.
   ``Once you start chipping away, this thing goes down the tubes,''
Ribicoff told the House subcommittee. ``If you stop the momentum,
from my political experience, you're on the way to defeat.''
   Critics of the commission's recommendations, particularly
lawmakers facing closings in their areas, have complained that the
findings are flawed.
   For example, Rep. Edward Madigan, R-Ill., has said the commission
erred in its assessment of Chanute Air Force Base, one of the
facilities recommended for shutdown.
   ``The commission report suggests that the base has a shortage of
recreational, medical, housing and warehousing facilities,'' he
said. ``But base officials tell me that Chanute's recreational
facilities are among the best in the Air Force, that the commission
mistakenly underassessed the base's medical and dental capacity and
that the base actually has a surplus of housing.''
   But Edwards defended the commission's efforts.
   ``We collected a vast amount of data describing conditions at
thousands of installations we were asked to review,'' he said. ``We
did not just pluck this list out of thin air.''
   The panel appointed last year by former Defense Secretary Frank
C. Carlucci recommended that the Pentagon close 86 installations and
partially shut five others. Estimated savings are $5.6 billion over
20 years.
   Congress is scheduled to vote within weeks whether to accept or
reject the plan. It cannot pick or choose among bases to be closed,
and the closings can be blocked only if both the House and Senate
pass disapproval resolutions.
   Ribicoff acknowledged complaints such as those leveled by Sen.
Alan J. Dixon, D-Ill., who said U.S. overseas bases should have been
reviewed with an eye toward closing before any domestic bases were
considered.
   ``My personal thinking is that bases overseas ought to be closed
first,'' Ribicoff said. ``But we were forbidden to undertake it.''
   He and Edwards were making their second day of appearances in
support of the commission's efforts to solve the politically
sensitive issue of closing outmoded bases.
   They appeared Thursday before panels considering a Defense
Department request to appropriate $500 million in fiscal 1990 for
base-closing expenses.
</TEXT>
