<DOCNO> AP890302-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     03-02 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Calls On Third World To Face Foreign Debt United</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Venezuela, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Thursday
the violence shaking Venezuela this week could happen at any time in
Latin America and urged the Third World to deal jointly with the
foreign debt problem.
   Ortega wrote Venezuela's President Carlos Andres Perez that the
bloody riots in his country are the result of ``rigid policies and
unjust economic relations'' by industrialized nations toward the
Third World.
   ``Today it's Venezuela; tomorrow it could be Brazil, Mexico,
Argentina or any of the nations of Latin America and the
Caribbean,'' Ortega said in his letter. ``All of them are exposed to
this jolt.''
   The letter to Perez, dated Thursday, was made available to news
media.
   Rioting and looting in Venezuelan cities have reportedly left at
least 200 people dead and 1,000 wounded. Violence hit after Perez's
government announced increases in the price of gasoline and public
transport, as part of measures demanded by the International
Monetary Fund to restructure the economy.
   ``It is time the governments unite to forge a common policy in
the face of an onerous and unpayable foreign debt, which limits our
chances of development and the available resouces to satisfy the
basic needs of our people,'' Ortega wrote.
   He told Perez he was ``deeply worried'' about the violence in
Venezuela.
   ``We know this is the result of rigid policies and unjust
economic relations that the industrialized nations and bodies such
as the International Monetary Fund have been imposing on developing
nations and particularly on the nations of Latin America and the
Caribbean,'' Ortega said in his letter.
   The leftist Sandinista government's economic plan for 1989
includes measures similar to those being put in place by Venezuela
to fight hyperinflation. Nicaraguan measures call for budget cuts of
more than 40 percent, laying off more than 30,000 public employees,
and tightly restricting credit.
   Nicaragua's currency, the cordoba, has been devalued six times so
far this year. Each time, the price of gasoline, and consequently
food prices also rose.
   No public protests have emerged because of the economic measures.
Ortega on Wednesday warned right-wing business executives in
Nicaragua and the ``Yankee empire'' not to incite the Nicaraguan
people to insurrection, saying they would be ``the first victims''
of an uprising.
</TEXT>
