<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral 3rdLd-Writethru a0769 03-02 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0769,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vrdolyak Unofficial Winner In Chicago GOP Mayoral Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-10, `Sohn will ..., with 7 grafs to CORRECT campaign
manager's first name to Chris, sted Conrad, to CORRECT attorney's first
name to Burton, sted Burt, UPDATE with reax from Daley's spokesman and
from Evans; picks up 11th graf, pvs: `Both Vrdolyak, ...; DELETES grafs
17-18, `Daley was ..., to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Alderman Edward R. Vrdolyak, who launched a
write-in campaign less than a week before the Republican mayoral
primary, apparently defeated the GOP-enorsed candidate, a city
election official said Thursday.
   Vrdolyak totaled 11,621 votes, or 52.5 percent, to 10,478 votes,
or 47.4 percent for Dr. Herbert Sohn, who had the party's backing,
said Ray Jagielski, one of three members of the Chicago Board of
Election Commissioners.
   ``It's a great victory for all of the people that voted for me,''
Vrdolyak said at the elections board. ``It's not a personal victory
for me.
   ``When you're going over uncharted waters, a write-in campaign,
you know it's going to be hard and you don't know what to expect.
But if the people can spell Vrdolyak or close to it ... it was just
wonderful.''
   Four of the city's 2,911 precincts remained uncounted and all
ballots must be reviewed before the winner is certified by the board
on Tuesday.
   Vrdolyak also apparently had a large enough lead to prevent Sohn
from finishing within 5 percentage points, which would entitle him
to a so-called ``discovery recount,'' an automatic recount of 25
percent of the precincts.
   Sohn will ask a judge to order a discovery recount, said Sohn's
campaign manager, Chris Robling. By law, the results of such a
recount may be used only to seek a court-ordered recount of all
ballots.
   ``If we don't get the discovery recount, we will look for other
ways to show a judge the count was improper,'' said Burton Odleson,
Sohn's attorney. ``We'll find and interview election judges,
precinct workers ... and others if need be.''
   The GOP winner named by the commissioners will face two other
candidates in the April 4 general election in this traditionally
Democratic city.
   Richard M. Daley, son of the late, legendary boss of Chicago
politics, defeated Mayor Eugene Sawyer in the Democratic primary
Tuesday. Sawyer's chief black rival, Alderman Timothy Evans, is
running a third-party challenge on the Harold Washington Party
ticket, named for the city's first black mayor, who died in 1987
during his second term.
   Daley was vacationing in Florida, but his press secretary, Avis
LaVelle, dismissed Vrdolyak's influence on the general election.
``We don't view him as any particular threat,'' LaVelle said. ``I
don't think he will hurt anybody very much.''
   Evans agreed. ``It doesn't mean anything to me, frankly,'' he
said.
   Both Vrdolyak, 51, and Sohn, 61, had said they expected to
challenge the results in court and had retained seasoned election
attorneys. A court fight conceivably could delay the general
election.
   Though both Vrdolyak and Sohn, like Daley, are white, political
observers said only Vrdolyak had the potential to draw off a
significant number of voters from Daley's core constituency of
ethnic whites.
   ``Sohn, like most real Republicans in Chicago, has only a small
following and would barely cause a ripple. Eddie can't win, but he
could cause some real mischief,'' said Tom Roesser, a veteran
political analyst active in Republican and civic circles.
   Nearly 25,000 Republican ballots were cast in the city's 2,911
precincts Tuesday, about 10,000 more than in 1987.
   Vrdolyak, a former county Democratic party chairman and alderman,
has lost his last two tries for elected office. He ran an
unsuccessful third-party bid for mayor in 1987 and lost last fall as
the GOP candidate for clerk of the Cook County Circuit Court.
   But he did receive about 80 percent of the white vote in 1987
against Washington.
   One political observer said that Vrdolyak's campaign would not
make much difference to either Evans or Daley.
   ``Daley will win it anyway. Vrdolyak will only draw white votes
away (from Daley) if people are sure they're not endangering the
chance of a white candidate winning,'' said Paul Kleppner, a
Northern Illinois University professor and author of ``Chicago
Divided: The Making of a Black Mayor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
