<SECOND>AM-Infant Kidnapped, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0792,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>5-Month-Old Boy Taken in Botched Robbery Is Recovered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with second arrest; SUBS 14th graf with
name of second suspect and detail of the arrest, picks up 15th graf, `Mrs.
Grant ... </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-month-old boy, kidnapped Thursday after his
parents crashed through a window to escape robbers, was recovered
unhurt 16 hours later at a subway station and his two abductors were
arrested, police said.
   ``The baby is safe,'' said police spokesman Sgt. Maurice Howard
after the infant, Mikhail Grant, was swapped for ransom at a subway
station in the tough Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn shortly
before 5 p.m.
   Mikhail's ordeal began shortly after 12:30 a.m. Thursday, when
his father, Fynlass Grant, 27, returned home from his job as a
livery driver.
   Grant said he was pushed into his second-floor apartment in
Queens by two men with automatic weapons, said Inspector Richard
Mayronne.
   When the men burst in, baby's mother, Yvonne Grant, 26, who is
pregnant, jumped out the second-story window. ``She didn't stop to
open the blinds or the window,'' said a police source speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Mrs. Grant was treated for a broken ankle at Mary Immaculate
Hospital.
   The two men tried to force Grant to open a safe that was in the
house but he was too nervous, the police sources said. The safe
contained about $4,000 and some jewelry, the sources said.
   The sources said the gunmen knew Grant as a low-level drug dealer
and believed he had money.
   Grant leaped out the same window as his wife as one of the gunmen
scooped up the baby, said Mayronne.
   The abductors called the family home three times, demanding the
money and jewelry in the safe. A ransom drop at the subway station
was set up but the kidnapers fled around 7:30 a.m., minutes before
police could close in,
   ``They're obviously not professional kidnappers,'' said Mayronne.
``I consider them very low on the food chain, someone who would take
a 5-month-old baby.''
   Another drop was negotiated, and at 4:45 p.m. Grant, accompanied
by a plainclothes police officer, exchanged the baby for a bag of
ranson.
   The officer arrested a 17-year-old man who gave his identity as
Josiah Robinson, who will be charged with kidnapping, Mayronne said.
   The other suspect, Wayne Johnson, who was at the opposite end of
the platform where the swap took place, jumped onto the subway
tracks and fled by was arrested a short time later. He faces the
same charges, Howard said.
   Mrs. Grant has three other children, ages 6, 7, and 8, but police
said it was not clear whether they were at home at the time of the
incident.
</TEXT>
