<FIRST>r i AM-Dominican-Blanco     03-02 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dominican-Blanco,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Suspends Jorge Blanco Retrial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge suspended the
corruption trial of former President Salvador Jorge Blanco on
Wednesday after prison authorities failed to bring the defendant to
court on time for opening session.
   Judge Juan Maria Severino halted the trial after allowing the
authorities 50 minutes to escort Jorge Blanco to the court from La
Fe prison less than two miles away in Santo Domingo, the capital.
   He set no date for resuming the trial.
   Jorge Blanco was brought into the courtroom about 10 minutes
after the proceedings broke up. There was no explanation for the
failure to get him to court earlier. The drive ordinarily takes
about 10 minutes.
   Jorge Blanco, 62, president from 1982-86, was taken back to
prison, where he has been held since returning to the Dominican
Republic on Nov. 30.
   Jorge Blanco returned home three days after he was convicted in
his absence of embezzling $5 million from the government by
inflating the price of equipment bought by the military and national
police in the last two years of his administration.
   Jorge Blanco had been living in Atlanta, where he had been
undergoing treatment for a heart ailment since May 1987.
   Severino presided over that earlier trial and sentenced Jorge
Blanco to 20 years in prison and fined him $16.4 million.
   Under Dominican law, the former president Blanco had the right to
a new trial upon returning to this Caribbean nation.
   Two businessmen convicted with Jorge Blanco in November, Leonel
Almonte and Juan Tomas Pena Valentin, are serving 20-year prison
terms.
</TEXT>
