<FIRST>r w AM-SeatBelts     03-02 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seat Belts,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seat Belt Use At All-Time High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record 46.5 percent of the drivers on U.S.
roads use safety belts, a federal report said Wednesday.
   Based on a survey of more than 50,000 drivers in 19 cities, the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said seat belt use
increased for the 12th consecutive time since it began making
semiannual surveys.
   The agency estimates that safety belts saved 4,300 lives in 1988
and 15,200 lives since a national campaign began in 1982.
   Before the campaign and enactment of state laws requiring belts,
only 11 percent of drivers used them, the report said.
   The survey, conducted in October and November 1988, showed that
in 13 surveyed cities where safety belt laws were in effect, usage
averaged 51.1 percent, compared to 36.3 percent in six cities
without belt laws.
   The government estimates 10,000 more lives could be saved if all
motorists used safety belts.
   Cities in the survey where seat belts are required showed the
following percentage of use by drivers: New York, 28.4; Baltimore,
50.7; Pittsburgh, 43.9; Chicago 29.8; Minneapolis, 61.5; Miami,
51.6; New Orleans, 40.7; Seattle, 61.4; San Francisco, 55; San
Diego, 59.1; Los Angeles, 52.7; Houston, 61.4, and Dallas, 67.7.
   Cities with no belt requirement had the following percentages:
Boston, 37.8; Providence, 19.9; Fargo and Moorhead, 35.7; Atlanta,
31.7; Birmingham, 35.2, and Phoenix, 52.7.
   The safety administration, in a news release giving the results,
did not say how the survey was conducted or how many drivers were
checked in each city.
</TEXT>
