<FIRST>r i AM-Arafat     03-02 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Says PLO Invited Syria, Others To Coordinate Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat said
Wednesday that his Palestine Liberation Organization invited Syria,
Egypt, Jordan and Lebanon to meet to coordinate policy on a Middle
East peace conference.
   The five parties are directly concerned with the Arab-Israel
problem, the PLO chairman said.
   The proposed international peace conference under U.N. auspices
would include participation by Israel and the five permanent
Security Council members _ the United States, the Soviet Union,
China, Britain and France.
   Arafat made his announcement through WAM, the official news
agency of the United Arab Emirates, soon after arriving in Abu Dhabi.
   WAM quoted Arafat as saying the invitation was for a policy
coordination meeting to take place ``within two to three weeks, to
coordinate stances on preparations for the international conference
on peace in the Middle East.''
   The Cairo representative of the PLO, Saeed Kamal, was quoted this
week as saying Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze proposed
reactivation of the five-member panel which was first set up after
the pan-Arab summit of 1974 when the PLO was named the sole
legitimate representative of the Palestinian people.
   Arafat said Shevardnadze told Egyptian officials during his
recent Middle East swing that Syrian President Hafez Assad ``agreed
that Syria should participate fully in the meetings of that
committee.''
   The United Arab Emirates is among Arab states trying to heal
rifts between Syria and Egypt and between Syria and the PLO.
   Rifts in the Arab ranks after the late Egyptian President Anwar
Sadat visited Jerusalem in 1977 froze the five-member group's
activities. Syria has refused to patch up differences with Egypt
unless it officially revokes the 1978 Camp David peace framework
that Sadat signed with Israel.
   In 1983, Syria also broke off with Arafat, saying he was moving
in line with ``surrenderist'' settlements with Israel.
   Arafat said the venue of the proposed meeting has not yet been
fixed but that it could be held in Damascus, Cairo, Amman or Tunis,
where the Arab League and the PLO are headquartered, WAM said.
</TEXT>
