<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     03-02 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Camp Raided in Town Named for Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARCOS, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assault troops brought in by
helicopter raided a Communist rebel training camp Wednesday near
this northern Philippine town named for the family of ousted
President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Brig. Gen. Bayani Fabic reported one arrest, but said the
14.8-acre camp was abandoned by the time about 30 troops arrived
aboard four helicopters.
   Elsewhere, the military reported that Moslem rebels killed five
troops and that about 75 communist rebels burned three buses on
Tuesday in Banay-Banay village in Davao Oriental province, about 630
miles southeast of Manila.
   The government-run Philippines News Agency said New People's Army
rebels also set fire to three trucks there and made off with food
and other cargo.
   The agency said the incident disrupted transportation in Davao
Oriental for the rest of the day when other public buses refused to
use the route.
   No explanation was given for the attacks, but rebels often
targeted transport companies which refuse to pay ``revolutionary
taxes.''
   The military said Moslem fighters killed three militiamen in an
ambush Sunday on the outskirts of Isabela town in the southern
island province of Basilan. It added that a breakaway Moslem group
ambushed a marine patrol Tuesday on Jolo Island, killing two
troopers.
   Three Moslem groups are fighting to establish an independent
nation in Islamic areas of the southern Philippines. Their rebellion
runs parallel with the 20-year-old communist insurgency, which began
when Marcos was president.
   Marcos was driven into Hawaiian exile by a popular
military-civilian uprising three years ago.
   Fabic said raiders found 50 dummy rifles used to train guerrillas
as well as first-aid kits. He said the camp included four wooden
huts, a field hospital and obstacle courses.
   The general said the raid blocked rebel plans for attacks on
municipal halls in several towns in this area, 240 miles north of
Manila.
   The camp was about four miles outside the Ferdinand municipal
district, part of the town of Marcos.
   Fabic said the rebels had begun a big recruiting campaign in the
province, which is considered a Marcos stronghold.
</TEXT>
