<FIRST>r i AM-EmergencyLanding     03-02 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landing,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Orient DC-10 Leaves For Boston After Engine Stall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Orient DC-10 bound from Frankfurt, West
Germany to Boston with 232 aboard made an emergency landing in
London Wednesday after an engine stalled, then continued on when
mechanics gave it a clean bill of health.
   The plane landed at Gatwick Airport on two of its three engines,
said an airport spokesman, who spoke anonymously.
   Northwest Orient spokesman Andy Plews said the No. 2 engine
stalled on takeoff from Frankfurt, West Germany ``and instead of
trying to restart the engine in flight the captain decided to divert
to London Gatwick.''
   The 222 passengers and 10 crew aboard Flight 47 disembarked
normally after the landing, an airline statement said.
   Mechanics checked out the engine on the tarmac, running it up to
full power in a test ``and discovered that there was no problem with
it,'' Plews said.
   The plane continued on its flight 5{ hours after landing in
London.
   He said Northwest Orient doesn't know why the engine failed ``but
it is possible for engines to do this occasionally. It could be a
lack of air flow through the engine which can be caused by an
atmospheric condition.''
   In a separate development on Wednesday, Brian Lavers, an aircraft
surveyor for Britain's Civil Aviation Authority, criticized airlines
for paying too little attention to corrosion.
   Lavers told a conference of about 100 experts at Gleneagles in
Scotland that airlines and others responsible for aircraft
maintenance showed a continuing apparent reluctance to make the
small extra investment in tackling the problem.
   Lavers reported that the belly areas of transport planes were
allowed to remain wet and dirty, retaining a mixture which acted
like wet blotting paper and defeated anti-corrosion coatings.
   The U.S. Air Transport Association said Monday that hundreds of
repairs were needed on certain aging airliners if more than 1,000
airplanes are to keep flying. The repairs would cost hundreds of
millions of dollars.
</TEXT>
