<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Cocaine     03-02 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Cocaine,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seize 3,740 Pounds of Cocaine In Raids On Two Labs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's national police raided two
jungle laboratories, seizing 3,740 pounds of cocaine and arresting
32 people, the country's top police official said Wednesday.
   The raids were part of a month-long campaign in which police have
confiscated 7,700 pounds of cocaine. The campaign, called Operation
Springtime, is the longest-running series of strikes against cocaine
traffickers ever seen in Colombia.
   The latest raids were conducted Tuesday near the town of Zarzal,
about 145 miles southwest of the capital of Bogota, and near the
town of Mani, 125 miles east of Bogota, police Gen. Miguel Antonio
Gomez Padilla said in a communique.
   In addition to the almost four tons of cocaine seized in the last
month, police have confiscated 135 tons of marijuana and have
destroyed 65 cocaine labs and 16 runways used by planes hauling
cocaine to the United States, the general said.
   Police also have destroyed 540,000 gallons of chemicals used for
processing cocaine and have burned 85 acres of coca plants.
</TEXT>
