<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Politics     03-02 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Politics,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nakasone Cancels U.S. Trip After Opposition Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone said
Wednesday he was forced to cancel a speaking tour in the United
States because of links to a widening stock scandal.
   Nakasone, prime minister from 1982-1987, was invited to speak at
the Massachussetts Institute of Technology, Yale University and Duke
University this week. He also was to meet with President Bush and
former President Reagan during the 14-day trip.
   ``It is very regretful and I must apologize for causing trouble
to the people who invited me,'' Nakasone said in a nationally
televised interview. ``But I guess a politician has to expect
something like this to happen.''
   Nakasone has been linked to the scandal in which Hiromasa Ezoe,
founder of Recruit Co., an information and publishing conglomerate,
sold unlisted shares in a subsidiary to more than 150 people at
bargain prices. Share prices shot up once they were listed publicly,
netting the buyers large profits.
   On Mondaym Nakasone acknowledged that his aides purchased and
reaped profits from the Recruit shares. Nakasone said the money was
used to purchase year-end and summer greetings gifts.
   Nakasone's link to the affair was brought to light after it was
revealed three of his aides earned more than $640,000 in profits by
selling their shares.
   Opposition parties, claiming Nakasone played a key role in the
affair, have demanded the government call the former two-term prime
minister to Parliament for questioning.
   ``It is not an appropriate time for him to travel abroad, while
opposition parties are demanding he be summoned to Parliament and be
questioned,'' said Osamu Yatabe, a parliamentarian from the largest
opposition group, the Japan Socialist Party.
   Eight people, including Ezoe, have been arrested and accused of
bribery and violating the securities law.
   The scandal, which has already forced the resignations of three
Cabinet ministers, has caused a public uproar and severely damaged
the credibility of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's administration.
</TEXT>
