<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LittleRockDesegregation     03-02 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Little Rock Desegregation,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Settlement In School Case Is Signed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state agreed Wednesday to encourage
desegregation throughout Arkansas and pay more than $100 million to
settle a 6-year-old federal desegregation case brought by the Little
Rock School District.
   The proposed settlement involving the state and all three school
districts in Pulaski County was signed by attorneys for all the
parties before U.S. District Judge Henry Woods.
   The mostly black Little Rock School District sued the state and
the neighboring, mostly white North Little Rock and Pulaski County
Special school districts in federal court six years ago, alleging
the defendants caused illegal segregation in Little Rock schools.
   Woods found North Little Rock and Pulaski County liable and
ordered the districts merged, but the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, affirming Woods' liability ruling, said his proposed
countywide consolidation was too severe.
   Instead, the appeals court ordered the boundary line between the
Little Rock and Pulaski County districts redrawn, moving large,
mostly white sections of the city of Little Rock, which were in the
county district, into the city district. North Little Rock was not
affected.
   The appeals court then asked the district judge to consider how
much the state would have to pay to fund compensatory programs in
the three districts, especially Little Rock. This led to the
settlement.
   If the agreement is approved by Woods, the state would be
released as a defendant in the case. Final approval would need to
come from Woods, all three school boards involved, the Legislature,
and the state Board of Education. No hearing was set.
   Robin Armstrong, Little Rock School Board president, said she was
pleased with the settlement, and Sheryl Dunn, a member of the
Pulaski County School Board, called it a momentous occasion.
   The terms of the settlement, under which the state will pay out
more than $100 million, include:
   _The state must pay the Little Rock district $59.1 million over
10 years for compensatory education programs and other desegregation
expenses, and the North Little Rock district $2.7 million in seven
annual payments, also for compensatory education.
   _The state must pay $7 million to the Pulaski County district by
July 1, plus an additional $6.7 million by July 1, 1990, if the
Legislature raises state revenues during the current session; if no
additional revenues are raised, the district would get $16 million
over five years.
   _The state must block construction of any school in a county
bordering Pulaski County if the new school would hurt desegregation
of schools in Pulaski County.
   _State officials must recommend to the Legislature repeal of all
laws impeding desegregation, and not to propose any new ones that
would have that effect.
   _The state must recruit black teachers for all three districts
and push for legislation to help minority students enroll in
teacher-education programs at college.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890302-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-Elections     03-02 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Elections,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Announces Election Law Barring Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma announced a proposed election law
Wednesday that would bar military officers currently governing the
country from running in next year's elections.
   State-run Radio Rangoon said the Election Commission, which
drafted the law, would make the document available to the public and
political parties Thursday for suggestions.
   Citing key points of the law, the broadcast said government
employees, including members of the armed forces and police, could
not run for election. That would prevent Gen. Saw Maung and other
members of the ruling military council from running unless they
resign from the armed forces.
   Saw Maung seized power in September. His troops brutally put down
a pro-democracy uprising that for months had clamored for the end of
26 years of authoritarian, one-party rule.
   Saw Maung allowed the formation of political parties and has
promised general elections in 1990 and a freer economy.
   The radio said the proposed law sets the voting age at 18 and
reduces the earlier minimum age of candidates from 24 to 21. Banned
from participation are people with allegiance to foreign powers,
members of parties who receive financial support from foreign groups
and people with links to Burma's numerous rebel groups.
   The Election Commission has asked the general public and
political parties to submit suggestions by March 31. It also has
asked the parties, which currently number 233, to choose between
different voting systems.
</TEXT>
