<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv03   03-02 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 03,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, March 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Old-Fashioned Fellow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In contrast to the conservative,
produced-to-a-polish and totally predictable managers who occupy the
executive suite in many mature companies, the founder was probably
simple, direct and unpredictable.
   That was J.B. Fuqua, founder of Fuqua Industries and, until he
eased himself out of the positions recently, its chairman and chief
executive officer.
   J.B., now 70, is an original, which makes his legacy especially
vital and meaningful today, when so many corporate messages are
crafted by publicists to impress a particular audience or create a
public image.
   This is part of his message, distilled from a commencement
address at Oglethorpe University in 1986, and perhaps a rare and
old-fashioned model for other corporate chairmen now preparing to
address the 1989 graduating classes.
   The subject was success and leadership.
   ``Attaining one's goals, however modest they may be, is success
for that individual,'' according to Fuqua. ``There is no more
successful a person than one who becomes a good teacher and is
dedicated to conveying knowledge.''
   Ambition and leadership are much the same, although one must
first be ambitious to become a leader, he said. He added, ``it
occurs to me that we have fewer people today than at any time in my
memory who are actually ambitious.''
   Leaders, he said, always want to be at the head of the line.
``They think big thoughts; they avoid a lot of trivia; and they just
don't waste precious time.'' They are curious. They learn how to use
books.
   ``The best way to be a success and a leader is to act like one.
Choose those people who are successful and imitate them. Getting
ahead of the crowd can be almost that simple.''
   One thing you will notice about successful people, he said, is
that they have better personal habits than the crowd. ``They dress
better. They don't smoke. They don't abuse drugs or alcohol. They
are careful of health.''
   When Fuqua started out he had little money. Moreover, he was very
young (he was a radio engineer at 19, part owner of a radio station
at 21). He learned to dress well.
   ``I dressed better than my peers because I knew I didn't have any
experience and had a limited education; but by dressing better I was
confident I could make a good first impression,'' he said.
   ``If you don't remember anything else I say today,'' he told the
students, ``I hope you will remember this: You'll never have a
second chance to make a first impression.''
   Leaders work longer hours. By working just 10 hours a week more
than average you gain three months more experience in just one year,
``and in only four years you've picked up an additional whole year.''
   Manners count. ``Learn to say `thank you' sincerely every time
there is any excuse for doing it.'' Be punctual. Be courageous.
``One of the great opportunities we have in this country is the
opportunity to make a mistake.''
   Leaders are accessible. ``I've always said I'm going to talk to
everyone who phones me because Santa Claus might call one day and I
don't want to miss him.''
   Leaders learn early that we all have two ears and two eyes, but
only one mouth. ``We don't learn anything while we are talking. The
only help your mouth can give you in learning may be in asking the
right questions.''
   Finally, never succumb to the weakness of saying you are just one
person and don't amount to very much.
   ``Individuals are the only important people there are. The world
only recognizes individuals. ... Nowhere in Atlanta will you find a
single monument erected to a committee.''
   But, he added, being an individual doesn't mean you need to be
just a common individual, an ordinary person.
   Fuqua, personally involved in every operation of his consumer
products and service business from its beginning in 1968 to is
present eminence on the New York Stock Exchange, was famous for
unique leadership.
   At one point he faced criticism for shrinking the company when
growth was in vogue. His individuality and courage were vindicated,
however, when the profits went up.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri., March 3.</NOTE>
</DOC>
