<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-02 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0759</SECOND>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines struggled to avert a weekend
machinists strike, offering pilots sweeter pay, job security and
other promises if they sign a new contract and defy a walkout by
fellow workers.
   The Machinists union has threatened to strike at 12:01 a.m.
Saturday because of a 17-month-old contract dispute.
   Meanwhile, travel agents said Wednesday that would-be travelers
to and from South Florida and the Caribbean were steering away from
Eastern Airlines as the strike deadline neared.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income in January posted
its largest gain in more than a year, rising 1.8 percent, but people
chose not to spend much of the extra money and instead built up
their savings, the government reported.
   Analysts were cautious about whether Wednesday's report might
signal the start of a long-sought slowdown in consumer spending,
which would help cool inflationary pressures in the economy, and
said the robust income figures suggested continued strength in the
economy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending rose 0.4 percent in
January as work on non-residential buildings such as factories and
offices offset a downturn in activity on government projects, the
government said.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that building activity
rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $424 billion in
January. January's advance followed a 2.1 percent increase in
December and a 1.3 percent jump in November.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hopelessly deadlocked National Economic
Commission, failing to reach a grand compromise to solve the
nation's fiscal problems, issued a final report that split
essentially along party lines.
   The commission's seven Republicans and the one Democrat appointed
by President Bush endorsed the president's 1990 fiscal budget on
Wednesday.
   But the commission's six Democrats said in a minority report that
castigated Bush's $1.16 trillion budget.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal savings and loan regulators say
depositors withdrew at least $1 billion last month from institutions
targeted for government takeover.
   M. Danny Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, told
the Senate Banking Committee on Wednesday that the nation's 2,950
S&amp;Ls suffered net withdrawals of $4 billion to $5 billion in
February, including $1 billion to $2 billion from the 220
institutions earmarked for takeover by the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade is moving to employ a
computerized, off-hours trading system for competitive reasons, but
its proposed new system will provide a ``significantly improved
audit trail'' for regulating its members, the market's chairman said.
   In a speech Wednesday to the Chicago division of the Futures
Industry Association, Karsten Mahlmann said the Board of Trade
within weeks would publicly unveil its proposed electronic
auction-market system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused to dismiss charges or
grant a mistrial in the GAF Corp. stock manipulation case and
defense lawyers called their first witnesses.
   The developments Wednbesday came at the trial of GAF and its vice
chairman, James T. Sherwin, who are charged with securities fraud
and other criminal counts in an alleged scheme to manipulate the
price of Union Carbide Corp. stock in October 1986.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Shoppers swarmed to Sears, Roebuck and Co., which reopened its
824 stores after cutting prices on 50,000 items to introduce its new
``everyday low pricing'' policy and mark the end of an era in
retailing.
   The nation's biggest retailer switched Wednesday to more
name-brand merchandise and discount prices in hopes of luring
shoppers away from cut-rate competitors like K mart and Wal-Mart,
which have grown rapidly at the expense of Sears and other old-line
general retailers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp.'s oil and gas production and
exploration units will be sold for about $1.4 billion to a British
concern to help finance a friendly takeover by Panhandle Eastern
Corp., Panhandle announced.
   The agreement with Enterprise Oil PLC was reached Wednesday just
days after the two Houston natural gas companies signed a $3.2
billion merger agreement.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices slumped in late trading Wednesday, as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials closed with a 15.35 loss at 2,243.04.
   The dollar rose broadly in foreign exchange trading.
   Bond prices fell sharply, pushing interest rates higher.
   Copper futures prices soared; precious-metals and soybean futures
prices plummeted; and grain, energy, and livestock and meat futures
were mixed.

</TEXT>
