<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Pepsi-MadonnaAd Bjt   03-02 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepsi-Madonna Ad, Bjt,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi Expects 250 Million Worldwide Will See New Ad With Madonna</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsi-Cola Co. hopes to reach a worldwide
television audience of 250 million today as its two-minute
commercial with pop singer Madonna makes its debut in 40 countries
from Turkey to Thailand.
   The commercial, which will be aired in the United States on NBC
during the top-rated ``The Cosby Show,'' also marks the first public
airing of Madonna's new song ``Like a Prayer,'' an unusual forum for
a song's debut.
   Pepsi officials, who previewed the commercial for reporters
Wednesday, said they tried to place the ad on the top-rated evening
show in each country.
   They refused, however, to disclose how much it cost to produce
the ad, to hire Madonna or to buy the advertising time.
   The commercial will appear first in Japan and follow the time
zones around the world before finishing on the West Coast of the
United States.
   The commercial opens with Madonna watching a grainy home movie of
her eighth birthday party, where she gets a new doll and sips on a
bottle of Pepsi.
   As the spot unfolds, the little girl in the movie and the
grown-up pop singer trade places.
   As she sings her new song, Madonna finds herself dancing with a
group of teens on the street, with uniformed school children at a
grade school and finally in a church where a gospel choir sings with
her.
   Those shots are mixed with glimpses of the little girl, played by
8-year-old actress Heidi Marshall, exploring Madonna's apartment,
finding clues to what her life will be like when she gets older.
   When the little girl finds her alter ego still has the doll she
was given on her eighth birthday, she looks back at the screen and
trades places with the singer once again.
   Madonna, back in her chair watching the movie, raises a Pepsi can
and offers a toast to the birthday girl: ``Go ahead, make a wish.''
   Bill Katz, an account executive for Pepsi's advertising agency,
BBDO, said the ad will be edited into 60-second and 30-second
versions for subsequent showings.
   It was directed by Joe Pytka, whose work for Pepsi has included
commercials featuring singer Michael Jackson and actor Michael J.
Fox.
   Pepsi long has used pop singers in trying to create a youthful,
energetic image for the soft drink, which trails only Coca-Cola in
the soft drink market.
   It is breaking ground by launching a singer's new release in its
commercial. With Michael Jackson, Pepsi waited until his songs were
at the peak of their popularity before launching commericals
featuring them.
   Madonna's single of ``Like a Prayer'' is scheduled to be released
Tuesday, followed two weeks later by her new album. A music video
that differs from the ad is slated to debut Friday on MTV: Music
Television, the cable TV music channel.
   Katz said Pepsi is confident that the song will be a hit and said
other performers may decide to launch songs on commercials after
seeing the Pepsi ad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
