<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-02 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was stable in European trading
early today, while the market waited to see whether West Germany's
central bank would raise interest rates.
   Gold was down.
   The market appeared split over the chances that West Germany
would raise its discount rate. ``I see the market 50-50 divided over
the change they will move,'' said a trader in Milan, Italy.
   The pound fell in London to $1.7200 from $1.7243 late Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.39 Japanese yen to a closing 128.07 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 128.12 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8370 West German marks, down from 1.8390; 1.5700
Swiss francs, down from 1.5705; 6.2550 French francs, down from
6.2575; 2.0725 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0755; 1,355.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,354.75; 1.1972 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1985.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $384.05 a troy ounce,
down from $384.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning Wednesday, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$384.10.
   In Zurich, gold was trading at $384.10 at noon, matching late
Wednesday's price.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.37 an ounce to close at a bid
$385.89.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $5.76 a troy
ounce, down from $5.79 late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
