<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-02 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Share Prices Up Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded sharply in Tokyo today after
a three-day plunge, and the U.S. dollar gained against the Japanese
yen for the third consecutive day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selcted issues, which had lost
more than 480 points over three days, gained 109.43 points, or 0.34
percent, and closed at 32,073.73. The Nikkei closed higher despite a
decline in morning trading.
   Kenji Ishizuka of Daiwa Securities said the index started upward
when investors started buying construction issues.
   ``The market seemed to have recovered from its nervousness ahead
of the West German banks' meeting later Thursday,'' he said.
   Securities and currency markets have been cautious, watching to
see whether West German banks would raise interest rates following
the U.S. discount rate hike last week. The U.S. Federal Reserve
Board raised its discount rate, its charge for loans to private
banks, from 6.5 percent to 7.0 percent.
   Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 800
million shares.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 128.07 yen, up 0.39
yen from Wednesday's 127.68-yen close. It opened at 127.93 yen and
ranged between 127.90 and 128.50 yen.
   The dollar now has gained 2.07 yen in the last three days.
   The U.S. currency's higher opening in Tokyo followed its upward
trend on overseas markets overnight, dealers said.
   Japanese investors were more interested in buying the West German
mark because of speculation that West German banks might raise their
interest rates, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``If West Germany does not raise rates, the dollar will probably
rise because those who were reluctant to hold many dollars today
will go back to the U.S. money,'' he added.
</TEXT>
