<DOCNO> AP890302-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Coke-Pepsi     03-02 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coke-Pepsi,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coke and Pepsi Taste Tests Are All Fizz, Regulator Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the heated advertising war between Diet Coke
and Diet Pepsi is being fought with celebrities such as Madonna,
Michael Jackson and Don Johnson, Massachusetts regulators say the
companies' claims last summer to win consumer taste tests were made
without substantiation.
   In the ads last summer, Pepsi said it was ``undisputed champion''
and ``decisively beat Diet Coke'' in taste tests, while Diet Coke
said it was ``winner and still champion'' after beating Pepsi four
times in four years.
   Paula W. Gold, state secretary of consumer affairs and business
regulation, said Wednesday that both companies' tests were skewed by
improper sampling techniques and ``did not fairly represent a random
sample of cities across the nation.''
   Coke and Pepsi have been competing intensely for the lucrative
diet soft drink market, which is growing at an annual rate of 8.4
percent, more than twice as fast as sales of soda as a whole.
   During 1988, Diet Coke had 8.2 percent of the $43 billion soft
drink market, while Diet Pepsi had 5.2 percent, according to Jesse
Meyers, publisher of Beverage Digest in Greenwich, Conn.
   Gold, an aggressive regulator who has previously ordered
investigations into auto salesmen and bank fees, said she decided to
check on Coke and Pepsi because of the obvious contradiction between
their high-profile ads. Both companies discontinued the ads at the
end of the summer.
   Although Coca-Cola is based in Atlanta, and Pepsi's headquarters
are in Purchase, N.Y., Gold said they have operations in
Massachusetts and their advertising has an effect here.
   ``I think if suspect advertising practices are allowed to go
unchecked, then advertisers come down to the lowest common
denominator,'' she said. ``You've got to look at and enforce the big
players as well as the little ones.''
   Spokesmen for both Coke and Pepsi disputed the Massachusetts
regulator's findings.
   ``This type of test has been upheld in the past by the courts,
certainly by the television networks, and also by the National
Advertisers Bureau,'' said Tod MacKenzie, a spokesman at Pepsi's
headquarters. ``This quite frankly seems to be a case in which the
state has stepped into an area that's new to it, and I think that
shows in their report.''
   Gold said she requested detailed information from the soft drink
companies in July and gave it to an independent evaluator, Frederick
Wiseman, a professor of marketing and statistics at Northeastern
University in Boston.
   Wiseman said Wednesday that Coke gave taste tests to 999 people
in 10 Eastern cities. Pepsi's test sample was 1,000 people in four
cities _ Seattle, Los Angeles, Philadelphia and Indianapolis.
   ``Taste test research does not have to be as exact as a political
poll, where you're really aiming for a national projection,''
Wiseman said.
   ``But this is a case where the samples were just too far off. You
had Coke basically ignoring one half of the country, and Pepsi
picking just four cities, all within 100 miles of a processing
plant.''
   Wiseman said he found no evidence that either company
deliberately rigged its samples to achieve a certain result. Rather,
he said, ``it appears they were just trying to get it done quickly.''
   Gold said that after the ads had aired, Coke expanded its sample
to 27 cities across the country. If Coke had done the broader
testing before the ads ran, she said, it would have been adequate
substantiation.
   ``But doing it after the fact still doesn't make it right,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
