<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     03-02 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Higher At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were slightly higher on London's Stock
Exchange at midday Thursday after trading in a narrow range
throughout the morning on continuing nervousness about future rises
in British and world interest rates.
   The West German Bundesbank left its key rates unchanged after its
fortnightly council meeting Thursday, easing earlier fears that
British rates would have to rise simply to keep pace with a West
German rate hike.
   But more signs of sterling weakness and the generally pessimistic
analysis of Wednesday's British trade figures combined to create
some nervousness about the long-term outlook for British interest
rates.
   Players were still considering the conflicting signals on the
likely trend in British rates, dealers said. Institutional investors
are likely to remain on the sidelines until the picture becomes
clear, they added.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 1
point, or 0.05 percent, at 2,022.3 at about 1:15 p.m., about halfway
between the day's high of 2,025.2 and the low of 2,017.6.
   Volume was a moderate 285.7 million shares compared with 341.6
million shares at the same time Wednesday.
