<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Stag-Sewage     03-02 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stag-Sewage,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Sues Brewery For Polluting Sewers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
has filed a lawsuit against the G. Heileman Brewing Co. for
allegedly polluting sewers in this Southern Illinois city for nine
years.
   The lawsuit accused Heileman's Stag Brewery plant of repeatedly
discharging wastes without adequate treatment into Belleville's
wastewater treatment system.
   The lawsuit, filed Feb. 9 in U.S. District Court in Alton,
charges that ``the brewery repeatedly discharged wastes containing
high concentrations of biochemical oxygen demand and total suspended
solids.''
   The Wisconsin-based company faces up to $37 million in fines if
found guilty, said Anne Weinert, an EPA environmental engineer.
Heileman officials could not be reached for comment.
   The EPA filed a lawsuit Nov. 22 in federal court alleging
Belleville had violated pollution discharge limits since April 1985.
EPA and city officials have been negotiating a fine but have not
reached a settlement.
   Ms. Weinert said Wednesday the agency now believes pollutants
discharged from the brewery are what caused the city to violate the
Federal Clean Water Act.
   ``We believe that Stag Brewery is one of the major reasons for
the (city's) violations,'' Ms. Weinert said.
   Mayor Richard Brauer said he believed the lawsuit against the
brewery could cause the EPA to lower the city's fine, which could
have been as much as $125,000.
   ``This would be part of our negotiations,'' Brauer said.
   Since Stag closed last August, the city has been in compliance
with the Clean Water Act, Brauer said.
   From the time Stag began operating in 1979, city officials worked
to help the brewery comply with EPA regulations, Brauer said.
   ``We were aware of the problem and we were working with the
brewery,'' he said. ``We proposed a couple of plans to the Illinois
EPA and one was accepted, but by the time (IEPA) accepted the plan,
Heileman decided not to go through with it.''
   The city offered to build a $2.9 million pretreatment plant for
the brewery, which would have brought it into compliance with EPA
regulations, Brauer said. Heileman would have had to repay the city.
   Heileman rejected the offer and decided to close the brewery
instead. The plant officially closed its doors in August, causing
the loss of about 230 jobs.
   Despite the sewage problems and lawsuits, Brauer said he would
prefer to see the brewery open again.
   Brewery officials have said the only thing that could keep the
Stag Brewery open was to sell 10 million more barrels of beer each
year. The brewery, which had the capacity to brew 25.3 million
barrels each year, shipped only 16.25 million barrels in 1987.
</TEXT>
