<DOCNO> AP890302-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Morrell-NLRB     03-02 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morrell-NLRB,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>NLRB Issues Complaint Against Morrell For Plant Reopenings: Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Labor Relations Board complaint against
meatpacker John Morrell &amp; Co. recommends reinstatement and back pay
for workers at plants which were closed, then re-opened with lower
wage scales, a union says.
   The NLRB office here issued a complaint Wednesday saying Morrell
``fraudulently concealed'' an ``unlawful scheme'' to circumvent its
master agreement with the union, the United Food &amp; Commercial
Workers said.
   The union said the NLRB complaint also cites discrimination
against workers because of their union activities.
   Back pay and job reinstatement for affected employees from the
plants in Kansas and Tennessee are among the ``sweeping and
breathtaking'' recommendations of the NLRB complaint, said Phillip
L. Immesote, director of the union's 85,000-member packinghouse
division.
   The union said the company could be responsible for $100 million
or more in back pay.
   Officials of the union in Washington and the NLRB office in
Chicago were not available late Wednesday.
   In June 1982, Morrell closed the former Rodeo Meats Inc. plant in
Arkansas City, Kan., where nearly 750 UFCW members worked at a base
wage of $11.07 an hour, the union said.
   The plant reopened in March 1983 under the name Ark City Packing
Co., with 200 workers paid $5 an hour, the union said. The plant now
employs more than 500 workers, represented by Local 340 of the
union, at a base rate of $7.60 an hour, according to the union.
   Morrell also closed a plant in Memphis, Tenn., in July 1982,
which had employed about 400 members of the union's Local 242 at a
base wage of $10.69 an hour, according to the union.
   When the plant reopened under the name Memphis Packing Co. in
September 1983, it employed 250 workers at a base wage of $5.50 an
hour. When it closed again in June 1986, it employed 300 workers at
a base wage of $8.50 an hour, the UFCW said. The plant has not
reopened.
   The NLRB says a majority of the rehired workers were former
employees, but the company refused to rehire certain workers because
of their union activities, the union said.
   David Parker, an NLRB spokesman in Washington, was not familiar
with details of the Morrell case, but said such complaints are often
a first step in cases that can be appealed to an administrative law
judge, the five-member NLRB or federal courts.
   A message left with an operator at Morrell's Cincinnati
headquarters after business hours Wednesday was not immediately
returned.
   ``This process can take a long time unless the parties reach a
settlement,'' Parker said. ``It can take several years.''
   The union claims to have a company document which spells out
strategy to break the master agreement and the union.
   If the company, a subsidiary of United Brands Co., does not fight
the complaint, it must reinstate all employees laid off in 1982 at
the Arkansas City and Memphis plants or find them ``substantially
equivalent positions,'' the union said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
