<FIRST>r f PM-UnocalExplosion-Settlement     03-02 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unocal Explosion-Settlement,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuits Over Fatal Explosion Settled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has approved a $29.9 million settlement of
27 lawsuits tied to a 1984 oil refinery explosion that killed 17
people and injured 10 others.
   Unocal Oil Co., owner of the Romeoville refinery south of
Chicago, and nine other companies were sued for negligence by the
families of those killed and injured in the explosion, attorney
Bruce R. Pfaff said.
   Pfaff, who represents six plaintiffs, said the case was about two
years from trial, prompting all sides to reach an agreement.
   Cook County Judge Donald P. O'Connell on Wednesday approved the
settlement after months of pre-trial conferences and negotiations
that at one time involved more than 50 law firms representing the
plaintiffs, Unocal and other companies.
   Lloyd Williams, who represented Unocal and the other companies in
negotiations, said the companies' individual contributions to the
settlement were confidential.
   The explosion occurred July 23, 1984, in a 55-foot vessel
containing liquid hydrocarbons, byproducts of the refining process,
Pfaff said.
   An investigation later determined that the vessel exploded when
internal cracks in the inch-thick steel broke through the outer
skin, Pfaff said.
   The lawsuits against Unocal and companies involved in the
vessel's design, construction and maintenance contended that Unocal
inspectors failed to properly test the vessel's walls for stress.
The lawsuits also said repairs made to the vessel by welders made it
too brittle to withstand inside pressure.
   Pfaff said the settlement did not require Unocal or the other
companies to admit fault.
   After about $100 million in repairs, the refinery reopened 16
months after the explosion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
