<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     03-02 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0260</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market showed a modest gain today,
aided by strength in the dollar and slightly lower interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.57 to 2,246.61 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 537 up, 365 down and
497 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 22.99 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   A steady showing by the dollar against leading foreign currencies
helped push bond prices a bit higher in the credit markets.
   That, in turn, seemed to encourage some selective buying in the
stock market.
   But analysts said many traders remained concerned about recent
evidence of increasing inflationary pressures.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Union Carbide, up } at 30\;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up ] at 30]; International Business
Machines, up [ at 120, and Exxon, up [ at 43|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.19 to 161.93. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .22 at 322.40.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 15.35
points to 2,243.04.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 610 up, 810 down and 527 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 177.21 million shares, up from 147.43
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
