<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Jaguar     03-02 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Jaguar,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaguar Workers Reject Company's Latest Pay Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Jaguar PLC, the British luxury car
maker, narrowly rejected the company's final pay offer and have
scheduled an overtime ban starting this weekend and weekly one-day
strikes after Monday.
   The final tally showed 3,700 workers rejecting the offer and
3,682 accepting it, a Jaguar spokesman, who wasn't identified, in
accordance with British custom, said Thursday.
   The result was decided by the votes cast late Wednesday by 800
night-shift workers.
   The spokesman said Jaguar would appeal the outcome, which was
based on votes cast at open meetings, and would ask the union to
stage a secret ballot.
   Those voting against the contract offer represented only 42
percent of eligible voters, and the company hopes a secret vote
would increase the voter turnout.
   ``We would like a secret ballot to sort this out,'' the Jaguar
spokesman said. ``This vote is not a sufficient mandate for damaging
industrial action.''
   In negotiations last weekend Jaguar made what it said was its
final offer, a two-year deal including raises of 4.7 percent in the
first year and 4.4 percent in the second, plus bonuses.
   Jaguar said its workers earn an average 210 pounds, or the
equivalent of $361, per week.
</TEXT>
