<FIRST>r f PM-AlleghenyInternational     03-02 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Allegheny International,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Executive Resigns Following Merger Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. said today that
Thomas J. Albani, chief operating officer and executive vice
president, resigned Wednesday following an agreement to be acquired
by investors led by Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc.
   ``It's only proper that the prospective new owners should be able
to select their managers,'' said Albani, 46, who joined the company
in 1984 as president of its Sunbeam North American Appliance Group.
   ``Mr. Albani has served AI with distinction,'' said Chairman
Oliver S. Travers.
   The takeover, for which a definitive agreement was signed
Wednesday, calls for the executive committee of the board to operate
the company until the acquisition is completed. James D. Milligan, a
long-time associate of DLJ, will serve as special adviser to the
committee.
   An acquisition company formed by DLJ plans to acquire 62 percent
of the financially troubled Pittsburgh company for an investment of
$60 million. Shareholders would be left with 38 percent of the
company, if a bankruptcy judge approves the plan.
</TEXT>
