<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-02 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower, Turn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices turned mixed
after opening slightly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
possibly indicating the markets' attention was turning from weather
concerns to export activity.
   The opening decline extended the sharp sell-off that ended
Wednesday's session. Analysts said the selling was prompted in part
by reports of beneficial rain in the soybean fields of Argentina,
the world's third-largest soybean producer.
   But the selling eased shortly after the opening on reports of
higher cash prices for soybeans and talk of Soviet interest in
purchasing U.S. corn.
   Export activity has been on the rise lately, with the Agriculture
Department targeting both China and Iraq for large sales of U.S.
wheat at subsidized prices.
   The wave of early buying may also reflect attitudes that
Wednesday's sharp decline in soybean prices was unwarranted.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.37} a bushel; corn was
unchanged to } cent lower with March at $2.71{ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1\ cents higher with March at $2.04 a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with March at $7.50 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .15 cent higher with April at
77.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with March at 82.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .17 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with April at 44.30 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .03 cent to .22 cent lower with March at 38.55
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
