<FIRST>r f PM-USShoe-Lawsuit     03-02 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US Shoe-Lawsuit,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Sue U.S. Shoe over Division Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six U.S. Shoe Corp. shareholders have sued the
company in an effort to block the planned sale of its footwear
division to an investor group for $422.5 million.
   The shareholders filed the lawsuit Wednesday in Hamilton County
Common Pleas Court alleging U.S. Shoe Chairman Philip Barach and the
company's directors breached their fiduciary duty to shareholders by
agreeing to sell the division.
   The shareholders claim U.S. Shoe officials should have done more
to increase the company's value for its shareholders.
   A U.S. Shoe representative declined comment on the suit.
   U.S. Shoe announced this week it was selling its footwear unit to
a group led by Merrill Lynch Capital Partners.
   The planned sale stemmed from a six-month search by another
Merrill Lynch affiliate to find a buyer for all or part of U.S.
Shoe, a $2.2 billion Cincinnai-based company which includes women's
clothing stores such as Casual Corner and the LensCrafters optical
stores.
   Wall Street had expected the entire company to be sold and was
disappointed in the announcement. Some analysts had predicted sale
of U.S. Shoe's individual businesses could be worth more than $30 a
share.
   Jerry Fuss, a New York stockbroker, was one of the six
shareholders filing the suit. It accuses U.S. Shoe directors of
trying to perpetuate their control of the company, rather than
carrying out their duties to shareholders to get maximum value for
the company.
   Fuss said he bought 200 shares of U.S. Shoe on Friday at $25.12{
expecting the entire company to be sold.
   Wednesday the stock closed in New York Stock Exchange trading at
$18.87{, representing a paper loss of $1,250. In early trading
today, U.S. Shoe was was up slightly at $19.37{ a share.
   Fuss said he bought the shares on expectations the company would
announce the sale of the whole business.
</TEXT>
