<FIRST>r f PM-Visa-DiscoverCard     03-02 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Visa-Discover Card,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Visa Forges Link With Discover Card</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Credit-card processor Visa U.S.A. has agreed to an
electronic link-up with Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s Discover card that
could lead to greater acceptance of Discover by merchants, a Sears
spokesman said today.
   The arrangement will enable merchants to run Discover cards
through their existing Visa processing machines, sparing them the
hassle of installing separate Discover authorization and computer
terminals, a Sears division spokesman said.
   ``Now a merchant who accepts Visa can just take Discover card
(sign) and stick it in his window and clear the Discover card
through the equipment he already has there,'' said James Flynn, a
spokesman for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., the Sears division with
responsibility for Discover.
   Sears said the electronic link will be established later this
year.
   Flynn said Visa, the nation's largest credit-card organization,
already has such an arrangement with No. 2 MasterCard.
   The 3-year-old Discover card posted a fourth-quarter profit of
$6.7 million. Sears said it had not expected the card to show a
profit until its fourth year.
   The Discover card is accepted by 900,000 merchants. Visa and
MasterCard both say their cards are accepted by more than 6 million
merchants.
   Discover claims to have 27 million cardholders compared with more
than 108 million for Visa and more than 81 million for MasterCard.
</TEXT>
