<FIRST>r f PM-DenverAirport 1stLd-Writethru f0070 03-02 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denver Airport, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0070,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pena Will Consider Airport Referendum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS background throughout on where money would come from and
opponents seeking to expand Stapleton. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Federico Pena says he will consider yet
another referendum on Denver's proposed $3 billion airport.
   ``There are arguments pro and con, and I'm trying to weigh those
arguments,'' he told the City Council and Chamber of Commerce on
Wednesday.
   The airport, which would be the first such major project in the
nation since the Dallas-Fort Worth Airport opened in 1974, survived
an election in May when Adams County voters agreed to annexation of
land outside Denver for the project.
   Pena and others contend the airport, scheduled for a July
groundbreaking, will ease a projected air transportation crush and
boost Colorado's economy. Stapleton International Airport is flawed
in design and too small, they say.
   But opponents have called the project a waste of money engineered
by ``fat cats'' and would rather see Stapleton expanded. City
Councilmen Ted Hackworth and Bob Crider are seeking to put an
airport question on the ballot.
   ``I just think we've got to make a decision _ pick a course we're
going to commit ourselves to, and then just stick to it,'' Pena said
Wednesday.
   On Sunday, the mayor had said a referendum isn't needed because
the airport won't be financed with local tax dollars.
   The city is asking for $500 million from the federal government,
with the rest of the money coming from revenue bonds, the sale of
land at Stapleton and revenue from the old airport, such as
concessions, fuel taxes and landing fees.
</TEXT>
