<FIRST>r f PM-MCorpRestructuring     03-02 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCorp Restructuring,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCorp Creditors Form Committee To Work On Restructuring Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of MCorp creditors, including New York
investment banker Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., has formed a
committee and started work on its own restructuring plan for the
troubled Dallas holding company, The Dallas Morning News reported
today.
   The newspaper cited sources as saying the committee has met with
MCorp managers and federal regulators with a goal of submitting a
plan to rescue the company.
   The group also includes another investment firm based in New
York, Kleinwort Benson Inc., the newspaper said.
   Shearson confirmed Wednesday the investment firm had joined with
other MCorp creditors in an informal group.
   Shearson has much to lose if MCorp cannot successfully
reorganize. The investment firm holds $147 million of MCorp
securities and suffered losses of more than $110 million in 1988
from recognizing the plummeting value of those holdings.
   Any recovery of those losses likely depends on MCorp's ability to
emerge as a going concern, The Morning News said.
   Shearson is said to have also taken a leading role in helping to
convince other MCorp creditors to not force the company _ which has
skipped bond payments _ into bankruptcy.
   A group holding bonds from National Bancshares Corp. of San
Antonio has threatened to force the company into bankruptcy if it
does not resume interest payments this week.
   And the trustee for bondholders of Texas American Bancshares Inc.
of Fort Worth has filed suit against that company _ also demanding
overdue bond payments. The federal suit was filed in December in
Fort Worth by the Bank of New York on behalf of bondholders, Texas
American said Wednesday.
   Texas American said it is contesting the suit, charging that the
bondholders want preferential treatment in the company's
restructuring effort.
   Federal regulators continue to negotiate with Minnesota banker
Carl Pohlad, who has tentatively agreed to buy both Texas American
and National Bancshares.
   Meanwhile, hope has faded that MCorp can win government approval
for the company's own proposal to bail out its 25 subsidiary banks.
Last fall, MCorp chairman Gene H. Bishop said the firm could raise
$400 million in new capital, which it wanted to combine with Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. assistance.
   Analysts have estimated MCorp would need at least $1 billion in
government aid.
   Soon after Bishop's announcement last October, Shearson publicly
supported the company's effort.
   But Bishop has made little apparent progress gaining FDIC
approval for his plan. The FDIC last week said it would continue to
solicit bids for MCorp from other parties until April 3.
</TEXT>
