<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Cadbury     03-02 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Cadbury,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cadbury Schweppes Posts 28.5 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dr Pepper, no period, is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cadbury Schweppes PLC, the British soft drinks and
confectionery group, said Thursday its 1988 after-tax profit jumped
28.5 percent over a year ago, helped by strong growth in Britain as
well as Australia and neighboring countries.
   The company said after-tax profit in the 12 months ended Dec. 31
totaled 140.5 million pounds, the equivalent of $242 million,
compared with 109.3 million pounds the year before.
   Earnings per share rose to 23.47 pence, or 40 cents, from 19.05
pence, helped by a change in the company's tax accounting.
   Sales rose 17.2 percent to 2.38 billion pounds, or $4.1 billion,
from 2.03 billion pounds.
   The company reported an extraordinary gain of 28.4 million
pounds, chiefly because it sold half of its 34.4 percent stake in Dr
Pepper for $108 million in cash and securities. The sale came when
the U.S. soft-drink concern merged with Seven-Up last year.
   Cadbury Schweppes retains an 18.4 percent stake in what is now
called Dr Pepper-Seven-Up Companies Inc.
   The company didn't break out quarterly results. It isn't required
to under British law.
