<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-RoyalDutch-Shell     03-02 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Royal Dutch-Shell,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Giant Posts 14.3 Percent Decline in Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Companies, the
Anglo-Dutch oil giant, said Thursday its fourth-quarter profit fell
14.3 percent, due mainly to a special charge and weak world crude
oil prices.
   The company, based in The Hague, the Netherlands, and London,
said net income for the three months ended Dec. 31 totaled 702
million pounds, or $1.2 billion, on an historical cost basis,
compared with 819 million pounds in the same period a year earlier.
   Royal Dutch-Shell said it took a special charge of 67 million
pounds during the quarter for an environmental cleanup of a former
chemicals manufacturing site at Rocky Mountain Arsenal property in
Colorado.
   On a current cost basis, which values the company's oil
inventories at current market prices and is more comparable to the
American accounting method of last in first out, or LIFO, net income
fell 19 percent to 765 million pounds, or $1.3 billion, from 943
million pounds.
   The per-share conversions into dollars were provided by the
company.
   Sales in the fourth quarter fell 7.2 percent to 14.2 billion
pounds, or $24.4 billion, from 15.3 billion pounds.
   For the year, net income rose 3.9 percent to 2.94 billion pounds,
or $5.1 billion, on an historical cost basis from 2.83 billion
pounds a year earlier.
   On a current cost basis net income rose 12.8 percent to 3.17
billion pounds, or $5.5 billion, from 2.81 billion pounds.
   Sales in 1988 fell 6.7 percent to 55.8 billion pounds, or $96
billion, from 59.8 billion pounds a year ago.
   The company said the annual profit improvement was curtailed by
depressed exploration and production activities, principally because
of the decline in world crude oil prices and lower natural gas sales
due to mild weather in Europe.
   However, manufacturing, marine and marketing earnings increased
substantially, the company said, because of higher volumes and
margins.
   The company also reported that chemicals had an excellent year,
with buoyant demand for petrochemicals and high capacity utilization.
</TEXT>
