<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Near Highs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher, near their session
peaks on Thursday, encouraged by the pound's recovery and a strong
early trend on Wall Street.
   The market recovered its poise after a nervous morning session,
with players trying to assess conflicting signals on the outlook for
British interest rates.
   The West German central bank's decision to leave its key interest
rate unchanged after its regular council meeting helped ease earlier
fears that British rates would have to rise simply to keep pace with
a West German rate hike.
   The unchanged West German rates helped the pound recover from an
early slide, which had reportedly prompted the Bank of England to
intervene several times to prop up sterling.
   Some players still feared another bout of sterling weakness could
force the Britsh government to signal an increase in the British
commercial banks' base lending rate from its current 13 percent
level.
   But many analysts said they believed the government is reluctant
for political reasons to raise rates ahead of Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson's March 14 budget statement, despite the
release Wednesday of another set of poor British trade figures.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 18.4
points, or 0.9 percent, higher at 2,039.7.
   Volume was a moderate 483.9 million shares, down from 535.4
million shares a day earlier.
</TEXT>
