<FIRST>u f BC-Eastern-Mediators     03-02 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Mediators,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mediators Report Progress in Airline Impasse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal mediators said Thursday that one side
in the dispute between Eastern Airlines and the Machinists' union
had made a new contract offer and negotiators were hopeful ``it
might be the kind of breakthrough we are looking for'' to avert a
strike.
   Walter C. Wallace, chairman of the Naional Mediation Board, said
representatives of the airline and the 8,500-member union had met in
Washington in the 17-month labor dispute.
   He declined to say which side had made the offer or what it
contained.
   ``We are assured by both sides that they want to reach a
settlement,'' Wallace told a news conference.
   The board asked President Bush last week to call a special panel
that would delay the strike 60 days beyond a midnight Friday
deadline.
   Wallace said the parties were evaluating the offer and would meet
later separately with board mediators in hopes of reaching a
settlement.
   ``There has been action that hopefully might be the kind of
breakthrough we are looking for. There's been some movement,''
Wallace said.
   Harry Bickford, chief mediator in the dispute, said, ``There is
an amended proposal made from one party to the other and it's under
consideration.'' He said it was the first change in the negotiations
in several weeks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
