<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0294</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose sharply today, recouping
Wednesday's losses with help from declining interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 15.35 points on
Wednesday, climbed 27.50 to 2,270.54 by 3 p.m. today on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by a wide margin in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues.
   A steady showing by the dollar against leading foreign currencies
helped push bond prices higher in the credit markets.
   That, in turn, seemed to encourage some steady buying in the
stock market.
   Analysts said the worries about increasing inflation and Federal
Reserve credit tightening that swept through the markets last week
apparently were easing.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, said he expects the increase
in the consumer price index for February to be smaller than the 0.6
percent gain reported for January.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Union Carbide, up 1 at 30{;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up \ at 30\; International Business
Machines, up { at 120], and Exxon, up ] at 43~.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet fell 1~ to 50{. The Wall Street Journal reported
that the company faces a controversy over sales practices involving
the credit data it compiles.
   Minnetonka, the most active issue in the over-the-counter market,
jumped 7\ to 21[. The company retained an investment banking firm to
advise it on a possible saleor other transaction.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.59 to 163.33. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 2.46 at 324.64.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 131.84 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
