<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0151</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market chalked up a broad gain today,
recouping Wednesday's losses with a boost from declining interest
rates.
   A steady showing by the dollar against leading foreign currencies
helped push bond prices higher in the credit markets.
   Late in the afternoon prices of long-term government bonds, which
move in the opposite direction from interest rates, showed gains of
more than $5 for each $1,000 in face value.
   That, in turn, seemed to encourage steady buying in the stock
market.
   Analysts said the worries about increasing inflation and Federal
Reserve credit tightening that swept through the markets last week
apparently were easing.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, said he expects the increase
in the consumer price index for February to be smaller than the 0.6
percent gain reported for January.
