<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     03-02 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.63 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 455 money market mutual
funds rose $1.63 billion in the latest week to a record $294.06
billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   It was the eighth straight week that the funds assets hit an
all-time high and reflected the growing attraction of money market
investments because of rising interest rates.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 224 general purpose funds rose $2.39 billion to $95.19
billion, assets of 93 broker-dealer funds rose $938.6 million to
$126.14 billion, and assets of 138 institutional funds declined
$1.70 billion to $72.73 billion.
   ``Virtually all short-term rates rose sharply in the last week of
February. This increase caused a further substantial widening of the
yield spread favoring money market funds over competing investment
vehicles,'' said Jacob Dreyer, the institute's chief economist.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.65 percent from 8.52 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.49 percent from 8.43 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 31
days, unchanged from the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.42 percent as of Wednesday from 6.36 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, were unchanged at 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.76
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.57 percent
the previous week. Yields were 8.93 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
8.80 percent; 8.96 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.85 percent; and
8.99 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.90 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
