<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-02 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Head Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures headed higher Thursday, paced by
rising prices for crude oil and wholesale home heating oil.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled 44 cents
higher at $18.72 a barrel, adding to Wednesday's gain of 13 cents.
Contracts for more distant months posted slightly smaller increases.
   Heating oil for April delivery settled at 51.87 cents a gallon,
up 1.38 cents from Wednesday's settlement.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
April unleaded gasoline, which fell 0.01 cent on Wednesday, rose to
52.21 cents a gallon from 51.56.
   Chris Gohler, in the energy group of Elders Futures Inc., said a
combination of fundamental and technical factors pushed up crude
prices.
   Reports circulating in the markets that certain oil-exporting
countries will cut back crude production by about 400,000 barrels a
day boosted oil buying in the futures market.
   The exporters mentioned _ which were not members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries _ included the Soviet
Union and China, Gohler said.
   The buying built momentum as trading progressed and the April
crude contract ended the day at its highest levels of the session.
   Continuing speculation about temporary shortages due to low
inventories of heating oil encouraged buying as it has previously in
recent weeks.
</TEXT>
