<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-02 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened Thursday against most
major currencies in thin trading after turning mixed overseas.
   Gold prices declined. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $383.50 a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EST, down 50 cents
from late Wednesday.
   Traders attributed the dollar's rise largely to technical
factors, although they said the currency got some support from the
West German central bank's decision Thursday to keep interest rates
unchanged.
   European traders said the dollar came under pressure against the
British pound after the Bank of England intervened to support the
weak currency by selling dollars for sterling. The pound had fallen
due to unexpectedly bad figures on Britain's trade performance
during January and persistent doubts about Britain's overall
economic health.
   The pound closed in London at $1.7270, more expensive for buyers
than Wednesday's late $1.7243. Later, in New York, sterling fetched
$1.7125, down from $1.72325.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 128.07 Japanese yen, up from 127.68 yen. The
dollar traded at 127.90 yen in London, and at 128.435 yen in New
York, up from 128.225 yen late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
levels, included: 1.8474 West German marks, up from 1.83675; 1.5824
Swiss francs, up from 1.5690; 1.19485 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19875; 6.2880 French francs, up from 6.2495; and 1,361.33 Italian
lire, up from 1,354.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Wednesday's rates:
1.8405 West German marks, up from 1.8390; 1.5710 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5705; 6.2575 French francs, unchanged; 2.0735 Dutch guilders,
down from 2.0755; 1.1945 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1985; and
1,360.50 Italian lire, up from 1,354.75.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $383.80 a troy ounce, down 50 cents from late
Wednesday.
   Gold closed in London at a bid of $383.75 an ounce, down from
$384.25 Wednesday. The late bid price in Zurich was $383.25 an
ounce, down from $384.10.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $384.35 an ounce, down from
$386.45.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery closed at $5.753 a troy ounce, up from $5.744.
Silver fell in London to $5.76 an ounce from $5.79.
</TEXT>
