<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Netherlands-UPI     03-02 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands-UPI,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Investors Moving To Take Over UPI</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch investment company that is
seeking to take over the conglomerate that controls United Press
International said Thursday it is strongly interested in the
U.S.-based news agency.
   Avacus, a newly formed investment partnership, has so far bought
8 percent of the outstanding shares of the company that controls
UPI, Infotechnology Inc., a New York-based technology and
communications company, said spokesman Joop de Jong.
   ``Avacus is aware of UPI's far-from-ideal track record, but the
fact that the news agency is part of Infotechnology has been an
important consideration in the decision to prepare a bid for the
company,'' De Jong said.
   ``Avacus's principals see opportunities to improve
Infotechnology's performance on the stock exchange, as well as
possibilities to improve the company's management,'' De Jong said in
a telephone interview.
   Avacus's move was heralded in a banner headline Thursday on the
front page of the Dutch national daily, De Volkskrant. No bid for
Infotechnology has yet been made, said De Jong.
   Infotechnology has managed UPI since February 1988, when it took
over the company from Mexican publisher Mario Vasquez Rana, who
relinquished control of his stock for 10 years. Its chairman, Earl
W. Brian, and Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. are the major shareholders.
   Avacus was formed in March 1988 for the sole purpose of acquiring
Infotechnology, according to the documents filed with the SEC. Reiss
&amp; Co., a Dutch investment company, is the majority partner.
   Johannes M.K. Nyks, former president and chief executive of the
American subsidiary of the Netherlands newspaper, VNU, also has an
interest. Nyks, who is based in Washington, left VNU in 1987.
   Nyks, in a letter to Brian dated Feb. 27, said Avacus considers
Infotechnology's stock undervalued and sought a meeting to discuss
``opportunities to increase shareholder value through a mutually
agreeable transaction.''
   Dwight Geduldig, a spokesman for UPI, said Wednesday that Brian
has responded publicly, ``I look forward to meeting with any
shareholder who has suggestions about ways to increase shareholders'
values.''
   In the cable television field, Infotechnology owns The Learning
Channel and Financial News Network, which brings business news to 33
million customers throughout the United States.
   Avacus ``has not yet conceived a fully developed business plan on
how to improve Infotechnology's performance,'' said De Jong. But he
added that there were no plans to curtail UPI's operational
independence.
   UPI reported a $16 million loss for 1988, and announced it was to
lay off 40 employees worldwide. The news agency's 1987 loss amounted
to $25 million. It employs about 1,000 people.
   Reiss and Co., the dominant partner in Avacus, is based in the
central Dutch town of Almere. It is involved in the computer
business, the funding of management buyouts and other investment
activities, De Jong said. It has not been previously involved in the
media world.
   Its majority shareholder is Jan Kuijten, a controversial Dutch
investor who has been named in the press here in connection with
irregularities in share transactions on the Amsterdam stock
exchange. No charges have ever been filed against Kuijten, who was
not available for comment.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
