<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drop in interest rates helped the stock market
stage a broad advance Thursday, recouping Wednesday's losses.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 15.35 on Wednesday,
climbed 22.67 to 2,265.71.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
982 up, 471 down and 506 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 161.98 million
shares, down from 177.21 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 191.87 million shares.
   A steady showing by the dollar against leading foreign currencies
helped push bond prices higher in the credit markets.
   Late in the afternoon prices of long-term government bonds, which
move in the opposite direction from interest rates, showed gains of
more than $5 for each $1,000 in face value.
   That, in turn, seemed to encourage buying in the stock market.
   Analysts said the worries about increasing inflation and Federal
Reserve credit-tightening that swept through the markets last week
apparently were easing.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, said he expects the increase
in the consumer price index for February, which will be announced
later this month, to be smaller than the 0.6 percent gain reported
for January.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Union Carbide, up 1[ at
30|; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up \ at 30\; International
Business Machines, up | at 120{, and Exxon, up | at 44[.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet fell 2] to 50. The Wall Street Journal reported
that the company faces a controversy over sales practices involving
the credit data it compiles.
   Storage Technology led the active list, up ] at 2[. The company
reported fourth-quarter earnings of 10 cents a share, up from 3
cents in the comparable period a year earlier.
   SSMC rose 1[ to 34[. On Wednesday Semi-Tech Electronics (Far
East) raised its bid for SSMC to $34 a share, topping a $33-a-share
offer from Vincent Tan, a Malaysian investor.
   National Education, which was added to Standard &amp; Poor's
500-stock composite index, gained ~ to 25|.
   Minnetonka, the most active issue in the over-the-counter market,
jumped 8 to 21~. The company retained an investment banking firm to
advise it on a possible sale or other transaction.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $25.64 billion, or 0.90
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
1.47 to 163.21.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.34 to 334.82, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 2.84 at 289.95.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market gained
2.73 to 402.53. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 324.95, up 2.77.
</TEXT>
