<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 1719EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     03-02 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Surge On Hint Of New Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A mere hint of Soviet buying interest sent the jittery soybean
futures market into a powerful rally Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade and sparked some of the most active trading so far this
year.
   Corn and oat futures also advanced but wheat futures retreated
following Wednesday's runup on rumors, which were confirmed
Thursday, that the Soviet Union had purchased 485,000 metric tons of
U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   On other markets Thursday, energy futures surged; livestock and
meat advanced; copper futures gained; and precious metals were
narrowly mixed.
   Soybeans settled 11{ cents to 20{ cents higher with the contract
for delivery in March at $7.67{ a bushel; wheat was 2 cents to 3}
cents lower with March at $4.36\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 3}
cents higher with March at $2.75{ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents to 6
cents higher with March at $2.08} a bushel.
   Unconfirmed rumors of Soviet plans to purchase U.S. corn and
possibly some soybean meal touched off the late rally on the Board
of Trade, analysts said.
   The reaction was especially pronounced in the soybean market,
which has become increasingly sensitive to demand factors as soybean
supplies have tightened _ a function of last summer's drought.
   ``In the face of no current supplies and users all being
hand-to-mouth, the market can blow up on you,'' said Cathy Leow, a
grain market analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York. ``Whenever you get a little demand at all, it explodes.''
   Traders said the rally accelerated after the May soybean contract
surpassed $7.75 a bushel, triggering waves of computer-driven
speculative fund buying.
   The supply tightness is expected to ease in mid-April when the
South American soybean harvest begins.
   But U.S. weather concerns may have taken precedence by then as
the market weighs the prospects for a second year of drought.
   ``If the weather is good we'll have trouble going much higher; if
the weather's bad, we'll go a lot higher,'' said Victor Lespinasse,
a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Energy futures rose sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange
following reports that non-OPEC countries, including the Soviet
Union and China, may cut their crude-oil exports by about 400,000
barrels per day in the second quarter.
   The market had been expecting a cutback by those producers of
less than 200,000 barrels per day.
   The cutbacks, which have not been officially announced, would
support the efforts of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to bolster oil prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 20 cents to 44 cents
higher with April at $18.72 a barrel; heating oil was .84 cent to
1.38 cent higher with April at 51.87 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .45 cent to .65 cent higher with April at 52.21 cents a
gallon.
   Cattle futures surged on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange as
continued strong cash prices defied expectations for a decline. Live
cattle fetched as much as $79 per hundredweight in Kansas.
   Pork futures also rose, reflecting light sales to packers at
higher prices.
   Live cattle futures settled .05 cent to 1.08 cents higher with
April at 78.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .50
cent higher with March at 82.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .10
cent lower to .32 cent higher with April at 44.55 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to 1.18 cents higher with March at
39.25 cents a pound.
   Copper futures advanced for the fourth straight day on New York's
Commodity Exchange amid supply fears linked to a planned, 3-day
miners' strike in Peru.
   Gold and silver futures were nearly unchanged.
   Copper settled 1.6 cents to 2.7 cents higher with March at $1.474
a pound; gold was 50 cents to 80 cents lower with April at $386.60 a
troy ounce; silver was unchanged to 0.9 cent higher with March at
$5.753 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
