<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Options 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Options, 1st Ld-Writethru,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Management Confronting Bad Alternatives</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS new 9th graf with Eastern debt; picks up 9th graf pvs bg'ng,
``It's obviously ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Eastern Airlines careens toward what could be
its final conflict, the besieged carrier's managers face bitter
choices like bankruptcy, asset auctions or a takeover at a fire-sale
price.
   The economic impact of those scenarios would be felt deeply in
Florida and across the gamut of 118 cities where Eastern operates in
the United States, the Caribbean and Latin America.
   Eastern employs around 31,200 people, including 10,200 at its
Miami headquarters, 6,700 in Atlanta and 3,200 in New York. In South
Florida alone, the airline spent $541.2 million last year on
salaries and other employee benefits, and $11.1 million on fees at
three airports.
   As a strike deadline against Eastern of 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday
loomed, federal mediators expressed some hope for a settlement of
the contract dispute between the money-losing airline and its
militant Machinists union.
   President Bush still was weighing whether to step in and avert
the impending strike, as the National Mediation Board has
recommended.
   If there is a strike of more than a few days, ``That will be the
end of Eastern as we know it,'' said Louis Marckesano, an airline
analyst at Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
   His warning reflects the assessment of many analysts and other
observers.
   Eastern recently reported a record net loss of $335.4 million in
1988, nearly double its $181.7 million loss the year before. Revenue
dropped to $3.8 billion from $4.4 billion in 1987.
   The airline has a crushing $2.5 billion or so in debt.
   ``It's obviously a situation that's heading fast for the edge of
the cliff ... I see the prospect of bankruptcy as a real potential
outcome here,'' Farrell Kupersmith, a financial consultant to the
Air Line Pilots Association, recently told a gathering of analysts.
   Kupersmith, an associate managing partner of the Touche Ross &amp;
Co. accounting firm, represented creditors of Continental Airlines
after that carrier was put into bankruptcy in September 1983 by
Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo. Texas Air, Lorenzo's
Houston-based holding company, owns Eastern and Continental.
   After the bankruptcy filing, the steely-tough Lorenzo
restructured Continental and slashed the number of employees to
around 4,000 from 12,500.
   Several observers believe an Eastern bankruptcy could follow a
series of events, notably sales of assets such as planes, airport
gates and landing rights. After the assets had been stripped off,
they suggest, Lorenzo could then put the remaining ``shell'' company
under protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy
laws.
   Lorenzo would have a tougher time putting Eastern into Chapter 11
and sacking employees than he did with Continental _ but he could
still do it. As a result of amendments to the bankruptcy laws passed
in 1985, the Texas Air chief would first have to negotiate further
with the Eastern unions and demonstrate that he had no other
alternative.
   ``I don't see bankruptcy as being an immediate possibility,''
said Paul Karos, who follows the industry for First Boston Corp.
``It's a very last resort.''
   Another possible scenario is a takeover by outsiders, something
the Eastern unions have been trying to engineer for some time.
   Takeover strategist Carl Icahn, head of Trans World Airlines
Inc., has been lurking in the wings for months as a potential
acquirer of Eastern and is still there, according to observers and
union sources. Icahn may be hoping to pick up what remains of
Eastern at a fire-sale price, analysts suggest.
   Icahn has said publicly that Eastern, with its domestic routes,
would fit nicely as a feeder into TWA's international network.
   Other investor groups remain interested in Eastern, the sources
say, although neither they nor Icahn has made a formal offer.
   Selling Eastern as an integral unit is Lorenzo's ``ace in the
hole,'' analyst Marckesano said.
</TEXT>
