<FIRST>r f AM-Champion-Cooper     03-02 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Champion-Cooper,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cooper May Have To Increase Offer For Champion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cooper Industries Inc.'s buyout of Champion
Spark Plug Co. may cost more than the $707 million in cash the
Houston-based company is offering because of Wall Street activity,
an auto industry analyst said Thursday.
   Cooper offered on Feb. 6 to buy Champion for $21 a share. The
merger agreement approved by the boards of directors of Cooper and
Champion on Feb 22.
   Since Cooper announced it would buy Champion, Gabelli Group Inc.,
a New York investment company, has reduced its 17.6 percent stake in
Champion to about 14 percent.
   The Gabelli Group sold off 376,650 shares of Champion common
stock at between $22.50 to $23 a share between Feb. 13 and Feb. 24,
according to Securities and Exchange Commission filing on Wednesday.
The group had been managing about 6 million shares of Champion stock
for investors.
   In addition, Champion stock has steadily been trading above $21 a
share on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Cooper may have to increase its $21-a-share offer to buy 50.1
percent of Champion stock, said William Prebe, an auto analyst and
former vice president for Dana Corp., an automotive giant that had
made a bid to buy Champion.
   ``Gabelli could be creating market activity to get the price
up,'' Prebe said. ``Cooper might not be able to get 50 percent of
the shares. And if Cooper cannot get 50 percent, they are going to
have to increase their tender offer.
   ``If he (Gabelli) is selling at $22 a share, someone has got to
be buying. He might be convincing a buyer that the price will even
go higher,'' he said.
   Several telephone messages left Thursday for Mario Gabelli,
manager of the Gabelli Group, were not returned.
   Prebe and other auto industry analysts have said it was unlikely
that another company would make a bid for Champion.
   Under the terms of the deal, Cooper is making a $21-a-share cash
tender offer for all of Champion's 33.6 million shares of
outstanding common stock.
   The deal, including debt reduction, legal fees and other
considerations, brings the total purchase price to about $800
million.
   The tender offer, which began Feb. 24, is scheduled to March 22,
with the merger taking place after May 1. Cooper spokeswoman Ellen
Meyers said the company won't reveal how many shares have been
tendered until after March 22.
   She also declined comment on speculation that the company may
have to increase its tender offer.
   ``I don't think we want to speculate on what the merger will cost
the company or the stock's activity,'' she said.
   Auto analysts say the key to the deal is whether Chinook Partners
L.P. will tender its shares, a move that could lock up the deal for
Cooper.
   Chinook was established in 1986 by the founding Stranahan family
to maintain a dominant voice in Champion's affairs. It controls 35
percent of Champion's common stock.
   ``I think the Chinook group will wait to the last minute before
tendering their shares because they want to get the best price,''
Prebe said.
   Champion is the world's leading manufacturer of spark plugs for
all types of internal combustion engines. It has annual revenue of
about $720 million and employs about 9,200 people worldwide.
   Cooper, with 1988 revenue of $4.3 billion, is a diversified
worldwide, manufacturer of products from the electrical, electronic,
commercial, industrial, compression and drilling markets.
</TEXT>
