<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 0157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-FarmCredit     03-02 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Farm Credit,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Credit System Reports Quarterly, Annual Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Farm Credit System reported Wednesday that
its fourth-quarter net income jumped 51 percent over the previous
year and that it earned a profit for all of 1988.
   The system said it netted $270 million in the three months ended
Dec. 31, compared with earnings of $179 million in the 1987 period.
   For the year, it earned $704 million, vs. a $17 million loss in
the previous year.
   Alan Fass, president and chief executive officer of the Federal
Farm Credit Banks Funding Corp., the financing arm of the farm
credit system, attributed the improvements largely to fewer loan
losses. Also contributing to the positive results were increased net
interest income and a gain on the sales of certain properties, he
said.
   ``Positive trends in the farm economy and the system's own
efforts to reduce non-earning assets, deliver credit more
efficiently and increase net interest income are making a difference
in the bottom line,'' Fass said in a statement.
   Net interest income rose to $216 million from $156 million during
the fourth quarter, and to $787 million from $509 million for the
year.
   The system said that net interest income increased throughout
1988 as a result of higher cash payments on nonaccrual loans and
reinstatements of nonaccrual loans to accrual status.
   When loans are placed on nonaccrual status they are accounted for
only as they come in rather than when they are due.
   Offsetting last year's positive factors, though, were
extraordinary charges of $174 million related to the debt
restructuring of three Farm Credit banks.
   The 1988 net income also included the recognition of $255 million
in losses relating to the Federal Land Bank of Jackson, which was
placed into receivership on May 20.
   The Farm Credit System is a nationwide system of federally
chartered agricultural lending institutions serving the rural
economy and cooperatively owned by their borrowers.
   The system took several steps last year to streamline its
structure following 1987 legislation that included the issuance of
up to $4 billion in government-backed, low-interest loans.
</TEXT>
