<FIRST>r f AM-AutoDealers 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Dealers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Rules Detroit Auto Dealers Broke Anti-Trust Laws</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to note appeal will be filed, pick up in the 3rd
graf: The FTC's ...; INSERTS 3 grafs after the 10th graf: Evidence heard
... to include dealer's comments, picks up 11th graf pvs: Under the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission said Thursday that
Detroit-area auto dealers broke federal antitrust laws by agreeing
among themselves to close showrooms on Saturdays and most weekday
evenings.
   The dealers were ordered to remain open 64 hours each week for a
year. The dealers' association said an appeal would be filed.
   The FTC's action overturned a 1987 decision by a federal
administrative law judge that declared the dealers justified in
limiting hours because they were seeking peace with their unions
rather than higher profits.
   But FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver said the agreement on showroom
hours was improper because it ``was not part of a labor negotiation
process.''
   On the contrary, he wrote in the FTC opinion, the dealers ``admit
that, to the extent the agreement was motivated by labor concerns,
it was designed to prevent collective bargaining.''
   An agreement to limit shopping hours is the same as an agreement
to raise prices, Oliver wrote. ``The evidence indicates that
respondents expected the hours restriction to benefit them by
limiting comparison shopping,'' he wrote.
   The FTC complaint charged that the dealers had conspired to limit
their hours of business since 1960.
   Most car dealers in the Detroit area are open past 6 p.m. only on
Monday and Thursday nights. They are closed on Saturdays, and blue
laws bar Sunday hours.
   Dealerships elsewhere in the nation typically are open on
weekends.
   Evidence heard by the FTC said the Saturday closings were
enforced against recalcitrant dealerships with picket lines,
threats, violence and vandalism, including gunshots through windows
at one dealership.
   Last April, six shotgun blasts peppered the large front windows
of the Key Motor Mall showroom in Warren. Owner Leo Jerome believed
the shots were linked to him keeping his business open on Saturday.
There have been no arrests, despite his offer of a $25,000 reward.
   Jones said Thursday he had mixed feelings about the FTC ruling.
He said he was happy because his position was upheld, but concerned
because the government was telling him how many hours he had to be
open. Normally, his showroom is open 61 hours a week.
   ``Now, by federal mandate, I have to be open another night or
another three hours on Saturday,'' he said. ``Already my people are
stretched out timewise.''
   Under the FTC opinion, which named 53 dealerships, 78
individuals, the Detroit Auto Dealers Association and 16 other
automotive associations, each Detroit-area dealer can set its own
hours as long as the 64-hour-a-week minimum is met.
   The hours of operation must be conspicuously posted at each
dealership.
   Moreover, the Detroit Auto Dealers Association will be required
to place at least four newspaper advertisements a week for at least
four weeks explaining that the FTC order prompted the extended
shopping hours.
   The dealers have 20 days in which to ask the FTC to reconsider
its decision, a rarely used procedure, or within 30 days could
appeal directly to a federal appellate court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
