<DOCNO> AP890302-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Portugal-Economy     03-02 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Portugal-Economy,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Selects Group To Run Petrochemical Giant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Thursday selected a group
headed by Finish firm Neste Oy to run the nationalized Portuguese
petrochemical giant, CNP, and buy government shares in a second
chemical firm.
   Neste Oy, together with two Portuguese firms, Cotesi and Quintas
e Quintas, will sign a 10-year contract to manage the money-losing
state-owned petrochemical company CNP _ Companhia Nacional
Petroquimica.
   As part of the deal, the companies will pay $670 million to buy
the government's 86.8 percent share in the second firm, the
profitable Empresa de Polimeros Sines (EPSI).
   The center-right, Social Democrat government of Prime Minister
Anibal Cavaco Silva linked EPSI and CNP hoping the sale of the
profitable polymer producer would tempt firms into taking on the
management of CNP, a major loss-maker with some $1.5 billion of
debts.
   Thursday's government statement said Neste Oy's was the only bid
that directly included Portuguese firms in the project and offered
the best financial conditions.
   The government statement also revealed steps towards the eventual
privatization of other state-owned firms.
   Telefones de Lisboa e Porto (TLP), a state telecommunications
company, and the oil company, Petrogal, are to be transformed into a
limited companies (Sociedades Anonimas) with majority holdings for
the state.
   Under the terms of Portugal's socialist-inspired constitution,
the government cannot yet sell more than 49 percent of nationalized
industries.
   However they are free to rent out the company, as will be the
case with CNP.
</TEXT>
