<FIRST>r f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     03-02 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock Files Suit Against Polaroid Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. filed suit
Thursday in U.S. District Court in Delaware against Polaroid Corp.'s
plan to buy back $1.1 billion of stock.
   The complaint alleges Polaroid has given its shareholders
misleading information about its future earnings and possible damage
payments arising from patent infringements by Eastman Kodak Co.
   Polaroid denied the allegation. The companies agreed to argue the
case on March 15 before Judge Caleb Wright so that a decision can be
rendered before the buyback offer expires March 20.
   Shamrock, a radio and television concern based in Burbank,
Calif., has made a $45-a-share hostile tender offer, valued at $3.2
billion, for Polaroid. Shamrock is also waging a proxy battle for
control of Polaroid's board of directors at the May 9 annual meeting.
   Polaroid, the instant camera and film company based here, will
significantly strengthen its position in the proxy battle if its
stock buyback plan is upheld by the court.
   Polaroid is offering $50 a share for 16 million shares, or 22
percent of its outstanding common stock.
   Shamrock, controlled by the Roy E. Disney family, asked the court
to enjoin Polaroid from repurchasing any shares.
   In describing its buyback plan, Polaroid projected growth rates
of 12 percent to 16 percent for both sales and profits from 1990 to
1995. It also said it could receive several billion dollars in
damages from Kodak. But it inserted cautionary language telling
stockholders not to rely on those figures.
   Shamrock contends the figures are unduly optimistic and that the
``boilerplate disclaimers'' are not sufficient. It contends Polaroid
is unfairly trying to improve incumbent management's chances of
winning the proxy battle.
   Polaroid, in response, said Shamrock's lawsuit is ``without merit
and is merely another self-serving attempt by Shamrock to further
its objective of acquiring Polaroid at a price the Board has
determined to be inadequate.''
</TEXT>
