<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TVAds Bjt   03-02 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV Ads, Bjt,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racy TV Show Loses Several Major Advertisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two big advertisers have quit buying time on
the racy television comedy ``Married ... With Children'' and others
have spurned selected episodes for fear of offending consumers,
executives said Thursday.
   Some advertising insiders expect such decisions to become more
common as TV entertainment shows carry more raunchy humor and
profanity and so-called tabloid TV programs delve into kinky sex,
devil worship and similarly salacious subjects.
   Others say controversy over content is as old as television, and
that recent advertiser defections from ``Married ... With Children''
are no more likely to have a lasting effect than did controversy
over ``All in the Family'' a decade ago.
   Some defectors from ``Married,'' which is the fledgling Fox
Broadcasting Co.'s top-rated show, were influenced by an energetic
letter-writing campaign by a Detroit-area mother, Terry Rakolta,
spokesmen said.
   The show, a situation comedy about a blue-collar family named
Bundy, includes references to sex and bathroom humor, and frequently
portrays the husband berating his wife.
   Two advertisers, Procter &amp; Gamble Co. and American Home Products
Corp., bought some ads on the show but have decided against further
sponsorship, spokesmen said Thursday. Johnson &amp; Johnson and
McDonald's Corp. officials said they decided against running
national advertising on the show, though individual, locally
purchased ads had run.
   Coca-Cola USA, whose president, Ira Herbert, wrote an apology to
Mrs. Rakolta, continues to screen ``Married'' episodes for content,
but hasn't found one suitable for advertising since her complaint
Jan. 15, said spokesman Tony Tortorici.
   Advertisers' concerns were summed up by Procter &amp; Gamble
spokeswoman Kelly Gillespie: ``We felt that the whole theme of the
show is basically one we do not want to be associated with. We were
concerned about the negative portrayal of American family life.''
   Fox, which purposefully appeals to the young adult audiences
sought by advertisers in its effort to build a fourth television
network, hasn't had any trouble selling ads on the show, which airs
Sunday evenings, said spokesman Brad Turell.
   ``The show is completely sold out,'' he said, adding that news
reports of Mrs. Rakolta's campaign prompted calls of support from
viewers.
   ``We have received literally hundreds of telephone calls today
from across the country from viewers saying that this one woman's
opinion is getting too much attention and hoping that we won't
change the show,'' Turell said.
   Procter &amp; Gamble, which makes hundreds of household products and
is the nation's second-largest advertiser, bought ads on several
``Married'' episodes last year, stopped from October through
December and then sponsored two shows in January, Ms. Gillespie
said. After receiving Mrs. Rakolta's letter, officials reviewed the
show and decided against further ads, she said.
   American Home Products, which makes goods as diverse as Jiffy Pop
and Woolite, had already decided to disassociate itself from the
show before receiving Mrs. Rakolta's letter, said spokeswoman Carol
Emerling in New York.
   Tambrands Inc., which produces feminine hygiene products such as
Tampax tampons, planned to advertise on two ``Married'' episodes but
canceled the second after a review prompted by Mrs. Rakolta's
letters, said Paul Konney, a spokesman at the company's New York
headquarters.
   Advertisers face a dilemma in deciding whether to sponsor racy
shows, which often attract big audiences but may offend some vocal
consumers.
   ``Tabloid TV'' shows such as ``Geraldo'' and Fox's ``A Current
Affair'' have difficulty attracting advertisers because of what many
see as their exploitation of the weaker side of humanity.
   A recent survey of advertisers and ad buyers found resistance to
such shows, topped by the often outrageous ``The Morton Downey Jr.''
talk show, said Dean McCarthy, vice president of Harrington, Righter
&amp; Parsons, a New York firm that helps television stations sell air
time.
   Virtually all big companies have guidelines for what kind of
shows are acceptable for their ads, and most hire screening
companies to check shows in advance for problems.
   As television presses the outer limits of conventional taste _
sparked in part by looser federal regulations and increased
competition among the various media for ads _ finding an appropriate
spot for an ad can get difficult, said McDonald's spokeswoman
Stephanie Skurdy.
   ``Ours is a children's and family business,'' Ms. Skurdy said
from the company's Oak Brook, Ill., headquarters. ``It has become
increasingly difficult to find family programming on prime-time
television.''
   ``I think the amount of sexuality portrayed on television today
is increasing dramatically,'' said Hal Katz, executive vice
president of Vitt Media International Inc., a New York ad buyer.
``As it increases, advertisers become more sensitive to it.''
   But Paul Isaacson, vice president of Young &amp; Rubicam, a New York
advertising agency, said complaints about shows' content don't
appear any more frequent now than they ever have.
   Those who seek to influence television content through pressure
on advertisers are attempting censorship, said Carol Sobel, an
American Civil Liberties Union attorney who has dealt with free
speech issues.
   ``If you don't want to watch it then don't watch it,'' Ms. Sobel
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
