<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CarIncentives     03-02 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Car Incentives,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Vice Chair: March A Test For Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The automobile industry and its reliance on
incentives is being tested this month, as car and truck sales
nationwide show signs of softening compared with last year, Chrysler
Corp.'s vice chairman said Thursday.
   Gerald Greenwald said incentives, which have become entrenched in
automobile selling during the last few years, aren't as common as
they were last year.
   Meantime, ``we've seen some slackening of traffic in dealerships
throughout the country,'' he said.
   Some people speculate that normal winter patterns are causing the
downturn in sales, ``but we're about to be put to a test.''
   ``Here we are in the month of March that is usually a very strong
selling month,'' he said at a news conference.
   February sales figures are due out Friday. Through Feb. 20, sales
of cars and trucks had fallen 3.2 percent compared with last year
when, as Greenwald said, ``blockbuster incentives'' were in effect.
   ``If the overall question is do I expect to see incentives
continuing, yeah, I do,'' he told reporters.
   Greenwald's comments came before he addressed a banquet at the
annual meeting of the Society of Automotive Engineers.
   Separately, Ford Motor Co. said Thursday it had extended for two
months a sales incentive program scheduled to expire Thursday and
will add to it, including a rebate of up to $4,000 on the imported
Merkur XR4Ti.
   The nation's No. 2 automaker offered cash-back incentives through
May 2 ranging from $400 to $4,000 for the XR4Ti, which carries a
base price of $19,929. The highest rebate, boosted from $3,000,
equals more than 20 percent of the German car's price.
   The company also extended low-financing offers ranging from 4.9
percent interest for two-year loans to 9.9 percent for five-year
loans on various models. Buyers of some of the models covered in the
offers had the option of taking cash incentives or the low financing
program.
   Also Thursday, Chrysler Corp. said it raised its stock dividend
from 25 cents to 30 cents a share, following the leads of General
Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
   The 20 percent dividend increase is the first for Chrysler since
April 1987, the company said.
   The dividend is payable April 17 to shareholders of record on
March 15. At the end of 1988, there were about 233 million shares of
Chrysler common stock outstanding, the nation's No. 3 automaker said.
   On Feb. 7, GM said it was boosting its dividend to $1.50 from
$1.25 and splitting its common stock 2-for-1. Ford boosted its
dividend Jan. 12 to 75 cents a share from 60 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
